<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Litton To Buy Rival Shipbuilder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Litton Industries Inc. will buy Avondale  
Industries for $529 million after Newport News Shipbuilding 
declined to raise its offer for the shipbuilder. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton also indicated Thursday it plans to re-examine its offer  
to buy Newport News in light of potential government opposition. 
</P>
<P>
	New Orleans-based Avondale had agreed earlier to merge with  
Newport News for $470 million in stock. But Litton offered more in 
cash, ultimately enticing Avondale. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale had given Newport News until Thursday to improve its  
bid, but the Virginia-based company decided against such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thoroughly reviewed the issues and determined that it was  
not in the best business interests of our shareholders to raise our 
offer for Avondale,'' said William P. Fricks, the chairman of 
Newport News. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Litton rose on the news, increasing $2.12 1/2 to close at  
$69.06 1/4 on the New York Stock Exchange. Shares of Newport News were 
down 62 1/2 cents to $28.25 on the Big Board, while shares of Avondale 
fell 12 1/2 cents to $38.18 3/4 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Newport News-Avondale combination was apparently doomed last  
Friday when Defense Secretary William Cohen said the Pentagon would 
probably tell the Justice Department to reject the Woodland Hills, 
Calif.-based Litton's $1.3 billion bid for Newport News for 
anti-competitive reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Cohen said the Navy had determined it would  
not oppose Litton's offer for Avondale. 
</P>
<P>
	The Litton-Newport News deal would have reduced the number of  
companies competing to build most classes of Navy warships from 
three to two. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton said Thursday it hasn't given up on acquiring Newport  
News, even with the statements by Cohen. The company did not 
elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton, which owns Ingalls Shipbuilding in Pascagoula, Miss.,  
made its bids for Avondale and Newport News earlier in May after 
Cohen rejected an attempt by General Dynamics Corp. to acquire 
Newport News. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton had originally bid $38 a share, or about $500 million for  
Avondale, but later sweetened its offer to $39.50 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Kitchen, Avondale's chief financial officer, said no layoffs  
were planned and the company was optimistic that more jobs could 
result from the merger. The two companies expect it will take about 
90 days to finish the merger, which must be approved by the federal 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking about evaluating the resources and capacity of  
both Ingalls and Avondale and putting them together in a way to 
expand in both locations,'' Kitchen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingalls employs about 11,000 workers, while Avondale has about  
6,000. The combined Litton-Avondale company would employ 40,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale, a non-union yard, has been engaged in a six-year fight  
to avoid having to recognize the Metal Trades Council of the 
AFL-CIO. The company, which is challenging a union representation 
vote held in 1993, has taken the case to a federal appeals court. A 
decision is pending. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anybody buying Avondale would be an improvement potential for  
the workers,'' said Jim Evans, a union organizer. ``But we're just 
in a wait-and-see position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At Ingalls, two unions on strike were scheduled to vote Thursday  
and Friday on contract offers. If the contracts are approved, 
workers will return to work Monday after three weeks off the job. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
