<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Moves Closer to N.Y. Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *RON FOURNIER   	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton will form an  
exploratory committee in early July preparing her for a potential 
Senate campaign in New York, a top adviser said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Harold Ickes, who is heading up Mrs. Clinton's political  
operation, disclosed the first lady's plans after it was reported 
that Rep. Nita Lowey had decided to seek re-election. Lowey's move 
leaves the Democratic field clear for Mrs. Clinton to run for the 
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nita called the first lady, told the first lady that it was  
clear to her that the first lady was going to run for the Senate 
and that therefore Nita was going to run for the House,'' Lowey 
spokesman Howard Wolfson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton described the call in a statement: ``Today Nita  
Lowey called me to say that she would be running for re-election to 
the House. I thank Nita for her support and I look forward to 
working with her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ickes, a former deputy White House chief of staff, said Mrs.  
Clinton listened to Lowey but did not go into detail about her own 
political plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you can discern (from the conversation) that Hillary  
is going to press forward and she will be forming an exploratory 
committee in early July and just keep moving forward,'' Ickes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Ickes said he meant to say that Mrs. Clinton intends to  
form a committee in July. 
</P>
<P>
	He said forming the committee does not necessarily mean Mrs.  
Clinton will seek the seat. ``This is one step at a time,'' Ickes 
said. ``The initial step forward is to form the exploratory 
committee and continue to talk to the people of New York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Advisers have said for days that Mrs. Clinton intended to form  
the committee, but Ickes was the first to say it on the record. 
Advisers say it would require a major change of heart for Mrs. 
Clinton to not launch a campaign after deciding to form the 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowey had earlier said she would not run for the Senate seat if  
Mrs. Clinton did so. 
</P>
<P>
	Her call to Mrs. Clinton came one day after the first lady was  
in New York City, looking like a candidate and sounding like a 
candidate as she shook hands, hugged strangers and made a rousing 
speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``Run, Hillary, run!'' students chanted at City College, where  
Mrs. Clinton began her day-long visit to Manhattan on Wednesday by 
giving the commencement address. 
</P>
<P>
	The content of Mrs. Clinton's speech to the college -- calling  
for more resources and support for public schools -- was similar to 
others she has made in a half-dozen recent appearances in New York. 
But this time her every sentence was met with a roar from the 
students, most of them black, Hispanic and from working-class 
backgrounds. And like a candidate on the campaign trail, Mrs. 
Clinton's cadences grew stronger with every cheer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can never lift up our public schools and the students they  
serve by tearing them down,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``We can never 
ensure the future of this city or state or our nation by 
undermining the public education system that is at the very 
foundation of the American dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York City's public schools have been criticized frequently  
by Republican Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who is also a likely Senate 
candidate. And City University, of which City College is part, has 
also been under attack, accused of lowering standards. 
</P>
<P>
	At an evening fund-raiser for Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., the  
congresswoman defended Mrs. Clinton against accusations of 
carpetbagging. The first lady has never lived in New York, and 
earlier Wednesday, Republican Gov. George Pataki had said, ``I 
don't think we need somebody from Washington or Arkansas moving to 
New York to represent us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We New Yorkers don't care where you're from,'' Ms. Maloney  
said. ``We New Yorkers care about what you can do to continue to 
build the greatest city, state and country in the world.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
