<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 08:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. To Sell Confidential Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- California will begin selling confidential  
wage data it collects on 14 million people statewide to private 
information companies, car dealers and creditors wanting to check 
an individual's annual income. 
</P>
<P>
	A law that passed last summer allows the state's Employment  
Development Department to disclose the salary information. 
Previously, the data was available only to other government 
agencies. The program, which could bring the state $15 million over 
the next decade, could start later this year or in early 2000, the 
Los Angeles Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	No data would be shared without the written permission of the  
individual, state officials said. However, private companies that 
are deemed qualified to access the data would operate on an honor 
system and would not be required to show proof of each individual's 
written permission before accessing the information. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters, including banks and lenders who championed the  
legislation, contend the data will allow them to process loan 
applications faster and cut back on fraud. But consumer groups say 
the electronic disclosure of someone's salary could fall into the 
wrong hands -- including debt collectors or marketing firms wanting 
to woo wealthy customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``This violates a basic principle of privacy,'' said Robert  
Ellis Smith, publisher of Privacy Journal, a monthly newsletter 
covering technology's effect on personal privacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said the state wage data was originally collected to  
figure out unemployment taxes and benefits, not to help aid 
creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials said the information would be given only to  
qualified creditors, primarily mortgage lenders. The department's 
salary information dates back about four years and covers about 85 
percent of all California residents. Federal employees and the 
self-employed are not included. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key issue is how do we implement this program while giving  
a priority to privacy rights,'' said Michael Bernick, the director 
of the Employment Development Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Diego County-based Verification of Income and  
Employment, a joint venture between Santa Ana-based First American 
Financial Corp. and Norwest Mortgage, is helping start the program. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which worked with the state Legislature for three  
years to get the law passed, also runs programs in Iowa, Minnesota, 
North Carolina, Pennsylvania and Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials said qualifying private companies must promise  
to use the wage information only as part of a credit application 
and to obtain the borrower's permission in advance. Users would 
then get access to an online database after paying a $5 to $10 fee 
per request. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it conducts random audits and hires and  
accounting firm to make sure there is written permission. To keep 
the system from being abused, users also can only request one to 
five names at a time and can't download the information to their 
personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the U.S. Supreme Court agreed to decide whether  
states can sell personal information from driver's license records 
such as people's addresses and Social Security numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	States have routinely sold such information to businesses,  
charities and political candidates, earning millions of dollars in 
revenue each year. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
