<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- Panama expects to earn $30 million  
from operation of the Panama Canal during its first year of local 
control. 
</P>
<P>
	The government will receive the sum from the new Panama Canal  
authority and use it for social projects, says the 2000 budget 
approved Wednesday by Panama's Legislative Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	The canal authority, which has a $605 million budget, replaces  
the U.S.-led Panama Canal Commission on Dec. 31, 1999 in accordance 
with a 1979 U.S.-Panama treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	The assembly set aside $489.5 million for administration of the  
85-year-old canal and another $100 million for infrastructure 
improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	The canal generated $546 million in tolls in fiscal year 1998.  
An average of 33 to 35 ships cross the Atlantic-Pacific link each 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The chairman of Mexico's ruling party  
admitted Thursday that a fugitive banker contributed to the party's 
election coffers several years ago but said the donations broke no 
laws at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Antonio Gonzalez Fernandez, of the Institutional  
Revolutionary Party, said Carlos Cabal Peniche contributed about 
$285,000 to President Ernesto Zedillo's 1994 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	He told reporters that the bulk of the contributions were made  
before Mexico reformed its election laws in September 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition lawmakers have asked Congress to appoint a special  
prosecutor to investigate the contributions to the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Cabal Peniche, wanted in Mexico for an alleged $700 million  
fraud against two banks he owned, said last week that he donated 
$25 million to the party. He said some $5 million went to Zedillo's 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	He was arrested in Australia last November and faces an  
extradition hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A jockey died after being trampled  
in a horse race in southeast Brazil, officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodrigo Antunes, 16, died late Wednesday following the accident  
at a racetrack in Porto Alegre, said Regina Becker, spokeswoman for 
the race organizers. The city is 960 miles southwest of Rio. 
</P>
<P>
	Antunes, a professional jockey for six months, was thrown off  
his horse on the final bend, she said. One of about ten horses 
behind him appeared to stamp on his chest. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- Public bus drivers in El  
Salvador went on strike Thursday to protest the government's demand 
that they pay traffic ticket fines totaling $28 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Army trucks offered free rides to thousands of people who were  
left with only partial bus service at best during the one-day 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Genaro Ramirez, head of public transportation alliance, Alianza  
Intergremial del Transporte, which organized the strike, said 
drivers could not afford to pay the fines. 
</P>
<P>
	The fines were incurred over the past several years by at least  
7,000 bus drivers. 
  	   	
</P>
