<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Accepts Peace Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav President Slobodan  
Milosevic, giving in to Western demands, today accepted a peace 
plan for Kosovo. The deal is designed to end mass expulsions of 
ethnic Albanians by Serb forces and 11 weeks of NATO airstrikes. 
But President Clinton and U.S. officials reacted cautiously, 
waiting for signs that Milosevic would begin pulling his troops out 
of Kosovo and allow the return of more than 855,000 refugees forced 
out of the province. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Welcomes Kosovo Agreement  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today airstrikes in  
Kosovo would continue until Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic produced 
``real results.'' Clinton welcomed Yugoslavia's acceptance of 
NATO's peace terms for Kosovo as encouraging news, but he said NATO 
must have clear proof that Milosevic fully accepts all conditions 
for peace and intends to implement them completely -- as he pledged 
to Russian mediator Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish President 
Martti Ahtisaari. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Moves Closer to N.Y. Run  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton intends to form an  
exploratory committee in early July, preparing her for a potential 
Senate campaign in New York next year, a top adviser said today. 
She would be the first sitting first lady to run for public office. 
Harold Ickes, who is heading up Mrs. Clinton's political operation, 
disclosed the plans after Rep. Nita Lowey said, in a telephone call 
to the first lady, that she would seek re-election to the House. 
That move leaves the Democratic Senate field clear for Mrs. 
Clinton. 

</P>
<P>
	NTSB Says Doomed Jet Was Briefed  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The pilot of the American Airlines jet  
that crashed in a thunderstorm was getting the ``play-by-play'' on 
the deteriorating weather as he brought the plane in for a landing, 
a federal investigator said today. Investigators are analyzing the 
conversation between the tower and the pilot, information from the 
plane's flight data recorder and evidence from the wreckage to try 
to determine why Flight 1420 skidded off the runway at the Little 
Rock airport, killing nine people, including the pilot. 

</P>
<P>
	Europe Will Forge Security, Defense  
</P>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- Hoping to lessen their reliance on U.S.  
military power, European Union leaders approved a blueprint today 
for achieving a stronger collective defense by the end of next 
year. A declaration issued on the opening day of a two-day summit 
said the EU must be able to respond to crises without having to 
rely on U.S.-provided hardware, communications and intelligence. 
The EU wants to take on a greater role in crisis prevention and 
peacekeeping around Europe. 

</P>
<P>
	Florida Girl Wins Spelling Bee  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nupur Lala, a 14-year-old Tampa, Fla., girl  
who never met a word she would not look up, correctly spelled 
``logorrhea'' today to win the 72nd annual Scripps Howard National 
Spelling Bee. ``I would read different books and whenever I found a 
word I didn't know, I would write it down and look it up later,'' 
Nupur said as she clutched her gold trophy cup after a victory 
leap. Nupur beat out 248 other spellers, ages 9 to 15, to win 
$10,000, encyclopedias, two airline tickets and computer software. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 85.80  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks closed higher today as strong  
sales at the nation's largest retailers reminded investors that 
economic growth isn't always bad news. The Dow industrials ended at 
10,663.69, up 85.80. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,597-1,316. 
Market indexes held steady after the New York Stock Exchange 
announced it will not adopt extended trading hours until at least 
2000. The Nasdaq was at 2,403.73, down 28.68. 

</P>
<P>
	Hingis, Graf in French Open Final  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Steffi Graf surprised even herself today,  
outlasting Monica Seles to make it back to the French Open final 
for the first time in three years. She will face 18-year-old 
Martina Hingis, who is seeking the only Grand Slam title she has 
yet to win. Hingis beat another veteran, defending champion Arantxa 
Sanchez-Vicario 6-3, 6-2 to reach Saturday's final. Graf, a 
five-time French Open champion, rallied after a strong first set by 
Seles to win 6-7 (2-7), 6-3, 6-4. 

</P>
<P>
	Sosa Homers in Cubs Win  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sammy Sosa homered for the second straight day  
and took over the National League lead with 19, leading the Chicago 
Cubs over the San Diego Padres 7-2 today. Sosa, who hit a major 
league record 20 home runs during June in 1998, has two this month, 
He has 15 home runs and 31 RBIs in his last 27 games. Henry 
Rodriguez hit a three-run homer, his 11th of the season, in a 
six-run second inning, helping the Cubs win for the sixth time in 
seven games. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  

  	   	
</P>
