<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	More stormy weather soaked the Plains today, with hail in the  
north, thunder in the south and high winds in between. The West had 
rain, too, and unseasonably cool weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Severe weather was hitting the northern Plains this morning  
ahead of a warm front stretching from Montana to the Dakotas. Hail 
struck parts of South Dakota and Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	In the central Plains, storms were expected to be severe  
particularly in Kansas, with winds up to 60 mph and small hail. In 
the southern Plains, storms concentrated in the Texas panhandle and 
central Oklahoma were expected to move east through the morning. 
</P>
<P>
	A cold front from the northern Rockies to southern California  
was pushing temperatures in the West to below-normal levels. 
</P>
<P>
	A low-pressure center in Montana was bringing clouds to the  
Pacific Northwest, and an upper level low was bringing ocean 
moisture and partly cloudy skies to the desert Southwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine-tenths of an inch of rain were reported Wednesday in  
Flagstaff, Ariz., the greatest 24-hour amount recorded for the date 
in 100 years. Record rainfall was also reported in Los Angeles, 
Long Beach and Pasadena, Calif., in what is supposed to be the dry 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Light rain in the Northeast this morning was expected to  
continue thanks to a stationary front. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers in the Ohio and Tennessee river valleys, caused by a  
cold front from Kentucky to New York state, were expected to 
slacken and move east into the mid-Atlantic states. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers in Georgia were also expected to shift east as the  
morning progressed, as was rain near Miami, leaving the Southeast 
with a typically muggy, partly cloudy June day. Afternoon 
thunderstorms were possible today on the Gulf Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms hit parts of the Southeast hard Wednesday, bringing wind  
gusts up to 87 mph in Little Rock, Ark., and close to 4 inches of 
rain in Tuscaloosa, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast mainly in the 50s and 60s over most of  
the West; the 70s from the northern Plains to the inland Northeast; 
the 90s from the extreme southwestern desert across the southern 
Plains to the Southeast; and the 80s elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures Wednesday ranged from 99 in Carlsbad, N.M., to 29  
in Leadville, Colo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
