<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Questions Judge's Use of Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- A judge who fought to preserve a display  
of the Ten Commandments in his courtroom may have violated ethics 
laws in using a fund set up to finance the court battle, a state 
panel found. 
</P>
<P>
	The Alabama Ethics Commission voted 5-0 Wednesday to send the  
case of Etowah County Circuit Judge Roy Moore to prosecutors for 
possible criminal action. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore said he had no improper dealings with the fund, created  
during a highly publicized fight over his courtroom prayers and Ten 
Commandments display. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethics Commission Director Jim Sumner said the panel believes  
Moore spent money on things other than his legal expenses and used 
the ``mantle of his office'' to help raise the funds. Sumner would 
not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	The state attorney general's office is not required to take any  
action on the referral. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an attempt to stop the message about God,'' Moore said of  
the ruling. ``It's no great surprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A religious-freedom lawsuit filed by state officials who  
supported Moore eventually reached the Alabama Supreme Court last 
year. By dismissing the suit on technical grounds, the court 
effectively allowed his religious activities to continue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
