<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 08:00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boys Charged in School Phone Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORT HURON, Mich. (AP) -- Two teen-agers have been charged with  
phoning in threats to public schools in cases unconnected to the 
murder-conspiracy case against four other teens in this city, 
police said today. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, a 15-year-old Port Huron South High School student  
called 911 and threatened ``a bloodbath'' at the city's high 
schools, police Capt. Brian Moeller said. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy first called 911 about 5 a.m., then called again about  
20 minutes later, Moeller said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he would shoot as many students as possible,'' Moeller  
said. Police traced the call to a pay phone and arrested the boy 
while he was still on the line with 911. 
</P>
<P>
	The 15-year-old was arraigned Wednesday in juvenile court on a  
charge of making a false threat to 911. Had he been charged as an 
adult, he would face a felony punishable by up to four years in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Acting on tips, police also arrested a 14-year-old eighth-grader  
on Wednesday in a May 10 telephone bomb threat at Holland Woods 
Middle School, Moeller said. The boy, who allegedly left the threat 
on the school's answering machine, was to be arraigned in family 
court this afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The bomb threat came two days before police discovered what they  
say was a plot by four Holland Woods students to steal guns and 
massacre students and teachers at the school. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen-year-olds Justin Schnepp and Jedaiah ``David'' Zinzo  
and 13-year-olds Daniel Fick and Jonathan McDonald are charged with 
conspiracy to commit premeditated murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say they foiled the plot after classmates reported  
it to school officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Moeller said there is no connection between the latest arrests  
and the murder-conspiracy case in this city of 34,000, about 60 
miles northeast of Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	The May 10 phone threat led to a Holland Woods parent meeting  
May 12, during which a pipe bomb was left outside the school. That 
bomb, as well as the arrests of the four students, led to the 
cancellation of classes May 15. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has been arrested in the planting of the bomb.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 23:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gambling Panel Finalizes Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal panel finalized a report that  
urges a go-slow approach to new casinos and lotteries nationwide 
and an increase to 21 in the minimum betting age. But members of 
the National Gambling Impact Study Commission were deeply split on 
what they believed their proposals could, or should, accomplish. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Richard Leone, the driving force behind the  
commission's most controversial ideas to limit or scale back 
gambling, said he believed the report would spur action by 
governments and civic organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We put four or five big issues on the table,'' Leone said as  
the commission wrapped up two years' work Thursday. ``We got the 
point across that we've come very far, very fast (on gambling 
expansion) without thinking about what we're doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leone proposed language encouraging a moratorium on further  
expansion of gambling, a call for states to require ``gambling 
impact statements'' before approving new gambling and restrictions 
on political contributions by the gambling industry in state and 
local campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner William Bible, former chairman of the Nevada Gaming  
Control Board, said he believed suggestions like the moratorium and 
limits on campaign contributions would be ``discounted, blown off 
by the states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he noted that all nine members of the commission found  
common ground on problem gambling and will issue a strong appeal 
for more research, education and treatment. That, he said, ``will 
probably be the legacy of this commission.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Concluding two days of meetings here, the nine commission  
members voted unanimously to adopt a report nearly 300 pages long. 
It contained more than 70 recommendations, including calls for an 
increase to 21 in the minimum betting age, more help for addicted 
gamblers and a curb on political contributions by the gambling 
industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The report will be presented to Congress, the White House, state  
governors and Indian tribes. 
</P>
<P>
	Commission members ranged from casino industry figures to James  
Dobson, president of the conservative group Focus on the Family. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress created the commission in 1996 after opponents of the  
industry charged the spread of casinos and other forms of gambling 
was taking a social toll on the nation, including increased 
bankruptcies, suicides and crime. Clinton, along with the leaders 
of the House and Senate, selected the commission members. 
</P>
<P>
	On many key recommendations the panel was divided. It voted 5-4,  
for example, for language urging states to consider a moratorium on 
new expansions of lotteries and casinos. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the commission unanimously called on insurance  
companies and managed-care providers to cover treatment plans for 
pathological gamblers. And in a last-minute additional 
recommendation, the commission unanimously urged states to curtail 
the growth of new lottery games, reduce lottery advertising and 
limit locations of lottery machines. 
</P>
<P>
	The commissioners joked about their wide ideological  
differences, which sometimes rendered consensus elusive and turned 
their meetings testy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We agreed on more than I ever imagined,'' said Leone, a former  
state treasurer in New Jersey. ``We finished with more respect for 
each other than when we started.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission struggled to the end over Indian reservation  
casinos, which in the past decade have developed into the 
fastest-growing segment of the U.S. gambling boom. 
</P>
<P>
	The only American Indian on the panel, Alaska businessman Robert  
Loescher, said the draft report overstated the potential spread of 
Indian casinos and understated gambling's unique ability to help 
tribes make money. 
</P>
<P>
	Loescher did press successfully to add a sentence declaring that  
the commission found no evidence ``suggesting any viable approach 
to economic development across the broad spectrum of Indian 
country, in the absence of gaming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the gambling industry, fearing the commission  
would become a runaway jury, worked to weaken its subpoena power in 
1996. Yet in the end, the commission never issued any subpoenas. 
Nor did the commission's anti-gambling members advocate an outright 
ban of gambling or a crippling federal tax on its proceeds. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner John Wilhelm, national president of the Hotel  
Employees and Restaurant Employees Union, said that despite ``some 
misguided, inaccurate or unrealistic'' elements, the report is good 
news for casino employees because it does not call for new federal 
taxes or regulation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
