<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers Study Knicks Without Ewing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- They may be just trying a little reverse  
psychology, but the Indiana Pacers say the loss of Patrick Ewing 
makes the New York Knicks a quicker, more dangerous team. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes our job a little more difficult. First, because of  
the simple fact they've been playing so much without him,'' said 
Reggie Miller, who made a snide remark to the New York center after 
Ewing missed a 15-footer at the buzzer in Game 2 Tuesday that would 
have sent the game into overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as you make the last shot, that's all that matters,''  
Miller said. ``Right, Pat?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller had hit two free throws with two seconds to play in the  
game, giving the Pacers a split of the first two games. Game 3 is 
Saturday in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing will watch the rest of the playoffs in a suit and a cast  
on his left foot. He learned Wednesday that he has a partial tear 
of his left Achilles' tendon. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller was more contrite on Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's very unfortunate. Looking at the game, I knew he was  
hobbling a little bit. But, looking at all the other playoff series 
I thought he was going to play through the pain,'' Miller said. 
``It's unfortunate he isn't there, but I think that makes them a 
more dangerous team. A wounded animal is more dangerous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller and his teammates believe the absence of the 36-year-old  
Ewing will mean more fast-break attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look for it to be more of a track meet. A lot of time ... he  
would wait at half court to see if they got the fast break and then 
he would run down and get in the post and they would throw it in,'' 
Miller said. ``Now they're going to put on track shoes and really 
try and get out and run, get as many easy baskets as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rik Smits, who is likely to be defended by Chris Dudley with  
Ewing gone, anticipates his task will be more challenging 
offensively and on the boards. 
</P>
<P>
	``He works his butt off on defense. He's tough down there. He's  
a guy that doesn't let anything come easy,'' Smits said of Dudley. 
``Dudley is a great rebounder. He's a guy who really works hard to 
get into position, beat his man off the board. It's going to be 
tough. I don't see things getting any easier for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smits felt compassion for Ewing, who he has battled for much of  
his career -- including five playoff series in seven years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I respect him as a fellow athlete, putting in this many years.  
He's got a lot of miles on him, a lot of hours. He's been trying to 
get that first championship,'' Smits said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt real bad for him, to play this far with this much pain  
and this much discomfort and now you've got to sit down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forward Dale Davis thought the loss of Ewing gave the Knicks a  
chance to show their character. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely going to be big,'' Davis said of Ewing's  
absence. '' Even though he was banged up he was in there giving 110 
percent. He's their leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can look at it one of two ways, either they're going to  
respond to him or it is going to hurt them badly. Knowing the 
character of that team, I think they'll respond positively,'' Davis 
said. ``I look for them to push the ball more. They're going to be 
home, so I look for them to be more of an up-tempo team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look at the things that he was doing when he was on  
the floor, while he was hurting, he still was rebounding,'' Antonio 
Davis said of Ewing. ``He still was trying his best to control the 
middle. I think if we're able to get guys in there attempting to 
rebound. Maybe that will be one stat that we'll have in our favor. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point we need something in our favor in order to be  
successful.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
