<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Cautious on Belgrade Peace Move  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration reacted cautiously  
today to Yugoslavia's reported acceptance of a peace plan for 
Kosovo and said there is no immediate plan to halt the bombing 
campaign. ``It's a hopeful sign, but we need to see more'' details, 
said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon. Officials said they want to 
hear directly from Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who is 
representing the European Union in talks with Slobodan Milosevic's 
government. The plan involves the withdrawal of Serb forces from 
Kosovo and the deployment of an international force to supervise 
the return of the 850,000 ethnic Albanian refugees to the province. 

</P>
<P>
	China, U.S. Discuss Bombing Probe  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China and the United States have begun talks on  
an investigation into NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in 
Yugoslavia, China's Foreign Ministry said today. Chinese Foreign 
Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao also reiterated that the 
investigation must be thorough and that those responsible for the 
bombing should be punished. China was incensed by the May 7 missile 
attack on its Belgrade embassy that killed three reporters. NATO 
said the missile attack was an accident. 

</P>
<P>
	4 Killed in Las Vegas Store Attack  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- A man armed with a shotgun opened fire today in  
a supermarket, killing four people. The 23-year-old man was 
arrested and taken into custody. Three of the dead were employees 
of the Albertsons supermarket and the fourth was a shopper, Lt. 
Wayne Petersen said. ``We're unsure why he chose this place to go 
on a rampage.'' Police first received word of the shooting around 
5:15 a.m. The supermarket is at a shopping mall at one of the 
city's busiest intersections, about two miles west of the Las Vegas 
strip. 

</P>
<P>
	Factory Orders Drop 1.2 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Orders to American factories for manufactured  
goods fell 1.2 percent in April, reflecting a big drop in demand 
for aircraft and other transportation products. The Commerce 
Department reported today that the decrease in factory orders in 
April followed a 1.9 percent advance in March and was only the 
second decline in the past six months. However, the weakness was 
confined to the volatile transportation sector. Excluding 
transportation, factory orders would have risen by 0.5 percent, 
posting the fifth increase in the past six months. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkish Rights Advocate Imprisoned  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- One of Turkey's leading human rights  
activists began a 10-month prison sentence today, the latest 
conviction under tough laws curbing freedom of expression. Akin 
Birdal, who barely survived an assassination attempt last year, was 
convicted for speeches he gave in 1995 and 1996 supporting Kurdish 
rights and an end to Turkey's war with Kurdish rebels. Escorted to 
an Ankara prison by hundreds of his supporters, Birdal, who leads 
the independent Human Rights Association, vowed to keep up his 
campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	Egypt Reopens Restored Giza Pyramid  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Egypt reopened the biggest of the three  
ancient Giza Pyramids to tourists today following yearlong 
restorations. The restoration of the Great Pyramid, built as a tomb 
for King Cheops about 4,500 years ago, included mending cracks, 
cleaning up graffiti and installing new lighting and ventilation 
systems. To prevent further damage, only 300 visitors will be 
allowed inside the pyramid each day, down from the daily droves of 
5,000 before the restoration. 

</P>
<P>
	Lockheed To Cut 2,000 Ga. Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) -- Lockheed Martin Corp. is cutting up to  
2,000 more jobs at its Marietta plant -- about 20 percent of the 
total -- as part of a continuing effort to reduce costs. The demand 
for the C-130J military transport plane, a major product of the 
plant, is good, Lockheed President Tom Burbage told a news 
conference today. But the job cuts are needed ``to be more 
competitive for the campaigns we have not won yet,'' he said, 
noting that the defense contractor is competing worldwide for 
several contracts. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Rises 72, Nasdaq Drops 3  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow Industrials were  
up 72.82 points at 10,650.71. Advancers on the New York Stock 
Exchange outnumbered decliners 1,545-1,064. The Nasdaq was down 
3.52 at 2,428.89. 

</P>
<P>
