<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Montoya-Franchitti Battle Moves On </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST ALLIS, Wis. (AP) -- Even when he isn't winning, Juan Montoya  
shows off his phenomenal talent. 
</P>
<P>
	The 23-year-old Colombian went into last Saturday's Motorola 300  
in Madison, Ill., with three straight wins -- a rookie record. His 
Target-Chip Ganassi Racing team made an uncharacteristic mistake, 
running the youngster out of fuel before his first pit stop. 
</P>
<P>
	Unfortunately, for them, it not only took precious extra seconds  
to restart the engine, but an untimely caution flag caught Montoya 
on pit road and put him a lap down. 
</P>
<P>
	The youngster was never back in contention, but he still brought  
the crowd at Gateway International Raceway to its feet with some 
spectacular driving as he tried to regain that lost lap. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice, Montoya's Reynard-Honda slid precariously towards the  
concrete wall, and twice he was able to somehow gather it in as the 
crowd gasped and then cheered. It was an amazing show of car 
control. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how he did that,'' said Dario Franchitti, who  
trails Montoya in the CART FedEx Championship Series standings by 
four points (69-65) heading into Sunday's Miller Lite 225 at the 
Milwaukee Mile. ``Once these cars get away from you, usually it's 
just too late to do anything. He's pretty quick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya, who served his apprenticeship in Europe as a road  
racer, has made a fast transition to oval racing, attested to by 
his victories on the ovals in Nazareth, Pa. and Rio de Janeiro, 
Brazil. He also came back to finish 11th at Gateway. 
</P>
<P>
	He has tested on the flat, one-mile over in this Milwaukee  
suburb, but this will be his first race here. 
</P>
<P>
	``Someone asked me if I'm getting sick of the ovals,'' Montoya  
said. ``No way. We're doing pretty good on them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Races like we had in Madison are very rough on me, but we did  
have success at Nazareth, so I'm ready for Milwaukee. Of course I'm 
looking forward to street courses, but I'm still learning a lot and 
I actually enjoy the ovals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's not great news for Scotsman Franchitti, who has made also  
made a good transition from European road courses to the less 
familiar American ovals. He has yet to win on an oval, but 
Franchitti did finish fourth -- behind Moytona's teammate Jimmy 
Vasser -- here last year. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this season, he's also finished third on the oval at  
Homestead, Fla., in the opener (where Montoya was 10th), second in 
Brazil and third in Madison. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been very strong on ovals, especially compared to this  
time last year,'' said Franchitti, who drives for Team Kool Green. 
``And we had a very productive test at Milwaukee, so we're happy 
with the baseline setup that we have. We did some long runs and 
we're reasonably confident that we know what the car is going to do 
during the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had one of my most enjoyable races last year at Milwaukee.  
Now, our goal is to score as many points as possible and to try to 
take over the championship lead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti showed some sensational car control him last week  
when he got sideways midway through the race and slid for several 
hundred yards without making contact with the wall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes, there's nothing you can do in that situation,'' he  
said. ``But I just tried to stay in the gas and keep the cars as 
straight as possible. I've thought about what to do in that 
situation and tried a few things before. Maybe it was just luck 
that we didn't hit anything, but maybe it helped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With 14 of 20 races remaining, there remain at least 10 drivers  
with realistic championship hopes, including Madison winner Michael 
Andretti, who trails Montoya by just eight points, and Greg Moore 
and Christian Fittipaldi, both 16 points behind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been saying all along that the most consistent team, the  
one that makes the fewest mistakes -- the one that can overcome some 
of the mistakes they do make -- will win it,'' Franchitti said. 
``Nothing I've seen so far has changed my mind.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
