<HEADLINE> Livent OKs SFX's $115 Million Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Livent Inc., the Broadway producer of shows such  
as ``Ragtime'' and ``Fosse,'' has accepted a buyout offer of up to 
$115 million from SFX Entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	SFX, the nation's leading producer of live music shows, agreed  
to buy most of Toronto-based Livent's assets with theaters in New 
York, Chicago and Toronto, according to court papers filed 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian company's filing acknowledged it had aggressively  
tried to sell its business after learning of massive accounting 
irregularities a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the offer, other bids will be accepted according to a  
schedule set by the bankruptcy court, Livent said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Arthur J. Gonzalez set a hearing for  
June 9. 
</P>
<P>
	Livent sought bankruptcy protection in November after a new  
management team headed by former Walt Disney Co. President Michael 
Ovitz said it uncovered fraud by the company's Canadian founders, 
Garth Drabinsky and Myron Gottlieb. 
</P>
<P>
	Drabinsky and Gottlieb were charged in January with fraud and  
conspiracy, accused of stealing $4.6 million from the company in 
the early 1990s and doctoring the books to hide it. Both have 
denied any wrongdoing and remain in Canada. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
