<HEADLINE> Michael Jackson's Son Recovering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Michael Jackson's 2-year-old son is improving  
in a New York City hotel and not on the verge of death after 
suffering a seizure as has been reported, the child's Los Angeles 
doctor said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many reports have circulated in Europe and the United States  
that are completely fictitious,'' said Dr. Allen L. Metzger, who 
has been consulting with Prince Michael Jackson Jr.'s New York 
doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	The pop star was in New York with Prince, who ``continues to be  
under the watchful eye of his family and supportive medical team,'' 
the doctor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Metzger last saw the child in Los Angeles about two weeks ago.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is no neurological disease. Such seizures can occur when  
a child's temperature is too high or goes up too quickly,'' Metzger 
said. ``He is showing slow and significant improvement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reports of the child's illness first developed during a benefit  
concert in Italy where Jackson had been scheduled to appear. Opera 
star Luciano Pavarotti choked back tears as he told the audience 
Tuesday that Jackson's son might be dying and asked people to send 
the child the prayers. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Morrish, an executive with Sony Records, Jackson's  
label, also gave dire reports at the concert site in Modena, Italy, 
that Prince had ``lost consciousness, and his legs and arms were 
paralyzed because of a high viral fever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Multiple attempts to reach Jackson's spokesman by phone have  
been unsuccessful. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson's son was rushed to a hospital in January and treated  
for a viral infection accompanied by fever and dehydration. He 
reportedly was treated in Los Angeles for the same symptoms in 
February. 
</P>
<P>
	Prince was born Feb. 13, 1997. Jackson and his wife had a second  
child, Paris, in April 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
