<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hackett To Stay With Canadiens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Goaltender Jeff Hackett signed a three-year  
contract extension with the Montreal Canadiens on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hackett, who turned 31 on Tuesday, had one year remaining on his  
current contract, after which he could have become an unrestricted 
free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Montreal Gazette reported that Hackett would honor the final  
year of his contract at $1 million, and add three years at what 
agent Rick Curren called, ``Guy Hebert money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hebert, Anaheim's goalie, has a three-year, $12 million  
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Hackett was the Canadiens' player of the year this season after  
being acquired last Nov. 16 in a six-player trade with the Chicago 
Blackhawks. 
</P>
<P>
	With Montreal, he had a record of 24-20-9 with a 2.27  
goals-against average and .914 save percentage in 53 games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 23:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Triple Crown at Stake in Belmont </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The way Bob Baffert sees it, there's more than  
the Triple Crown on the line in Saturday's $1 million Belmont 
Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	More than the Triple Crown?  
</P>
<P>
	``You've been missing the boat,'' said Baffert, who sends out  
his star filly Silverbulletday against Kentucky Derby and Preakness 
winner Charismatic as the colt tries to become racing's 12th Triple 
Crown winner. ``This is the best filly in the country against the 
best colt in the country. It's like a heavyweight fight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The presence of Silverbulletday adds a dimension to the race  
that didn't exist in any of the 25 Belmonts with a Triple Crown at 
stake. For the first time, a filly is in the field as a potential 
spoiler, and not only is she in, but she's the third choice at 4-1 
behind favored Charismatic at 2-1 and Derby and Preakness runner-up 
Menifee, 7-2 in the morning line. 
</P>
<P>
	But to Baffert's thinking, Menifee doesn't quite enter into the  
top-billing equation. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's had two chances already,'' Baffert said.  
</P>
<P>
	While Charismatic, who will be ridden by Chris Antley, attempts  
to become the first Triple Crown winner since Affirmed in 1978 and 
also earn a $5 million bonus from Visa, Silverbulletday looks to be 
a worthy opponent, having overwhelmed the filly ranks by winning 
her last eight races, including easy two-length victories in the 
Kentucky Oaks and the Black-Eyed Susan. Her times, notes Baffert, 
have routinely been faster than the colts'. 
</P>
<P>
	Is it the right move to challenge the boys in the Belmont, and  
try to foil a Triple Crown? 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 926 horses who have run in the Belmont, Silverbulletday  
will be just the 21st filly. Only two have won -- Ruthless in 1867 
and Tanya in 1905. 
</P>
<P>
	More recently, Kentucky Derby-winning Genuine Risk was second to  
Temperence Hill in 1980 and My Flag was third in 1996 to Editor's 
Note. 
</P>
<P>
	``Running in the Triple Crown races is a one shot deal, a filly  
cannot do the three races,'' said Baffert, who found out the hard 
way when his other filly, Excellent Meeting, came off a good effort 
in the Derby and then had to be pulled up in distress in the 
Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Derby wasn't the right time for Silverbulletday; we wanted  
to run her in the Preakness, and we were really dejected when she 
drew the No. 14 post. The time is right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Silverbulletday, who will be ridden by Jerry Bailey, is  
putting her unbeaten-as-a-3-year-old streak on the line in the 
1 1/2-mile race, Baffert feels he has little to lose, and everything 
to gain. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is all about `my horse is better than your horse,' ''  
Baffert said Thursday morning outside Barn 50 at Belmont Park, 
several hours after Silverbulletday went for an early-morning jog. 
``It's the best 3-year-old filly against the best 3-year-old colt. 
This is so big, it ought to be on pay-per-view.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bailey, who replaced Gary Stevens as the filly's regular rider,  
was aboard Silverbulletday once before, winning the Ashland Stakes 
at Keeneland on April 3. It was Bailey, Baffert said, who helped 
convince him and owner Mike Pegram to enter the filly in the 
Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	``She is just one tough filly, a model of consistency,'' Bailey  
said. ``I think she's a special individual, and I said, `What else 
is there for her to conquer?' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Possessed of a quick turn of foot and extraordinary  
acceleration, her rivals have only managed to run with 
Silverbulletday for a few hundred yards before being left in the 
dust, a fact not lost on Charismatic's trainer, D. Wayne Lukas. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's had a cupcake schedule all spring,'' Lukas said. ``She's  
coming into it fresh and that's a huge advantage. The other side of 
the coin is that she hasn't been pressed. She will have to pass 
that test and she's in for a long hard one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Baffert views the Belmont as a showdown, he does admit  
there are others who could win, including Menifee and the Allen 
Jerkens-trained Best of Luck, recent winner of the Peter Pan at 
Belmont on May 23. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, 12 horses were entered, making it the second largest  
Belmont field where a Triple Crown hung in the balance. In 1971, 13 
horses went to post as Pass Catcher upended Canonero II's Triple 
Crown run before a record crowd of 82,694. 
</P>
<P>
	The field, from the rail out, is: Teletable (John Velazquez,  
99-1); Vision and Verse (Herberto Castillo Jr., 20-1); 
Silverbulletday (Bailey, 4-1); Charismatic (Antley, 2-1); Pineaff 
(Sidney LeJune Jr., 30-1); Lemon Drop Kid (Jose Santos, 20-1); 
Patience Game (Kent Desormeaux, 20-1); Adonis (Jorge Chavez, 20-1); 
Prime Directive (Mike Smith, 30-1); Menifee (Pat Day, 7-2); Stephen 
Got Even (Shane Sellers, 10-1); and Best of Luck (Jean-Luc Samyn, 
6-1). 
</P>
<P>
	With sunny skies and warm temperatures forecast for Saturday,  
New York Racing Association officials are hoping -- and bracing -- 
for another huge crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	The Triple Crown will be at stake for the third straight year,  
with 70,682 turning out in 1997 to watch Touch Gold foil Silver 
Charm by three quarters of a length; and 80,162 at the '98 Belmont 
for Victory Gallop's dramatic nose win over Real Quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert says he doesn't view Silverbulletday as a potential  
spoiler. 
</P>
<P>
	``That kind of comes after the race,'' he said. ``We're just  
trying to win the Belmont. ... And the mile-and-a-half? You never 
know. I just hope when she gets to the eighth poll, she doesn't 
pull a Robbie Gordon and run out of gas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The distance is a question mark with every horse in the field,  
from 99-1 shot Teletable to Charismatic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't train horses in this country to run 1 1/2 miles,'' Lukas  
said, ``but we've had two great legs over a five-week run that only 
happens in fairytales. If we can get it done, we're going to enjoy 
it, and if we don't we're still going to enjoy it. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Baffert, he remains confident his filly is ready for a  
``huge race. 
</P>
<P>
	``When people sit down to make their picks on Friday,'' he said,  
``and if they have to hesitate between the filly and him, then 
we've made the right choice in going in this race.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
