<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rivlin Resigns As No. 2 Fed Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Alice Rivlin, the No. 2 official at the  
Federal Reserve, announced Thursday she was resigning from the 
central bank after serving three years as its vice chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	The unexpected resignation was announced in a brief statement by  
the Fed, which also released her resignation letter to President 
Clinton. In the letter, Rivlin said the resignation would be 
effective July 16. 
</P>
<P>
	She said leaving the Fed would give her more time to spend as  
head of the Financial Assistance Authority for the District of 
Columbia, the group that is overseeing Washington's city 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope to spend more time and to be more effectively involved  
in the city than I have been able to be at the Fed,'' she said in 
her letter. 
</P>
<P>
	The authority, known as the control board, was created by  
Congress when the District of Columbia was on the brink of 
financial collapse during the administration of former Mayor Marion 
Barry. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years the city has regained its financial footing, and  
both Congress and the control board have relaxed their day-to-day 
supervision of local affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin's departure means there will be two vacancies on the  
seven-member Fed board of governors. The administration has 
indicated that Carol J. Parry, an executive vice president of Chase 
Manhattan Bank, the country's third largest bank, is the 
front-runner for a vacancy that has existed since last June when 
Susan Phillips left the board. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin was nominated to be vice chairman of the Fed by Clinton  
in 1996. At the time, she was serving as head of the president's 
Office of Management and Budget, where she had the reputation as 
one of the administration's leading deficit hawks. 
</P>
<P>
	She and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin helped pushed the  
administration toward a more aggressive effort to eliminate the 
budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an enormous privilege to be part of the Clinton  
economic team and help put together the policies that turned that 
huge budget deficit into a surplus,'' Rivlin said in her letter to 
Clinton. ``We did the right thing and it worked!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin announced that in addition to devoting more time to her  
duties as chair of the control board, she will also return to the 
Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivlin had also served as the first head of the Congressional  
Budget Office from 1975 to 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of her pending departure, the Fed announced that Rivlin  
would not participate in the next interest rate meeting of the 
central bank's Federal Open Market Committee, composed of Fed board 
members and presidents of the Fed's regional banks. 
</P>
<P>
	The FOMC next meets on June 29-30. At its meeting last month,  
the FOMC signaled that it was poised to begin raising interest 
rates if inflationary pressures get out of hand. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
