<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 19:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alexander Orders Campaign Cutbacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Strapped for cash and trailing in polls,  
Republican presidential candidate Lamar Alexander has ordered steep 
campaign cutbacks to focus his dwindling resources on Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Tennessee governor trimmed his press, legal and  
research operations to keep the campaign afloat in hopes that 
George W. Bush's front-running presidential bid falters and gives 
Alexander a surge in early voting states, advisers said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Their streamlining strategy requires that Alexander finish  
strong -- preferably first -- in an August straw vote in Ames, Iowa., 
and steal momentum from the Texas governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to adjust to reflect the difficulties in raising money  
in the wake of Bush mania,'' Tom Rath, a top Alexander consultant 
said in a telephone interview from New Hampshire. ``Until that 
subsides -- and it may subside when (Bush) gets out on the campaign 
trail and we see what kind of candidate he can be -- we need to do 
things to stay viable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush characterized Alexander's move as one of those ``bumps in  
the road for a lot of campaigns'' and predicted that he'll have a 
few bumps of his own ``should I go for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The development underscores the potency of Bush's fledgling  
campaign. And it could foreshadow similar problems for his 10 
Republican rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough raising money for these candidates who are  
long-shots,'' said Thomas Mann of the Brookings Institute, a 
Washington think tank. ``Everybody is rushing to George W. Bush's 
side, hoping to coronate him. That means money is flowing in, 
endorsements are flowing in and his standing improves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even before making his first campaign swing next week, the Texas  
governor leads every poll and has amassed endorsements from more 
than half the GOP governors and members of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	He will raise at least $16 million in the first six months of  
1999, far more than any other GOP candidate, Bush allies say. Only 
Steve Forbes, who can dip into his family fortune, can compete with 
Bush dollar-for-dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides say Alexander, a formidable fund-raiser in his failed 1996  
campaign, will raise about $2.5 million by June -- not even half of 
what he had hoped. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole, a third moderate Republican competing with Bush  
and Alexander for the support of moderate donors, also has had 
money problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're having a strong second quarter, not as strong as  
Governor Bush but certainly it's going to be competitive with the 
rest of the pack,'' spokesman Ari Fleischer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Vice President Dan Quayle, one of the conservative  
candidates, has had to redirect some resources. Senior staff 
members voluntarily missed paychecks this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a plan to make sure we have adequate staffing and  
appropriate funds,'' Quayle said in a telephone interview from 
California. ``I've never known a campaign that has too much 
money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander began running for the presidency almost as soon as the  
1996 campaign ended. He began the year with high hopes, planning to 
raise at least $15 million to establish himself as the leading GOP 
moderate in the race. He established one of the strongest 
organizations in Iowa and New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Bush bandwagon knocked him off track.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's just a very different environment that we thought we'd be  
in,'' said Rath, Alexander's top adviser. ``What will change the 
fund-raising environment is a change in the political 
environment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rath did not provide details, but three officials familiar with  
the cutbacks said the payroll was being significantly reduced. 
Among those leaving the campaign are communications director Steve 
Schmidt and his deputy, Jeff Macedo, research director Brian Jones, 
legal counsel Kathryn Phillips and several support staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the departing staff will be retained as consultants, but  
at dramatically reduced pay rates, said the officials. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Alexander will reduce his travel --focusing most of  
his attention on Iowa, the site of the first voting of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander is not reducing his fund-raising staff, and he  
recently added four staff members in Iowa, officials said. 
Alexander plans to use the 2000 caucuses as a springboard to the 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	By mid-July, the Alexander staff will be down to 34 from a high  
of 38, according to political director Brian Kennedy. Although that 
represents a net loss of only four staffers, officials said the 
departure of press, legal and research staff involve higher-paid 
employees than those being added to beef up Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're clearing, cutting back on our national campaign staff  
... to make the best use of our resources in Iowa and New 
Hampshire, where we believe this race is being run right now,'' 
Rath said. ``We're trying to be lean as we can be, putting our 
resources in those two states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cutbacks come just days after Alexander moved his  
communications staff from Nashville, Tenn., to Washington to be 
closer to the national political press corps. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
