<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Up on Weather Worry / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices advanced early  
today on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for weather 
conditions that could reduce crop production. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service's latest 10-day forecast calls for  
above-normal temperatures and normal to below-normal rainfall in 
Midwest growing regions. Hot, dry weather could hurt young crops, 
and market participants are beginning to worry a dry weather 
pattern could sharply reduce production on what is expected to be 
bumper acreage. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures also found continued support from delays in spring  
wheat plantings, which come as the window of opportunity for 
getting those crops into the ground comes to a close. Wheat also 
gained amid expectations heavy recent rainfall in the Plains may 
have reduced the quality of the winter wheat crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 2 1/2 cents to $2.55 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn rose 1 1/2 cents to $2.18 1/4 a bushel; July oats rose 1 1/4 cents to 
$1.23 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans rose 3 1/4 cents to $4.62 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures were mostly higher on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .28 cent to 64.80 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .23 cent to 75.90 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .37 cent to 51.02 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .70 
cents to 53.40 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
