<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 12:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton: Bombing Will Continue  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today that Yugoslav  
steps to accept NATO-demanded peace terms for Kosovo are welcome, 
but are not firm enough to warrant an end to the bombing of Serbian 
targets. Clinton says until there's a ``verifiable withdrawal'' of 
Serb forces from Kosovo, the military effort will continue. The 
president says there needs to be ``clarity'' that the Serb leaders 
have accepted the international peace plan, and that it will be 
fully implemented. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Accepts Peace Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic today  
accepted a peace plan for Kosovo designed to end mass expulsions of 
ethnic Albanians and 11 weeks of NATO airstrikes on Yugoslavia. 
Though cloaked in language meant to make it palatable to the 
Belgrade government, the proposal contains tough conditions 
resisted up to now by the Yugoslav president. ``Yugoslavia accepts 
the document for peace brought by the highest representatives of 
the European Union and Russia,'' the official Tanjug news agency 
said. Even amid news of peace in the offing, NATO jets attacked 
communication facilities and fuel depots in Kosovo and elsewhere in 
Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton Moves Closer to Race  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton will form an  
exploratory committee preparing her for a potential Senate campaign 
in New York, a top adviser said today. ``She'll be forming an 
exploratory committee in early July,'' said Harold Ickes, a former 
White House deputy chief of staff heading up Mrs. Clinton's 
political operation. 

</P>
<P>
	Local Police Ratings Vary by Race  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Blacks' dissatisfaction with police outstrips  
that of whites by 2-to-1 or more in New York, Chicago and other big 
cities, the government said today in a report that comes amid 
controversy over ``racial profiling'' by police. The biggest 
black-white difference in the survey of 12 cities: Knoxville, 
Tenn., where 37 percent of blacks said they were dissatisfied with 
police compared with 9 percent for whites. The release of the 
survey comes amid controversy that some police departments engage 
in racial profiling, the practice of stopping motorists based on 
race. 

</P>
<P>
	Mbeki Vows Help for S.Africa's Poor  
</P>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- Nelson Mandela's hand-picked  
successor promised to govern South Africa ``with humility'' and 
speed up help for the nation's poor, while election returns today 
show his African National Congress winning a huge victory. Results 
from yesterday's election, the first since all-race voting in 1994 
ended apartheid, are coming in slowly. The ANC's margin of victory 
is hovering around the two-thirds mark -- a level that would give it 
unilateral power to change the constitution. The South African 
Broadcasting Corp. is projecting that the ANC will reach that mark. 

</P>
<P>
	Florida Girl Wins Spelling Bee  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nupur Lala, a 14-year-old from Tampa, Fla.,  
who studied how to spell words for two hours a day, won the 
national spelling bee today by correctly spelling ``logorrhea,'' 
which means incoherent talkativeness. ``My parents -- they would 
take turns quizzing me,'' said Nupur, who is in the eighth grade at 
Louis Benito Middle School in Tampa. ``When one got tired, the 
other would take over. They were my coaches.'' 

</P>
<P>
	NYSE Delays Extending Trading Hours  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Stock Exchange will delay extending  
its trading hours until next year at the earliest, its chairman 
announced today. Richard Grasso said the board of the world's 
biggest stock exchange would wait first to make sure stock traders 
smoothly handled two challenges -- the Year 2000 computer bug and 
the planned shift to reporting stock prices in decimals rather than 
fractions. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 66, Nasdaq Down 5  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 66.81 points at 10,644.70. Advancers on the New York Stock 
Exchange outnumbered decliners 1,536-1,309. The Nasdaq was down 
5.02 at 2,427.39. 

</P>
<P>
	Karl Malone Wins NBA MVP Award  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Utah's Karl Malone won his second Most Valuable  
Player award today, edging out two other big men, Alonzo Mourning 
and Tim Duncan. Malone, who also won the award in 1996-97, received 
827 points and 44 first-place votes from a panel of sports writers 
and broadcasters. Voting took place before the start of the 
playoffs. Miami's Mourning finished second with 773 points and San 
Antonio's Duncan was third with 740 points. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
