<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Deadlocks on Genentech Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal jury has deadlocked on a lawsuit  
against biotech giant Genentech Inc., which was accused of stealing 
a patented DNA molecule and using it to develop a top-selling 
growth hormone. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors voted 8-1 in favor of the University of California's  
claim of patent infringement, but were unable to resolve the 
impasse in six days of deliberations, jurors told reporters 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The university sought up to $400 million for lost license fees  
on Protropin, which had sales of more than $1.2 billion between 
1985 and 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury, however, rejected Genentech's claim that the 1982  
patent was invalid. 
</P>
<P>
	John Kidd, a lawyer for Genentech, deferred comment to the  
company, which did not issue a statement. But he said the deadlock 
``shows that the university did not prove its case on 
infringement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The retrial will include claims of infringement against a second  
Genentech growth hormone, Nutropin, said Gerald Dodson, a lawyer 
for the university. 
</P>
<P>
	Genentech, based in South San Francisco, has grabbed headlines  
recently for its research, including work on a drug that was once 
thought would allow patients with chest pain to grow tiny blood 
vessels in the heart and thus avoid surgery. It is also behind the 
pioneering breast-cancer drug Herceptin and Pulmozyme, a 
cystic-fibrosis therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	The university's 1990 suit stems from the early years of  
Genentech. 
</P>
<P>
	UC San Francisco researchers identified a genetic pattern for  
human growth hormone in 1978. One of the researchers, Peter 
Seeburg, now a director of the Max Planck Institute for Medical 
Research in Heidelberg, Germany, testified that he quit his 
university job in November 1978, then made a midnight visit to his 
former lab and took cloned DNA samples to Genentech, where he had 
just gone to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Seeburg said he and another Genentech scientist tried for months  
to produce human growth hormone DNA on their own, then removed the 
cloned samples from a freezer and were able to isolate material 
that could be injected into bacteria and reproduced. He said he 
failed to disclose the source of the research in a 1979 article in 
a scientific journal. 
</P>
<P>
	Genentech paid the university $2 million for the DNA in 1979.  
</P>
<P>
	The company attacked Seeburg as a liar and an admitted drug user  
who had told conflicting stories about the source of the product. 
His former research partner, David Goeddel, testified Genentech 
developed the hormone without using the university's DNA. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate action, Genentech agreed in April to plead guilty  
to a criminal charge and pay a $50 million fine for marketing 
Protropin for uses not approved by the Food and Drug 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Early today, Switzerland's Roche Holding Ltd. announced it will  
allow Genentech Inc. to remain an independent company, agreeing to 
buy outstanding shares of the biotech giant and then make a public 
offering. Roche will remain the company's majority shareholder. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
