<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of June 6-12:  
</P>
<P>
	60 years ago: Greta Garbo was on a set for the first time in two  
years as the cameras rolled for ``Ninotchka.'' 
</P>
<P>
	35 years ago: The Rolling Stones recorded at the Chess studios  
in Chicago, where they met Chuck Berry, Willie Dixon and Muddy 
Waters. 
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: Brian Jones, citing artistic differences,  
announced that he was leaving The Rolling Stones. A month later, he 
was found dead in his swimming pool after going on a midnight swim. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-record rock opera ``Tommy'' hit the U.S. album chart at  
the No. 4 spot. It was the first album by The Who to make it into 
the U.S. Top 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Blind Faith made its live debut in London's Hyde Park. It was  
the only show the group ever performed in Britain. The band, which 
included Eric Clapton, Steve Winwood, Rick Grech and Ginger Baker, 
split up later that year. 
</P>
<P>
	And Barbara Hershey, Richard Thomas and Cathy Burns starred in  
``Last Summer.'' The film was directed by Frank Perry. 
</P>
<P>
	25 years ago: Rick Wakeman announced that he was leaving Yes.  
Although he had a successful solo career, he rejoined the rock band 
two years later. 
</P>
<P>
	And Dolly Parton's ``I Will Always Love You'' was No. 1 on the  
country and western charts. 
</P>
<P>
	20 years ago: Chuck Berry performed at the White House for  
President Jimmy Carter. 
</P>
<P>
	15 years ago: Phoebe Cates starred in ``Gremlins.''  
</P>
<P>
	And Bill Murray, Dan Aykroyd and Sigourney Weaver starred in  
``Ghostbusters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	10 years ago: The Elvis Presley Automobile Museum, an exhibit of  
more than 20 cars once owned by the king of rock 'n' roll, opened 
at Graceland, Presley's former Memphis, Tenn., residence. It was 
the newest attraction at Graceland's souvenir shopping center. 
</P>
<P>
	And a new lineup of The Doobie Brothers embarked on its first  
U.S. tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: Jack Palance, Billy Crystal and other stars of  
``City Slickers II'' attended the movie's premiere in Atlanta to 
benefit former President Jimmy Carter's inner-city Atlanta Project. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: British actor Derek Jacobi won the 1998 Hamburg  
Shakespeare Prize. The $23,000 prize was awarded by the Alfred 
Toepfer Foundation. Jacobi had portrayed Hamlet, Richard II and 
Richard III on the British stage. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken 10 years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``I keep reading that we're too old, but they never say too old  
for what.'' -- William Shatner, the 58-year-old star, director and 
co-writer of ``Star Trek V: The Final Frontier.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``Anyone who makes fun of 'Baywatch' is doing it out of  
ignorance. This is a good quality show.'' -- David Hasselhoff, one 
of the stars and executive producer of the syndicated television 
show. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken one year ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``If we ever revealed the secrets behind all this, the show  
would be unmasked as the ridiculous little hoax that it is.'' -- 
David Duchovny, star of ``The X-Files.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
