<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Judge's Ethics Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GADSDEN, Ala. (AP) -- A judge who fought to keep a Ten  
Commandments plaque hanging in his courtroom may have violated 
ethics laws by soliciting donations from people who supported his 
crusade, a state panel has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The Alabama Ethics Commission voted 5-0 on Wednesday that there  
was probable cause to believe Roy Moore violated the state law 
prohibiting public officials from using their offices for private 
financial gain. 
</P>
<P>
	Ethics Commission Director Jim Sumner said Thursday that members  
believed Moore also spent money on more than legal expenses and 
used the ``mantle of his office'' to solicit funds. He declined to 
elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore denied personally raising money or receiving any money  
from the fund, which he said is maintained by his attorney. Moore 
said he is being persecuted for his defense of Christianity. 
</P>
<P>
	Dean Young, a former spokesman for Moore and founder of the  
``Judge Roy Moore Fund,'' said it had raised over $100,000 two 
years ago. Up-to-date figures were not immediately available. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics commission sent the case to Attorney General Bill  
Pryor, who must decide whether to take the case before a grand 
jury. 
</P>
<P>
	Pryor, a Republican who once spoke at a 1997 rally for Moore,  
said he had not seen the ethics referral and could not comment. 
</P>
<P>
	If charged with a crime and convicted, Moore could face removal  
from the bench, up to 20 years in prison and a $10,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Moore's fight began in 1995 when the American Civil Liberties  
Union challenged his hand-carved courtroom display. The federal 
lawsuit eventually was dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Alabama Supreme Court in January dismissed on technical  
grounds a lawsuit filed by Pryor and former Gov. Fob James' legal 
adviser that sought to declare Moore's display legal. James had 
threatened to call out the National Guard if necessary to keep the 
plaque from being removed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 20:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force Helicopter Crash Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT BRAGG, N.C. (AP) -- One crew member died Thursday after a  
crash of an Air Force special operations helicopter on a nighttime 
training mission. 
</P>
<P>
	The MH-53J Pave-Low, used to ferry troops behind enemy lines,  
went down about 10:05 p.m. Wednesday in a clearing in woods on the 
western side of Fort Bragg. 
</P>
<P>
	The helicopter was assigned to the 20th Special Operations  
Squadron, part of the 16th Special Operations Wing based at 
Hurlburt Field in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Staff Sgt. Kurt Upton, 25, of Niota, Ill., died of injuries from  
the crash about 5 a.m. Thursday at Womack Army Medical Center, said 
senior airman Jodi Jordan, a spokeswoman at Hurlburt. 
</P>
<P>
	The other crew members sustained only minor injuries.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
