<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 12:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kasich Helped Bury Supporter's Dog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Would-be presidents have done lots of  
unusual things on the campaign trail in New Hampshire. But Rep. 
John Kasich probably is the first to dig a grave -- for a dog. 
</P>
<P>
	Linda Kaiser accidentally ran over her dog, Magic, a 13-year-old  
black Shetland sheepdog, as she hurried to get some last-minute 
things for a coffee chat she was hosting for the Ohio Republican at 
her Amherst home May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``I started backing up and I heard this little thump, and I got  
out of my car and there he was,'' Kaiser said in a telephone 
interview Thursday. ``He looked at me and then he died.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kaiser said she stashed Magic's body in the barn and covered him  
with a towel. 
</P>
<P>
	When he heard what had happened, Kasich took Kaiser outside and  
asked if she wanted to cancel the gathering. Not a chance, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential candidate lingered until all the  
guests had left, then said it was time to tend to Magic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not leaving here without burying this dog because if I do  
my wife will divorce me after she kills me,'' Kaiser said Kasich 
told her when she protested his offer to help. 
</P>
<P>
	And so Kasich and Kaiser's husband, Christopher, grabbed shovels  
from the barn and dug a grave for Magic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I would see the other candidates doing that,''  
she said. ``When you watch them on television, they always seem so 
busy. He wasn't too busy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That Kasich is keen for canines should come as no surprise to  
anyone who visits his campaign Internet site, which prominently 
displays photos of his dog, Penny Bird. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 08:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yahoo! Sets Sights Beyond PCs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Yahoo! Inc. made a pair of moves in  
an effort to deliver its Web content beyond personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! acquired Palo Alto, Calif.-based Online Anywhere, a  
provider of Internet delivery services for televisions, personal 
digital assistants and wireless devices, including pagers and data 
phones. 
</P>
<P>
	The all-stock transaction is valued at approximately $80  
million, according to a Yahoo! statement released Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Santa Clara-based Yahoo!, which operates the Internet directory  
service Yahoo.com, already was using Online Anywhere's technology 
to format its content for display on non-PC devices. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! also entered an agreement with Kansas City, Mo.-based  
Sprint PCS to offer Web content to Sprint's 3 million wireless 
phone subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies will deliver news, weather, sports, e-mail,  
horoscopes, and calendar and address book functions to Sprint PCS 
phone users. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are committed to making Yahoo! services available to users  
of any device, from any access point, at any time,'' said Ellen 
Siminoff, vice president of Yahoo! business development and 
strategic planning. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint PCS, wholly-owned by Sprint Corp., and Yahoo! expect to  
make Sprint PCS My Yahoo! services available by the fourth quarter 
of this year. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 23:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Jones-Johnson To Fight for Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BILOXI, Miss. (AP) -- Roy Jones Jr. and Reggie Johnson don't need  
Saturday night's light heavyweight title fight. That's why they 
want it so much. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a matter of me needing Roy or Roy needing me,''  
Johnson said. ``We've both got titles. It was a matter of us 
needing each other because we both want to add `undisputed' to our 
title.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones holds the WBC and WBA championships, while Johnson has the  
IBF belt. Their bout will unify the division for the first time 
since 1985, when Michael Spinks held the titles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one who wins this can say he's the baddest fighter in the  
world, and anyone who doesn't believe it will have to fight to 
prove it,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 32, is 39-5-1 with 24 KOs. He is 7-4 in championship  
fights, with all his losses in close, disputed decisions. His last 
fight was Feb. 27 when he won a 12-round unanimous decision against 
top-ranked contender Will Taylor. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be the toughest fight of my life,'' Johnson  
said. ``I have a lot of respect for Roy. I know how tough he is, 
how good he is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The respect goes both ways. Jones' father trained both fighters  
for a while in 1991, a move that drove father and son apart in a 
bitter dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	``What my father didn't understand was that it was inevitable  
that we would one day meet in the ring,'' Jones said Thursday. ``I 
knew it right away. I knew we were both headed for the championship 
and we'd have to settle it between us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was trained by his father throughout his amateur and early  
pro career. But he called his father's decision to bring Johnson 
into his training program the final straw that broke their 
relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he wanted to bring someone in to get me ready for the race,  
it shouldn't have been the horse I was going to have to run 
against,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones and his father didn't speak to each other for several  
years. Although they have since reconciled and now talk, Jones said 
many of their ties remain broken. He doesn't blame Johnson, 
however. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not at all. We both have a lot of respect for each other,''  
Jones said. ``There aren't going to be any mind games or any other 
kind of games. There's just going to be some big boxing. This is 
going to be the real deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, 30, is 39-1 with 33 knockouts. He has successfully  
defended his WBC title three times, the WBC championship once. He 
won his last fight by stopping New York City policeman Rick 
Frazier. 
</P>
<P>
	Reminiscing about their days as sparring partners, Jones said he  
remembered the damage Johnson could do with either hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was very heavy-handed, knockout power in either hand,''  
Jones said. ``He's a big puncher, a good defensive fighter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said Jones was a guy who could hurt you fast and often.  
</P>
<P>
	``He has extremely fast hands, he's very smart,'' Johnson said.  
``He's a little flashier than I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two other title fights are on Saturday night's card. IBF  
cruiserweight champion Arthur Williams will make his first defense 
against Vasilly Jirov, the fourth-ranked challenger, and IBF 
lightweight champion Roberto Garcia will defend against No. 2 
Derrick Gainer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
