<HEADLINE> Pacific Exchange Names New CEO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The Pacific Exchange has appointed former  
mutual fund executive Philip DeFeo as chief executive, succeeding 
Robert Greber, who will remain as chairman of the nation's 
third-largest stock options market. 
</P>
<P>
	Until February, DeFeo, 53, was president and chief executive of  
Van Eck Associates Group, a New York fund company with $1.5 billion 
in assets that specializes in commodities and international stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFeo's appointment followed the recent resignations of the  
Pacific Exchange's president, Warren Langley, and chief financial 
officer, Kim Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	The new CEO arrives at a critical juncture for the Pacific  
Exchange. Since the collapse of its pending merger with the Chicago 
Board Options Exchange earlier this year, it has been updating its 
technology to replace its traditional trading floor system, where 
brokers shout out buy and sell orders, with a computer-based 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFeo said he plans to study all alternatives for the exchange's  
future. ``Everything will be under review,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, DeFeo said he will re-examine negotiations under  
way with the brokerage Cantor Fitzgerald to start a computer-based 
stock options trading system. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the proposed deal, Cantor would provide its electronic  
trading technology and the Pacific Exchange would move a portion of 
the 800 options it handles from its San Francisco trading floor to 
the joint venture. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
