<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Armey Says Pop Culture a Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Majority Leader Dick Armey is suggesting  
that economic boycotts as well as federal legislation have a role 
in combating ``the violence of crudity'' that pervades modern pop 
culture. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do need to hold Hollywood, the music industry and video  
game makers accountable...,'' the Texas Republican wrote in a 
letter to all GOP House Republicans following the shootings at a 
Colorado high school. ``Demanding better warning labels and 
organizing boycotts of the most egregious products are obviously 
first steps,'' wrote the former economics professor. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to the shootings, Armey said, ``We should not simply  
blame the guns.... Nor should we rush to impose government 
censorship on Hollywood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Censorship would not have deterred these mass murderers. And  
more importantly, we have to admit that somebody out there is 
paying for all that gratuitous sex and violence on the screen. 
Somebody out there is permitting their children to watch 20 hours 
of television a week. Somebody out there is letting their children 
see 200,000 fictional murder by the time they're 18.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, Armey wrote, ``We have no more important duty than to  
replace today's moral relativism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The House will debate the issue later this month, when  
Republicans bring to the floor legislation to attack juvenile 
crime. Gun control proposals are certain to be part of the bill, as 
they were in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Armey, in his letter, called for a few new gun-related  
provisions, including the so-called juvenile Brady bill that would 
bar juvenile violent felons from ever owning a gun. He also 
suggested letting judges, police officers and others crack down on 
young offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	But he took no position on other issues likely to come up on the  
House floor, including Senate-passed measures requiring that safety 
locks be sold with all new guns and background checks be performed 
for all firearms sales at gun shows and pawn shops. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore will pick up yet another endorsement from  
a congressional Democrat next week in his quest for the 
presidential nomination, the latest turn in a checkered 
relationship with Rhode Island Rep. Patrick Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost a year ago, Gore traveled to Rhode Island for an  
appearance regarding Social Security and Kennedy was not invited to 
speak. Kennedy felt snubbed and let it be known; Gore's aides 
countered that the scheduling decisions had been made by others. 
</P>
<P>
	But that was long ago, when Kennedy's patron, Rep. Richard  
Gephardt of Missouri, was preparing to challenge Gore for the 
presidential nomination. These days, Gephardt is firmly in Gore's 
corner and Kennedy is chairman of the party's campaign committee, 
which is trying to win a Democratic majority in the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy will bestow his endorsement next weekend, say Democratic  
officials who spoke on condition of anonymity, when Gore returns to 
Rhode Island for a fund-raising event to benefit House candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	That event will be part of an intensive weekend of Democratic  
fund-raising to benefit House Democratic candidates. On Thursday 
night, President Clinton is scheduled to attend an event in 
Washington. On Friday, while Gore is in Rhode Island, Hillary 
Rodham Clinton is to join Gephardt in St. Louis for yet another 
fund-raising event. In all, officials say they hope to pull in $2 
million for House candidates over the two days. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
