<HEADLINE>  Jones-Johnson To Fight for Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BILOXI, Miss. (AP) -- Roy Jones Jr. and Reggie Johnson don't need  
Saturday night's light heavyweight title fight. That's why they 
want it so much. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't a matter of me needing Roy or Roy needing me,''  
Johnson said. ``We've both got titles. It was a matter of us 
needing each other because we both want to add `undisputed' to our 
title.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones holds the WBC and WBA championships, while Johnson has the  
IBF belt. Their bout will unify the division for the first time 
since 1985, when Michael Spinks held the titles. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one who wins this can say he's the baddest fighter in the  
world, and anyone who doesn't believe it will have to fight to 
prove it,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 32, is 39-5-1 with 24 KOs. He is 7-4 in championship  
fights, with all his losses in close, disputed decisions. His last 
fight was Feb. 27 when he won a 12-round unanimous decision against 
top-ranked contender Will Taylor. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be the toughest fight of my life,'' Johnson  
said. ``I have a lot of respect for Roy. I know how tough he is, 
how good he is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The respect goes both ways. Jones' father trained both fighters  
for a while in 1991, a move that drove father and son apart in a 
bitter dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	``What my father didn't understand was that it was inevitable  
that we would one day meet in the ring,'' Jones said Thursday. ``I 
knew it right away. I knew we were both headed for the championship 
and we'd have to settle it between us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones was trained by his father throughout his amateur and early  
pro career. But he called his father's decision to bring Johnson 
into his training program the final straw that broke their 
relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he wanted to bring someone in to get me ready for the race,  
it shouldn't have been the horse I was going to have to run 
against,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones and his father didn't speak to each other for several  
years. Although they have since reconciled and now talk, Jones said 
many of their ties remain broken. He doesn't blame Johnson, 
however. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not at all. We both have a lot of respect for each other,''  
Jones said. ``There aren't going to be any mind games or any other 
kind of games. There's just going to be some big boxing. This is 
going to be the real deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, 30, is 39-1 with 33 knockouts. He has successfully  
defended his WBC title three times, the WBC championship once. He 
won his last fight by stopping New York City policeman Rick 
Frazier. 
</P>
<P>
	Reminiscing about their days as sparring partners, Jones said he  
remembered the damage Johnson could do with either hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was very heavy-handed, knockout power in either hand,''  
Jones said. ``He's a big puncher, a good defensive fighter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said Jones was a guy who could hurt you fast and often.  
</P>
<P>
	``He has extremely fast hands, he's very smart,'' Johnson said.  
``He's a little flashier than I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two other title fights are on Saturday night's card. IBF  
cruiserweight champion Arthur Williams will make his first defense 
against Vasilly Jirov, the fourth-ranked challenger, and IBF 
lightweight champion Roberto Garcia will defend against No. 2 
Derrick Gainer. 
  	   	
</P>
