<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agassi Favorite Among Semifinalists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Three players who might have thought their best  
days were behind them, and one whose seem yet to come, make up the 
unlikely semifinalists at this year's French Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Andre Agassi, the only seeded player left in the men's event,  
faces Dominik Hrbaty, and Andrei Medvedev takes on Fernando 
Meligeni in Friday's semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi, 29, is closing in on the record books.  
</P>
<P>
	A championship win here would make him only the fifth man to win  
all four Grand Slams, and the first since Rod Laver in 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	Such greats as Boris Becker, Jimmy Connors, Stefan Edberg and  
Pete Sampras have won the other three Grand Slams, but slipped up 
on the clay of Roland Garros. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi, gets great satisfaction just from being in the last  
four. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gives me the opportunity to do something I haven't done,  
which is always special,'' the 13th-seeded player said. ``Getting 
to the semifinals on a surface that has presented many obstacles 
for me in recent years leaves me to believe I can do much more. 
This has been nothing short of a great chapter in my career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Agassi fails, an unseeded player will be champion for only  
the fourth time in Roland Garros history. Marcel Bernard won in 
1946, Mats Wilander in 1982 and Gustavo Kuerten two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Agassi is the favorite, but needs to be at his very best to  
advance to Sunday's final. 
</P>
<P>
	Hrbaty beat top-seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov and ninth-seeded  
Marcelo Rios on the way to his first Grand Slam semifinal. The 
21-year-old has won five out of six matches against top 10 players 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hrbaty was voted best newcomer by his fellow professionals in  
1996, but has taken time to break through. His best previous Grand 
Slam performance came in the 1997 Australian Open, where he reached 
the fourth round. 
</P>
<P>
	He also won his only match against Agassi, at the Lipton  
Championships in March. 
</P>
<P>
	But Agassi said he was not fully fit in that match.  
</P>
<P>
	``While it was a good performance on his part, I hadn't  
recovered from the hamstring injury I had,'' he said. ``We are both 
playing a lot better than we did then. I am anticipating a very 
brutal match.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 54th-ranked Meligeni and Medvedev, ranked 100th, compete in  
the other semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
	At 28, Meligeni is a tour veteran making his first appearance in  
a Grand Slam semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
	Medvedev, who beat Pete Sampras in the second round, was ranked  
as high as No. 4 back in 1994 before tumbling in the rankings. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
