<HEADLINE> Companies Recall Stairway Gates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) --North States Industries, Inc. is recalling  
about 3,200 stairway gates because the lock can fail when the gate 
is shaken and could result in children falling down the stairs, 
according to the Consumer Product Safety Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The Minneapolis-based company has received one report of the  
lock on the gate failing. No injuries were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The recalled gates -- intended for use with children from six  
months to 24 months of age -- are white plastic and a little over 2 
feet high. 
</P>
<P>
	Ames, Ann &AMP; Hope, Hambleton &AMP; Carr and Value City department  
stores sold the gates from March through April of this year for 
about $15. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers should stop using these gates and return them to the  
store where purchased for a refund. They can also call the company 
at 800-848-8421 between 9 a.m. and 6 p.m. EDT Monday through 
Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
