<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Spellers Appeal Eliminations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Harry Altman was stumped for four minutes and  
30 seconds by the first word he faced today in the finals of the 
national spelling bee. 
</P>
<P>
	He whispered the word ``banns'' to himself, glanced around the  
stage, sighed hard into the microphone, closed his eyes -- even 
stuck out his tongue. 
</P>
<P>
	``B-a,'' he started. He stopped. Then he started again.  
``B-a-n-d ... oops, let's see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judges were getting impatient.  
</P>
<P>
	``Take a deep breath and let's finish the word,'' judge Mary  
Brooks told the sixth-grader kindly. 
</P>
<P>
	Harry spelled ``b-a-n-d-s'' with little confidence. The  
elimination bell sounded. The 12-year-old computer enthusiast from 
Glen Rock, N.J., was out. 
</P>
<P>
	He appealed his elimination, arguing that the official  
pronouncer mispronounced the word ``banns,'' a plural noun that 
means an announcement of an intended marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said `bands' and they didn't make me repeat it,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Spelling bee officials disagreed. They did not reinstate Harry,  
but they did reinstate Greg Touney, 14, of Decatur, Ill., who 
appealed his elimination as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg's word was ``immanent,'' which means dwelling within. He  
spelled it ``imminent,'' and was eliminated. After he appealed, the 
judges ruled that he had given an acceptable alternate spelling. 
</P>
<P>
	The 72nd annual Scripps Howard National Spelling Bee began  
Wednesday with 249 spellers. When the competition resumed today, 
104 spellers were still in the running. At the end of the fifth 
round, 21 were left. The winner gets a $10,000 first-place cash 
prize, plus encyclopedias, two airline tickets and computer 
software. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the 9- to 15-year-old contestants, all wearing white  
polo shirts, spelled with their hands stuffed deep in their 
pockets. Others gazed at the ceiling for inspiration. When they sat 
waiting their turn, they yawned, examined the bottoms of their 
tennis shoes, twirled hair and fidgeted with yellow numbered 
placards hung around their necks. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday was a nerve-wracking day for Jason Espiritu, a  
13-year-old speller from Tamuning, Guam. 
</P>
<P>
	First he faced the word ``verisimilitude,'' a noun meaning  
something that appears real. It has seven -- count them, seven -- 
vowels. Then the judges accidentally sounded the elimination bell 
when he correctly spelled ``operatable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It really shook me. They rang the bell, but it was right,''  
Jason said. 
</P>
<P>
	His third word on Wednesday was ``encaustic,'' a paint mixed  
with beeswax. That one troubled him for four minutes, two seconds, 
but he got it right. 
</P>
<P>
	The words didn't get any easier today. Jason spelled ``toccata''  
correctly but was stumped momentarily by ``cartonnage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He wanted to know the origin of the French word. He asked to  
hear it in a sentence. He asked for its definition (the material 
used to make Egyptian mummy cases). Finally he spelled it, then 
waited for the elimination bell. When it didn't ring, he thrust 
both arms in the air and got a high-five from another speller. 
</P>
<P>
	Jason then gave a high-five to Angela Smiley, a 13-year-old from  
Kokomo, Ind., who was so happy when she correctly spelled 
``festschrift,'' defined as a volume of essays, that she skipped 
back to her seat. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 08:40:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cops: Missing Pa. Students Were Shot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BURGETTSTOWN, Pa. (AP) -- Three teen-agers suspected of breaking  
into an apartment near a Roman Catholic university campus and 
kidnapping two members of a religious fraternity say the pair were 
shot to death, according to investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	Law officers resumed a search for the missing students today in  
western Pennsylvania, about 15 miles from the Franciscan University 
campus in Steubenville, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Muha, 18, a sophomore biology major from suburban  
Columbus, Ohio, and Aaron Land, 20, a junior business major from 
Philadelphia, have been missing since Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Somebody broke into their apartment just before dawn on Memorial  
Day, and police said they found blood in a bedroom and at least two 
bullet shells. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Stephen Stern declined to identify the suspects, ages  
19, 18 and 16, who were held at the Jefferson County, Ohio, jail. 
The suspects said the victims had been killed, although each said 
the others did it, Stern said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trooper Diana Grady of the Pennsylvania state police said the  
three were suspected of aggravated burglary, kidnapping and 
aggravated robbery. She did not know whether charges had been 
filed. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said they found blood inside and on the outside of  
Muha's Chevy Blazer, which was stopped with two of the suspects 
inside. 
</P>
<P>
	``The indication was that the car was pulled alongside a road  
and the alleged victims were taken up an embankment and shot two to 
four times in a wooded area,'' Stern said. 
</P>
<P>
	Franciscan University is a Roman Catholic liberal arts school  
with about 2,000 students. The university is operated by the 
Franciscan Friars of the Sacred Heart Province in Loretto. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the campus was nearly deserted for the summer session, a  
vigil Wednesday night drew about 400 people to the campus chapel. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what to think,'' Land's brother, Mike, told  
KDKA-TV. ``I couldn't imagine life without my brother. He's just 
the greatest guy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
