<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 02:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *Nathan S. Ancell    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Nathan S. Ancell, co-founder of the Ethan Allen  
furniture company and pioneer of the concept of selling furniture 
in room-style settings, died Monday at his home in New Rochelle. He 
was 90. 
</P>
<P>
	Ancell and his brother-in-law, Theodore Baumritter, started  
their company in the 1930s in Beecher Falls, Vt., out of a bankrupt 
furniture factory. Its headquarters was eventually moved to 
Danbury, Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	Breaking the tradition of displaying furniture in rows of  
chairs, tables and beds, Ancell applied the ``gallery concept'' of 
showing furniture in coordinated settings. 
</P>
<P>
	Ancell succeed Baumritter as chairman in 1970, handing over  
management to Farooq Kathwari in 1985. The company was bought by 
Interco Inc. for $150 million in 1980, and was sold to a management 
group led by Kathwari in 1989. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Vaclav Benda    	
</P>
<P>
	PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) -- Vaclav Benda, a Czech senator,  
mathematician, philosopher and former anti-communist dissident, 
died today, the news agency CTK reported. He was 52. 
</P>
<P>
	Benda, a member of the Civic Democratic Party and a signatory of  
the Charter 77 human rights movement, spent four years in communist 
jails. 
</P>
<P>
	After the 1989 peaceful revolution that toppled the communist  
regime, he became a deputy in the Czechoslovak parliament and later 
headed a newly established institute investigating crimes of the 
former communist officials. 
</P>
<P>
	He was elected to the upper chamber of the Czech parliament, the  
Senate, in 1996. 

</P>
<P>
                      *Dr. L. Joseph Butterfield    	
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Dr. L. Joseph Butterfield, known as the father of  
neonatology, died Tuesday at his home in Denver. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Butterfield was known worldwide for his ideas about the care of  
newborn babies. His medical career and affiliation with The 
Children's Hospital in Denver spanned five decades. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1965, he was recruited as the medical director to create  
Children's Newborn Center, among the first of its kind in the 
nation. His program, ``Newborn Country USA,'' became recognized as 
a national model for regional perinatal care. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Christopher Cockerell    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sir Christopher Cockerell, inventor of the  
hovercraft, died Tuesday. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Cockerell studied engineering at Cambridge University and worked  
for the electrical company Marconi, helping develop a transmission 
antenna for the BBC's first TV station at Alexandra Palace, north 
London. 
</P>
<P>
	During World War II, he worked on the development of Britain's  
radar defense system and helped design an aerial direction finder 
that helped Allied pilots navigate their return to Britain's 
wartime air bases. 
</P>
<P>
	By the early 1950s, he left Marconi and settled in Norfolk,  
eastern England, to build tourist boats, but he also began work on 
inventing his hovercraft, which could move across land or water on 
a cushion of air. 
</P>
<P>
	The first prototype hovercraft, the SR-N1, crossed the English  
Channel in June 1959. The first commercial service began in Britain 
in 1962 and across the English Channel in 1966. 
</P>
<P>
	He was knighted in 1969, and in 1971 received $250,000 from the  
government for surrendering his patent rights to the hovercraft. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Leonard Edward Howard    	
</P>
<P>
	LAWTON, Okla. (AP) -- Leonard Edward ``Ed'' Howard, city/county  
reporter for the Lawton Constitution, died Monday after a brief 
illness. He was 44. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard began his career in January 1979 as a staff writer for  
The Lawton Constitution and Morning Press. He went on to work at 
the Miami (Okla.) News Record, The Georgetown (Texas) Weekly and 
The El Reno Tribune before returning to the Constitution in October 
1993. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Charles Pierce    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Charles Pierce, an actor and female  
impersonator famous for characterizations of Hollywood stars 
including Bette Davis, Mae West and Joan Crawford, died Monday of 
cancer. He was 73. 
</P>
<P>
	Pierce did monologues and stand-up comedy in 1952 at the Cabaret  
Concert on Sunset Boulevard. He first got paid for his impressions 
while performing at the Club LaVie in Altadena. 
</P>
<P>
	He added women's clothing to his act in the 1960s, quickly  
gaining admiration for his uncanny ability to conjure up images of 
female celebrities by using subtle facial expressions and vocal 
inflections. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, he took his show to San Francisco's Gilded Cage and to  
Miami, where he got around laws barring cross-dressing by using 
props or wearing trousers under his gowns. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, he returned to the stage after the death of Davis, his  
most famous character, revamping his one-man nightclub act of 
``legendary ladies of the silver screen.'' 

</P>
<P>
                          *Harvey Puckett    	
</P>
<P>
	PARIS, Ky. (AP) -- Harvey Puckett, a jockey at tracks in southern  
Ohio and northern Kentucky, died Sunday of kidney failure. He was 
41. 
</P>
<P>
	Puckett had some of his best years in the mid-1980s at River  
Downs in Cincinnati, where he won six stakes races. He rode Tall 
Grass Walker to the 1984 Spartacus Stakes victory and set a course 
record aboard the horse on June 10, 1984, when they covered 7 1/2 
furlongs on the turf course in 1:29 3/5. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Crocker Snow Sr.    	
</P>
<P>
	IPSWICH, Mass. (AP) -- Crocker Snow Sr., a pioneering aviator and  
director of the Massachusetts Aeronautic Commission, died Tuesday. 
He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow was a founder of Skyways Aviation, the first commercial  
flight operation at Logan International Airport in Boston. Amelia 
Earhart was one of his students. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow became the state's first aviation director in 1939 shortly  
after the forming of the commission, which he helped create by 
writing the first comprehensive aeronautical law for Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	His only absence from the commission in nearly 40 years was a  
tour of duty during World War II in the Army Air Force. He became a 
colonel by 1944. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970, President Nixon appointed him chairman of the Aviation  
Advisory Commission, created by Congress to report on the 
long-range needs of commercial and private aviation. 
</P>
<P>
	He made his last solo flight in 1998.  

</P>
<P>
                           *Frank Spencer    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Anthropologist Frank Spencer, who accused a  
well-respected English anatomist of masterminding the 1912 Piltdown 
Man fraud, died Sunday of cancer. He was 58. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer worked since the early 1970s to solve the decades-long  
mystery of who was behind the counterfeit of early human fossils. 
He explained his findings in a 1990 book titled, ``Piltdown: A 
Scientific Forgery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piltdown, a small village in England, made international news in  
1912 when a skull and other artifacts were discovered by Sussex 
lawyer Charles Dawson in a gravel pit. 
</P>
<P>
	The discovery was debunked in 1953 when scientists learned the  
remains were a modern human skull joined to an orangutan's jaw. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer's books included ``The Piltdown Papers,'' also published  
in 1990; ``Ecco Homo,'' a bibliographic history of physical 
anthropology; and ``The Origin of Modern Humans,'' a world survey 
of the fossil evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also the editor of ``The History of Physical  
Anthropology,'' published in 1997. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Robert M. Thompson    	
</P>
<P>
	POYNETTE, Wis. (AP) -- Robert M. Thompson, who oversaw law  
enforcement at Fort McCoy when it served as an internment camp for 
thousands of Cuban refugees in 1980, died Tuesday of a heart 
attack. He was 71. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson, a former U.S. marshal, served five terms in the  
Assembly as a Democrat but switched to the Republican Party in 1990 
in an unsuccessful bid for secretary of state. 
</P>
<P>
	He was appointed by President Carter in 1978 as U.S. marshal for  
western Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	That made him the top law enforcement officer involved when the  
Army camp near Sparta became home to 15,000 Cuban refugees, 
including freed prisoners and mental patients, who were permitted 
by Fidel Castro to leave for the United States. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
