<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Profits Slip at Air France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French national carrier Air France's profit fell 11  
percent in its latest fiscal year, hurt by a pilot strike and a 
slump in Asian cargo shipments. But it expects solid growth in 
operating results this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Air France also said Thursday it will select a U.S. partner in  
the course of 1999 ``to create a global alliance'' although it 
offered few details on what kind of alliance it had in mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Executive Pierre-Henri Gourgeon told a news conference  
that a partnership either with Delta Airlines or Continental 
Airlines would form the backbone of the alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	Air France currently has code sharing agreements with  
Continental and Delta, enabling them to coordinate flight schedules 
with Air France, and Gourgeon said he hoped to maintain the 
agreement with the airline that did not enter the alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	The alliance could include other airlines as well, but Gourgeon  
said it would not exceed 10 companies. It will likely include 
another European airline, said Jean-Cyril Spinetta, the chairman of 
Air France. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline's profit fell to 249 million euros, or $239 million,  
in the year ended March 31 from 280 million euros a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue for the year rose to 9.1 billion euros, or $8.75  
billion, from 8.97 billion euros the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	A 10-day strike by Air France pilots last June just as the World  
Cup was getting underway cost the airline an estimated $32.3 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Cargo revenues fell 12 percent and its cargo unit posted a net  
loss for the full year. 
</P>
<P>
	The French government announced in January it would sell part of  
Air France, eventually reducing the state share in the airline to 
about 53 percent. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
