<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Against Euro, Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro fell yet again to a new low Thursday,  
reflecting continued disappointment with European economic 
fundamentals and unease about the realistic possibility of peace in 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar edged higher against the Japanese yen on revived  
speculation that China would devalue its currency. The yuan has 
remained the stable currency of the region during two years of 
financial turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro fell to $1.0343 from $1.0355  
Wednesday and a decrease of more than 11 percent since the euro was 
launched in January. During the trading day, the euro fell as low 
as $1.0303. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose to 121.66 yen from 121.33 yen  
</P>
<P>
	Traders sold euros and bought dollars Thursday as they wondered  
whether peace had truly arrived in Yugoslavia even after Slobodan 
Milosevic agreed to NATO demands and the withdrawal of Serb troops 
from Kosovo. Some 850,000 ethnic Albanian refugees were to be 
allowed back home. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO, meanwhile, will continue its bombing of Yugoslavia because  
President Clinton said he wanted clear confirmation the Serbs fully 
accepted NATO's terms. The airstrikes began at the end of March. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar, meanwhile, has risen against the euro fairly  
steadily since its January launch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just part of the same grinding bearish trend we've seen  
since right after the kickoff,'' said Jordan Rosner, chief 
economist at Optima Investment Research in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro's lackluster performance is largely attributable to  
Europe's stagnant economy, especially when compared with the 
soaring economy in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, interest rates in the United States are more  
attractive than those in the euro zone and the Federal Reserve has 
indicated it's likely to raise them more. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors are going to put their money where they can get the  
best return on it,'' Rosner said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other late New York trading, the dollar rose to 1.5402 Swiss  
francs from 1.5373, but fell to 1.4759 Canadian dollars from 
1.4799. The British pound rose to $1.6064 from $1.6041. 
</P>
<P>
	The currencies of the 11 countries that have switched to the  
euro no longer are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a 
fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth:  
1.8911 German marks, up from 1.8889; 6.3412 French francs, up from 
6.3331; and 1,876.17 Italian lire, up from 1,869.16. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
