<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 23:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sprinters Coast Into NCAA Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Leigh Daniel of Texas Tech was a shoe-in  
once she got her shoe on. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last event at the NCAA track championships Wednesday  
night, Daniel started the women's 10,000 meters as the prerace 
favorite. But in the second lap, somebody stepped on the back of 
her shoe, and it came loose. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to hold on to it with my toes, but decided that wasn't  
going to work in such a long race,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She stopped and tried to tug it back on, but finally had to  
reach down and retie the shoe. When she started again, the race 
leaders were half a lap ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was confident I could catch up,'' she said. ``I knew it was  
possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few laps later, she rejoined the leaders. She took the lead at  
the start of the next-to-last lap and won going away in 34 minutes, 
1.63 seconds. Daniel, the NCAA indoor 5,000 meter champion, will 
try for a double in that event Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be lying down a lot between now and then,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The four-day meet continues tonight at Boise State University  
with 12 finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Heading into tonight's competition, Southern Methodist was first  
among the women with 20 points, followed by UCLA with 12, 
Pittsburgh and Kansas State with 10 each and Southern California 
with 9. Defending champion Texas had just four points after two 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford, which finished 1-2-3 in Wednesday's 10,000 meter race,  
continued to lead the men with the 24 points won in that race. The 
Cardinal were in good shape to pick up more points with a strong 
contingent in tonight's 5,000 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	Auburn was second with 13 points, followed by seven-time  
defending champion Arkansas, Tennessee, Southern Methodist and 
Kansas State with 10 points each. Indiana State have eight points, 
with Northern Arizona, Mississippi and California having six each. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's top collegiate sprinters mostly coasted into  
tonight's semifinals. Nanceen Perry of Texas and Louisiana State's 
Peta-Gaye Dowdie had the best times, 11.19 seconds, but some of the 
other top competitors said they took it easy. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to run smart races,'' said Southern Cal's Angela  
Williams, a freshman who easily moved into the semifinals with 
teammate Torri Edwards. ``You've got to believe you can make it to 
the next level. That's what we're here for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kaaron Conwright of Cal Poly-San Luis had the best qualifying  
time among the men, 10.12 seconds. Defending champion Leonard 
Myles-Mills of Brigham Young finished third in his heat and moved 
into the semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida's John Capel, who won the third heat, had an easy time,  
winning in a slow 10.31. 
</P>
<P>
	``My coach told me to blast out the first 60 (meters) and relax  
the rest of the race. That's what I did,'' Capel said. ``Don't try 
to kill yourself (in the first round). I can go a lot faster than 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Melvin Lister of Arkansas won a controversy-filled long jump.  
Frankie Young of Indiana State had the same distance, 26 feet 10 
inches, but Lister's last jump was better than Young's second-best 
effort, so he was declared the winner. But there was a delay before 
the event was decided. 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi's Savante Stringfellow was disqualified for bad  
sportsmanship, but after an appeal, he was reinstated. That allowed 
him to complete his last three jumps after the other competitors 
were finished. He finished third. 
</P>
<P>
	Lister's victory continued a long tradition for the Razorbacks.  
Since 1984, Arkansas has won eight long jump titles and 11 triple 
jump crowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee's Tom Pappas won the decathlon with 8,184 points,  
winning four of the 10 events. 
</P>
<P>
	Southern Methodist's Kajsa Bergqvist won the women's high jump  
at 6-2 3/4, and UCLA's Sua Seilalu won the shot put at 57 feet, 9 
inches. She qualified in four throwing events, but decided to skip 
the hammer and javelin and concentrate on the discus and shot put. 
She will try for a double in the discus Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why not go for a sure 20 points for my team when I know I can  
win the shot put and the discus,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
