<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Electrical Workers OK New Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASCAGOULA, Miss. (AP) -- Striking electrical workers approved a  
new contract Thursday with Ingalls Shipbuilding, a major 
shipbuilder for the Navy and Mississippi's largest private 
employer. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 733  
approved the contract by more than 50 votes -- a step that may end a 
nearly month-long strike at Ingalls. 
</P>
<P>
	Local 733, which represents about 1,200 of Ingalls's 11,500  
workers, is the first of 11 striking unions to ratify the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Metal Trades Council, which represents 6,500 workers, will  
conduct voting Friday. Two other unions representing Ingalls 
employees accepted a contract earlier this month, before some 7,000 
workers went on strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Local 733 leaders said the new contract offers improvements to  
pay scales and insurance costs that had doomed a deal last month. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a good package,'' said Chico McGill, business manager for  
the Electrical Workers. 
</P>
<P>
	McGill said the new 45-month package offers increased  
journeyman's wages of $1 per hour for the first 14 months; 60 cents 
per hour for 15 months and 70 cents per hour for 16 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous package offered raises of 93 cents an hour the  
first year; 50 cents per hour the second year and 47 cents an hour 
the third. It also called for $10 annual increases in employee-paid 
health insurance premiums. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the pending agreement, McGill said insurance rates will  
increase by $5 in each of the three years. 
</P>
<P>
	An attendance bonus also will be extended into the new contract,  
McGill said. Workers will receive 37 cents per hour if they work 
the 40-day period (40 hours a week) without missing time. 
</P>
<P>
	``This equates to a 16.3 percent wage increase over the life of  
the contract,'' McGill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingalls, a builder of Navy destroyers, is a division of Litton  
Industries, which controls a number of aerospace, defense and 
electronics businesses. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
