<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 03:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lukas Ready for Triple Crown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In his Hall of Fame career, D. Wayne Lukas has  
trained 18 Eclipse Award winners, won 13 Breeders' Cup races and 
saddled the winners of four Kentucky Derbies and five Preakness 
Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	He also won three Belmont Stakes in a row, from 1994-96, and  
that experience could work to his advantage on Saturday, when he 
sends out Charismatic in his bid to become only the 12th horse in 
history to sweep the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first couple of times I tried it, I came away very, very  
humbled and very, very distressed over the Belmont Stakes,'' said 
Lukas, whose first Belmont starter, Preakness winner Codex, 
finished seventh in the 1 1/2-mile race in 1980. ``And then we had a 
little bit of success with it, but ironically, the three times we 
won it, we won it with three different horses with three different 
characteristics. There's no how-to manual -- it's a constant 
learning process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The same might be said of Lukas' handling of Charismatic, who  
along with the trainer arrived at Belmont Park on Wednesday from 
Louisville. Charismatic, who won the Derby at odds of 31-1 and the 
Preakness at 8-1, was made the 2-1 morning-line favorite and drew 
post No. 4 under Chris Antley for the $1 million Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	A winner of only one race in his first nine starts, the  
well-bred, high-priced Charismatic so befuddled Lukas that the 
trainer twice risked losing him by sending him out in claiming 
races. 
</P>
<P>
	In the middle of February, Lukas changed tactics with the big  
colt and began working him hard and shortening up the time between 
his races. He finished second in an allowance on Feb. 19, second in 
the El Camino Real Derby two weeks later and then a respectable 
fourth in the Santa Anita Derby on April 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Santa Anita race was not conducive to Charismatic's  
success,'' said Lukas, who has saddled 14 starters in the Belmont 
since 1980. ``But the three he just won (the April 18 Coolmore 
Lexington, the Derby and the Preakness) and this one, the Belmont, 
are a much better fit. He's a horse that has responded at every 
turn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With a break of 21 days since the Preakness, it will be the  
first time since the Santa Anita Derby that Charismatic has not 
raced back in two weeks, but Lukas remained confident in the colt's 
ability to handle the final leg of the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not a very good work horse, but he responded well  
yesterday, so we're back in the race here,'' said Lukas, referring 
to Charismatic's 5-furlong work of 1:00 4-5 at Churchill Downs on 
Tuesday. ``One of the things you have to like about going into this 
race is that the horse would have the bounce-back ability -- go to 
the Derby, come back and run a big one in the Preakness, and 
hopefully have one more left.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That would give Lukas the one prize that has eluded him -- the  
Triple Crown, last won in 1978 by Affirmed. In all, 25 horses have 
headed into the Belmont with a chance to win racing's most coveted 
trophy, and only 11 have succeeded. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic heads into the Belmont as the favorite in a 12-horse  
field that includes Derby and Preakness runner-up Menifee (7-2), 
the Bob Baffert-trained filly Silverbulletday (4-1), and Best of 
Luck (6-1), who won the Peter Pan Stakes for trainer Allen Jerkens 
with an impressive late rush in his last start. 
</P>
<P>
	Also entered Wednesday were the Nick Zito-trained duo of Stephen  
Got Even (10-1) and Adonis (20-1), Lemon Drop Kid (20-1), Vision 
and Verse (20-1), Patience Game (20-1), Pineaff (30-1), Prime 
Directive (30-1) and Teletable (99-1). 
</P>
<P>
	It's the second biggest field in a Belmont with a Triple Crown  
on the line. In 1971, Pass Catcher denied Canonero II the Triple 
Crown in a 13-horse field. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lukas, along with owners Bob and Beverly Lewis, say they are  
delighted with a full field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not being cocky, but I hope everybody that has a Belmont  
horse is ready to run,'' Lukas, wearing his trademark white cowboy 
hat, said, ``so on Sunday morning, when they all talk about this, 
whether it's us, or somebody else (winning), we'll know who the 
best horse was on that day at a mile-and-a half.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tabasco Cat gave Lukas his first Belmont win in 1994, and the  
trainer followed up wins from Thunder Gulch and Editor's Note. If 
Charismatic wins the Belmont and the Triple Crown, the Lewises 
would also get a $5 million bonus from series sponsor VISA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Charismatic's had three great runs for us and we're delighted  
to get this far,'' Lukas said. ``If we can get one more, we'll be 
very happy, and if we don't we'll still be happy.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
