<DOCNO> APW19990603.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 14:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert Downplays Lukas Rivalry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bob Baffert does not warm to the task easily.  
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, he lost a $5 million bonus by the length of a  
thoroughbred's nose. The year before, he left the same $5 million 
on the table when his horse came up four strides short of winning 
the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``How would I feel watching someone else walk off with one?''  
Baffert repeated. 
</P>
<P>
	Pause.  
</P>
<P>
	Bloodshot eyes flicker behind the trademark amber shades, the  
result of allergies or revelry. Baffert does not say. He climbed 
out of a car at 9:40 a.m., several hours after everybody else in 
the training fraternity arrived, and threw the session open to 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	This question, though, is tough, and made tougher still because  
the ``someone else'' in this case -- the only someone who can win 
the Belmont and a Triple Crown this year -- is ubertrainer D. Wayne 
Lukas, whose rivalry with Baffert is the biggest the sport can 
muster. 
</P>
<P>
	They bid on the same yearlings, court the same owners, covet the  
same prizes. Between 1994 and 1996, Lukas won six Triple Crown 
races in a row, though he failed to sweep the Kentucky Derby, 
Preakness and Belmont in the same year with the same horse. The 
last two years, it was Baffert who came to New York with a shot at 
the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the shoe is back on Lukas' foot. So Baffert struggles to say  
something kind, or even better, something neutral. This is what 
comes out: 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think of it that way. Win, lose or draw, believe me  
Wayne will be glad when it's over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is no question which of those fates Baffert would wish for  
Lukas and his brilliant colt, Charismatic. Indeed, some people 
think Baffert is so desperate to stop his archrival that he is 
risking his equally brilliant filly, Silverbulletday, by throwing 
her in with the boys. 
</P>
<P>
	He ran a pair of colts and his other filly, Excellent Meeting,  
against Lukas' two horses in the Kentucky Derby and got whipped. He 
brought Excellent Meeting back for the Preakness and she developed 
a breathing problem before being eased on the backstretch. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert entered and then scratched Silverbulletday from both  
those races. But if he has any lingering concerns, bravado 
steamrolls them now. 
</P>
<P>
	``All her times have been faster than the colts. We had to wait  
for the right time,'' he said, ``and this is the right time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas has been lashed in the past -- sometimes unfairly -- for  
pushing horses to the limit and beyond. Two days earlier, he 
forcefully reminded some reporters what would have happened if he 
and Baffert's roles had been reversed -- if he'd been the trainer 
with one promising filly eased in the Preakness and a second 
pressed into service in the toughest of spring classics as a 
spoiler. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lukas didn't bring it up again Thursday, when an air of  
civility as thick as the early summer haze hung over Belmont's 
barns. With the race little more than 48 hours off, it wasn't just 
the horses who refused to talk trash. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like the Knicks and Miami, with Van Gundy and Riley  
going at it,'' said Lukas, who coached basketball before he turned 
to horses. ``It's not just the two of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas and Baffert came up through the thoroughbred ranks when  
deans like Charlie Whittingham and Woody Stephens took the measure 
of one another in the newspapers almost daily. Back then, a 
well-timed barb could make a rival chafe just as much as sticking a 
burr under the saddle of his mount. And Lukas was a frequent 
target. 
</P>
<P>
	They were amused because he had grooms manicure the grounds  
around his stable and insisted the bridles and buckets and blankets 
be stacked just so. They had fun with the creases in his jeans and 
the starch in his manner. He was already racing's organization man 
and his desire to win was so raw that Stephens and Whittingham 
never lacked for material with which to taunt him. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert is 18 years Lukas' junior and the funnier of the two.  
They have little in common, but as the rivalry deepened, Baffert 
began to value Lukas more as a foe than a foil. 
</P>
<P>
	Both started in the quarterhorse racket, learning to make do  
with a shoestring budget. Both learned to spot talent in a 
heartbeat and get it for a song. Both learned to break the horses 
themselves in order to train them. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that both have the best of everything and all the help they  
need, they need each other as a way to measure how far they have 
come. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have respect for each other,'' Baffert said. ``Even though  
we're not great friends, we know when we run against each other 
that we have to be ready. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
