<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Open Fans Must Endure Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Tennis fans haven't let a citywide transport strike  
stop them from seeing action at the French Open. 
</P>
<P>
	They've hitched rides, endured traffic jams and reached the  
stadium on foot, rollerblades or bicycyle. 
</P>
<P>
	Paris transport workers walked off the job Wednesday following  
erroneous reports that a ticket inspector died after being attacked 
by thugs. 
</P>
<P>
	But most Metro lines were running with partial service by  
mid-afternoon after officials announced that the ticket inspector 
died of natural causes, not a violent attack. 
</P>
<P>
	With no warning of the strike, French Open organizers said they  
were unable to provide extra buses or parking facilities for 
spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	The impact was evident around the stadium in western Paris, with  
heavy traffic and scores of bikes chained up outside the courts. 
</P>
<P>
	With taxis almost impossible to find, some fans resorted to  
rollerblading or jogging to catch a piece of the action. 
</P>
<P>
	But attendance figures haven't been impacted.  
</P>
<P>
	Tournament organizers said that 17,217 spectators showed up on  
Wednesday, just 273 fewer than on the same day last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ian Nash, a tennis coach from London visiting Roland Garros with  
his wife, rides from sympathetic Parisians. 
</P>
<P>
	``On Wednesday, I knocked on a car window and the driver dropped  
me about a five minutes walk from the courts,'' said Nash, who is 
staying at a hotel five miles across town. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, I carried a sign with `Roland Garros' written on it and  
got a lift after ten minutes,'' he said. ``I can't believe how 
friendly and helpful people have been. I don't think that would 
ever happen in London.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others have put up with heavy delays.  
</P>
<P>
	Michel Bernadeau, a sales account manager from Paris, treated  
his 11-year-old daughter Nathalie to a visit to the women's 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	It took him more than an hour for a drive what would normally  
take 15 minutes, but he has no regrets. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first time I've got tickets for Roland Garros, so  
it was worth it,'' he said. ``Anyway I had no choice because my 
daughter is the No. 1 fan of Martina Hingis.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
