<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> College Choir Helps at Crash Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- There were shoves and cries of fear on  
American Airlines Flight 1420 as frantic passengers clambered to 
get out of the burning plane and into the stormy night. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was also selflessness at the terrifying scene. Choir  
members from an Arkansas college have emerged as heroes, risking 
their lives to make sure fellow passengers made it out of the 
flaming, smoke-filled wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the Ouachita Singers, a choir from Ouachita Baptist  
University in Arkadelphia, went back into the aircraft to retrieve 
the elderly and the injured. They also guided others to safety and 
told rescuers about those who needed help. 
</P>
<P>
	``They pulled off their shirts and covered the injured,'' said  
Arnold Bowden, a 63-year-old retired real estate dealer from 
Russellville who was on the flight. ``I never saw people so kind 
and so helpful to each other as they were in this disaster.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nine of the 145 people aboard were were killed in Tuesday's  
crash after the plane slid off a runway during a powerful storm and 
was torn apart by a light tower. The jet ended up only yards from 
the Arkansas River. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 25 people traveling in the choir party, one was presumed  
dead Wednesday night and two were in critical condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The choir was returning from a two-week trip to Europe, where  
members entertained German school children and Kosovo refugees in 
Austria. They had planned to tour China, but rescheduled after the 
NATO bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade forced a 
cancellation. 
</P>
<P>
	After a stopover in Dallas, the Ouachita party boarded Flight  
1420 to Little Rock. 
</P>
<P>
	Ouachita senior Luke Hollingsworth remembers seats collapsing  
and a black smoke that filled the cabin. He and several others 
escaped through a rip in the tail section and began pulling people 
out after them. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollingsworth went back to the cockpit to check on the pilots.  
</P>
<P>
	``The pilot was dead,'' said Hollingsworth, 21. ``The co-pilot,  
he was alive. He was talking to us. He asked, `Is the pilot dead?' 
and I said, `Yeah, he's dead.' 
</P>
<P>
	``He was calm. From the waist up, he was OK, but his legs looked  
like they were broken, crushed up pretty bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tad Hardin found Kristin Maddox, 22, of Ponca City, Okla. -- a  
bridesmaid at his June 12 wedding -- leaning against the bumper of a 
fire truck. Blackened skin was peeling from her face and hands, and 
Hardin lost no time shepherding her to an ambulance. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though there were professionals on the scene, we realized  
they were just as confused as we were,'' Hardin said. ``On foot, we 
were pretty much equal ... out there in the rain and the hail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hardin said he was inspired by watching choir director Charles  
Fuller, whose own 14-year-old daughter Rachel was critically burned 
in the crash, guiding passengers onto the wing of the plane. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't so much that I could see him, but I heard his voice  
and I saw his silhouette and I knew that if he was there things 
were going to he handled smoothly and orderly, and he wasn't going 
to leave until everyone was out of there,'' Hardin said. ``He 
didn't even know where his own children were and he was right there 
helping total strangers. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was really being the father for all of us.''  
</P>
<P>
	Hollingsworth, a 6-foot-2 fullback on the school football team,  
carried a woman with a broken pelvis through the river's backwater 
on his shoulders. Before he left her in the triage area, he gave 
her his shirt. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's all I had,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Dave Ozmun, an assistant mass communications professor who was  
along to videotape the choir's tour, lost his glasses and had to 
listen for voices as he led people out of the billowing smoke. He 
said he was very proud of his students. 
</P>
<P>
	``All through the trip -- and certainly last night -- I saw a  
level of maturity and courage and strength,'' Ozmun said Wednesday. 
``I didn't hear people screaming. I knew that they would not only 
be able to take care of themselves, but they would be able to take 
care of others too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The singers said their faith helped them, and Hardin said the  
words of the 91st Psalm echoed in his head during the rescue: 
``Thou shalt not be afraid for the terror by night.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITORS NOTE: Allen G. Breed is the AP's Southeast regional  
writer, based in Raleigh, N.C. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
