<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Moves Closer to N.Y. Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton intends to form an  
exploratory committee in early July, preparing her for a potential 
Senate campaign in New York next year, a top adviser said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	She would be the first sitting first lady to run for public  
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Harold Ickes, who is heading up Mrs. Clinton's political  
operation, disclosed the plans after Rep. Nita Lowey said, in a 
telephone call to the first lady, that she would seek re-election 
to the House. That move leaves the Democratic field clear for Mrs. 
Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told her it seemed clear she was running ... I wished her  
well,'' said Lowey, who also had been eyeing the Senate race. ``I 
told her I would support her enthusiastically.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, Mrs. Clinton said, ``I thank Nita for her  
support and I look forward to working with her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no mention of her own plans.  
</P>
<P>
	Lowey said she did not ask Mrs. Clinton if she would seek the  
seat being vacated by retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. ``It's 
clear to me she was running and it was time for me to move on,'' 
the congresswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about Mrs. Clinton's conversation with Lowey, Ickes said,  
``I think you can discern that Hillary is going to press forward 
and she will be forming an exploratory committee in early July and 
just keep moving forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a subsequent conversation, Ickes, a former deputy White House  
chief of staff, said he meant to say that Mrs. Clinton intends to 
form a committee in July. 
</P>
<P>
	He cautioned that formation of a committee does not necessarily  
mean Mrs. Clinton will seek the seat. ``This is one step at a 
time,'' he said. ``The initial step forward is to form the 
exploratory committee and continue to talk to the people of New 
York.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton met Thursday with political mastermind James  
Carville. Asked whether they discussed the New York Senate race, 
Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said, ``They both have a 
love of politics, so it wouldn't surprise me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the exploratory committee, Berry said, ``We are not  
announcing an exploratory committee and the actions taken by 
Congresswoman Lowey today do not affect Mrs. Clinton's 
decision-making process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think exploring New York is a good thing. Maybe she should  
explore New York a little,'' New York Mayor Rudloph Giuliani 
quipped to reporters when told of Ickes' remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani formed his own exploratory committee six weeks ago in  
anticiapation of seeking the Republican nomination for Moynihan's 
seat in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Staying in Washington on Thursday after a campaign-like foray  
into New York City the previous day, Mrs. Clinton spoke at high 
school graduation and posed for Paris fashion photographer Michel 
Comte. The photo shoot was for an upcoming cover story in Talk 
magazine, the latest project of Tina Brown, the former editor of 
The New Yorker. 
</P>
<P>
	Advisers have said for days that Mrs. Clinton intended to form  
an exploratory committee, but Ickes was the first to say it on the 
record. Advisers also have said it would require a major change of 
heart for Mrs. Clinton to decide against a campaign after forming 
the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Formation of an exploratory committee will allow Mrs. Clinton to  
begin raising money. That means she can begin paying for some of 
her travel to New York, for polling and other campaign expenses. 
She already has come under fire for making campaign-style trips to 
New York at taxpayer expense. 
</P>
<P>
	Judith Hope, the state's Democratic Party chairwoman, said that  
while she was disappointed to lose Lowey as a potential statewide 
candidate for next year, ``I'm happy we have a united Democratic 
Party in New York, unlike the Republicans who seem to be split into 
two or three separate camps.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
