<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dolphins' Burton Faces Jail Over DUI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAVIE, Fla. (AP) -- Miami Dolphins defensive lineman Shane Burton  
already has a 2-year-old drunken driving conviction on his record, 
meaning he could get jail time if convicted again for a similar 
arrest last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida Motor Vehicle Department records show Burton was  
arrested for driving under the influence in North Carolina on Dec. 
27, 1996. He was convicted the following April. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Florida law, a second DUI conviction within five years  
brings a mandatory jail term of between 10 days and nine months. He 
also would face a fine of between $500 and $1,000, and up to a 
year's probation. 
</P>
<P>
	The 25-year-old lineman was arrested by Davie police May 9 after  
driving his Lexus east in the westbound lanes of State Road 84 
around 6:30 a.m., according to a Florida Highway Patrol arrest 
report. The car's emergency flashers were on. 
</P>
<P>
	His blood alcohol level was .106, according to the arrest  
report. The legal limit in Florida is .08. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton, attorney Adam Swickle and agent Drew Rosenhaus have  
refused comment on the case. 
</P>
<P>
	League and team officials apparently were not aware of Burton's  
previous conviction, even though it came near the end of Burton's 
rookie season. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as the league is concerned, Burton has one DUI, and  
it's (the May 9 arrest),'' Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton will have to undergo an evaluation as part of the NFL's  
substance-abuse program. League spokesman Greg Aiello indicated a 
previous conviction could impact those results. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prior history would be factored in terms of both  
substance-abuse program and possible fines,'' said Aiello, who 
would not comment on Burton specifically, citing confidentiality 
rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton played as a reserve in 15 games last year, finishing with  
23 tackles, two sacks and one fumble recovery. The 6-foot-4, 
300-pound lineman was the Dolphins' fifth-round draft pick out of 
Tennessee in 1996. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
