<HEADLINE> Chargers Unhappy With Leaf's Absence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The San Diego Chargers are a little upset that  
quarterback Ryan Leaf prefers to be at a charity golf tournament in 
New Jersey instead of at the team's minicamp. 
</P>
<P>
	While these workouts are voluntary, the Chargers made it clear  
that Leaf should be here, what with his horrendous play as a rookie 
and because new coach Mike Riley continues to put in his offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very disappointing,'' general manager Bobby Beathard  
said. ``We'd love for him to be here. He needs it as much as 
anybody. We just hope he wants to play football as badly as we want 
him to play football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Riley said Leaf told him several weeks ago that he would have a  
conflict due to a charity event, but the coach was under the 
impression it would be for just one day. Riley doesn't expect Leaf 
here until Monday, meaning he will have missed three days of what 
the Chargers call ``summer school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After his round Thursday in the NFL Golf Classic, Leaf was asked  
if he had spoken with Riley about his absence, but he basically 
evaded the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we had practice yesterday and today and tomorrow and  
we had the schedule for about a month or so,'' Leaf said. ``But we 
have a summer school next week, too, and I'll be back for that.'' 
  	   	
</P>
