<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philly Waits on GOP Convention Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Wendy Rosen is tired of waiting for the  
Republicans to decide where in Philadelphia they want to hold their 
presidential nominating convention. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Rosen, who produces trade shows for the wholesale craft  
industry, booked the glitzy Pennsylvania Convention Center in 
downtown Philadelphia for the week before the 2000 Republican 
National Convention. But she'll have to move her show to Atlantic 
City, N.J., if the Republicans select the convention center over 
the First Union Center, home of the city's professional basketball 
and hockey teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why are they putting all the rest of us in so much pain and  
agony? This is extremely selfish on their part,'' said Ms. Rosen, 
whose show draws 10,000 artists, craft stores and jewelers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Rosen is not the only one in limbo. If the Republicans pick  
the convention center, they could potentially displace the nation's 
largest municipal workers union and the second largest teachers 
union -- traditional Democratic supporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Sally Muravchik, director of conventions and meetings for the  
American Federation of Teachers, said she has confidence that a 
solution will be found. Ms. Muravchik wouldn't even entertain a 
scenario in which her group would have to switch dates or move. 
</P>
<P>
	The union plans to send 5,000 teachers to Philadelphia the week  
of July 2, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been dealing with Republicans for a long time. We can  
deal with them a little bit longer,'' said Ted Kirsch, president of 
the Philadelphia Federation of Teachers. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees  
is scheduled to meet in Philadelphia in late June that year. About 
7,000 people are expected at that convention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans have said they would need the convention center  
from about mid-June 2000. The convention is scheduled to begin in 
late July. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson expects to  
make a final decision on a site within the next few weeks after 
consulting with convention manager James ``Chip'' DiPaula. 
</P>
<P>
	Both prospective locations are appealing. The $522 million  
convention center, which opened in 1993, is within walking distance 
of major downtown hotels and attractions. The $210 million First 
Union Center, which opened in 1996, is larger and has 
state-of-the-art television production equipment and a superior 
sound system. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican spokesman Tim Fitzpatrick said the GOP ``wants to  
make the right decision for this convention and not a hasty 
decision. We feel it merits careful consideration because so many 
other things will be affected by it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are on schedule with our decision,'' Fitzpatrick said. ``We  
have been following the timetable that we laid out from the start. 
We're about six months ahead of where we were in preparations for 
the '96 convention in San Diego.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The convention center would require more preparation work:  
Skyboxes for broadcast media would have to be built, along with 
elevated seating. The First Union Center already has seating for 
21,000 people, 126 luxury suites and 13 club boxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP's lengthy decision-making process has forced at least  
two other groups to change plans.. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Bandy, president of the Trade Show Exhibitors  
Association, pulled out of Philadelphia this week. ``I think that 
the Republicans are doing a disservice to the city of Philadelphia 
by using their big stick, if you will,'' said Bandy, whose group 
will meet in Washington, D.C., instead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I might have to vote Democratic in the next election, and I've  
never done that,'' Bandy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Microscope Society of America had been booked for the same  
week of the Republican convention, but accepted a later date. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
