<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boston Sues Gun Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Accusing the gun industry of ``negligence,  
recklessness and greed,'' Mayor Thomas M. Menino announced the 
filing Thursday of a lawsuit against 31 companies accused of 
flooding the city's streets with guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, similar to a slew of litigation filed in other  
cities, said guns have created a public health problem. It accuses 
gunmakers of failing to incorporate all possible safety devices and 
unjustly making money from firearms flowing to people not 
authorized to own them. 
</P>
<P>
	The city is seeking more than $100 million in damages for  
police, fire and medical expenses caused by gun violence, as well 
as for increased security costs and declines in real estate values. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the companies named in the suit are Springfield-based  
Smith &AMP; Wesson Corp., Colt's Manufacturing Company Inc. of 
Hartford, Conn., and Browning Arms Corp. of Morgan, Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	``These lawsuits, they have no merit,'' said Travis Hall, a  
spokesman for Browning. ``Our industry is one of the most 
prohibited and monitored industries there is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said public officials should more rigorously enforce gun laws  
and not allow people accused of gun-related crimes to make plea 
bargain deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston joins 19 other cities, including Chicago and New Orleans,  
in filing suit against the gun industry. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
