<HEADLINE> Reds Send Belinda for Rehab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Relief pitcher Stan Belinda, sidelined since  
the spring because of biceps tendinitis, was sent to the Cincinnati 
Reds' Triple-A affiliate in Indianapolis on Thursday on a 
rehabilitation assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	The right-hander is being sent to Indianapolis to get in some  
work and there is no timetable for when Belinda might return to the 
Reds, team spokesman Mark Walpole said. 
</P>
<P>
	Belinda, 32, was placed on the disabled list March 24 with what  
was described as a strained right shoulder. He has not been 
activated this season, but has been throwing on the side. 
</P>
<P>
	Belinda's season was cut short in August last year because of  
inflammation in his spinal cord. In September, doctors went public 
with worse news, that Belinda was diagnosed in the early stages of 
multiple sclerosis. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors said he could resume his baseball career because the  
disease was detected early and could be treated aggressively to 
allow him to pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	His arm ailment is not believed to be related to the disease.  
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Belinda had a 4-8 record and 3.23 earned run average  
with one save in 40 relief appearances. 
  	   	
</P>
