<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 04:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Battle Continues on Florida Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSCEOLA NATIONAL FOREST, Fla. (AP) -- Add alligators to the  
hazards faced by those who are battling widespread wildfires here. 
</P>
<P>
	Mac McCarthy was one of 600 firefighters Wednesday helping  
contain a fire that has burned 64,000 acres in the Osceola National 
Forest, the Okefenokee Swamp and private timber lands. 
</P>
<P>
	``It got pretty scary last night,'' said McCarthy, 23. ``We had  
to go through the swamp and put out some fires. There were several 
alligators, about 3 or 4 feet. I kept an eye on them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCarthy, 23, from Anadarko, Okla., is a Kiowa Indian, from one  
of several American Indian tribes that have sent crews. The Navajo, 
Creek, Cherokee, Kiowa, Arapaho and Chickasaw also have 
firefighters on the lines. 
</P>
<P>
	The blaze, dubbed the Friendly Fire by firefighters, started as  
a lightning strike on May 21 in the Osceola National Forest, 
between Lake City and Jacksonville. There have been no serious 
injuries or structures burned. 
</P>
<P>
	Containment lines have been established around the fire south of  
Florida Highway 2 and appeared to be holding, said Mike Melton, the 
incident commander for the U.S. Forest Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The fire continues to burn in a northerly direction through the  
Okefenokee Swamp on the Florida-Georgia line. 
</P>
<P>
	``This fire is not going away for a long time until it rains,''  
Melton said. ``We are in for the long haul.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCarthy, who has the Kiowa tribal shield painted on the side of  
his truck, said he enjoys the work. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope we can be here for a while because I'm making good  
money,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
