<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lockheed To Cut Up to 2,000 Ga. Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) -- Lockheed Martin Corp. will cut up to 2,000  
more jobs at its Marietta plant so the defense contractor can offer 
cheaper planes. 
</P>
<P>
	While 40 percent of the job cuts will come through early  
retirement, attrition and transfers, the bulk of the cuts -- about 
1,200 jobs -- will be layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is necessary to make us competitive for future  
business,'' said Tom Burbage, who became president of the Marietta 
plant in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuts, which will shave the plant's total workforce of 9,550  
by about 20 percent, are part of an overall streamlining strategy. 
</P>
<P>
	While demand for the plant's major product -- the $60 million  
C-130J military transport plane -- is adequate, Burbage said the 
downsizing is necessary for the plant to compete for future 
contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that we need to streamline our operation and make  
our organization more effective,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to its C-130J production, it is the lead developer  
of the F-22 stealth fighter jet. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Georgia's congressional delegation have been pushing  
for increased Air Force orders for the C-130J, for which orders 
have slowed. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant lost a powerful advocate this year when former House  
Speaker Newt Gingrich, whose district included Marietta, resigned 
from Congress. But Burbage said the current congressional 
delegation is doing ``a fine job'' in helping the company. 
</P>
<P>
	``The products themselves are really what makes you a success or  
failure,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant, which laid off 280 workers in January, had as many as  
32,000 employees in Marietta, northwest of Atlanta, in the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Lockheed Martin were down $1 to $40.50 in trading on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
