<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Snooping a Part of Horse Claiming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Doug Peterson is part snoop, part  
detective and a good bluffer, all necessary qualities to 
successfully play horse racing's claiming game. 
</P>
<P>
	He's lucky, too.  
</P>
<P>
	The trainer claimed a rundown-looking horse for $25,000, fixed  
its bad teeth, trimmed its overgrown hair, medicated its ulcers and 
helped it gain weight. Now the horse is good enough to run in a 
$125,000 stakes race this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Not exactly Charismatic, a one-time $62,500 claimer who will run  
for the Triple Crown on Saturday, but good enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``Claiming horses is kind of like going through trash cans,''  
trainer Mel Stute said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainers never know if they'll find a gem like Charismatic or a  
horse on its last legs. 
</P>
<P>
	Turnover is constant, with horses moving in and out of trainers'  
barns and changing owners as frequently as every 25 days, making 
them the equivalent of leased vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're like buses, they just keep coming,'' said Peterson,  
who trained Seattle Slew after the colt won the Triple Crown in 
1977. 
</P>
<P>
	In a claiming race, any licensed owner or trainer with enough  
credit or cash can buy a horse for a predetermined price. Horses in 
claiming races usually aren't fast enough to run in stakes races or 
compete in allowance races against well-bred horses on their way 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	Prospective buyers line the fence around the paddock before a  
race to check out the horses, then fill out a claim card and drop 
it in a box in the steward's office 16 minutes prior to post. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very secretive,'' Peterson said. ``I don't want them to  
scratch their horse if they get wind early enough, and I don't want 
somebody else taking my idea and following me to the claim box and 
putting in a claim also.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the horse's name is misspelled or the claiming price is  
incorrect, the card is voided. Otherwise, a buyer is obligated once 
the gates open. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the horse breaks down during the race, it's your horse,''  
said Jim Miller, paymaster at Hollywood Park. ``It's a shame, but 
that's the brutal reality of the business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Every trainer can recall his greatest claims, like the horse  
Stute paid $32,000 for that went on to win more than $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	But for every good claim, there are costly ones.  
</P>
<P>
	Peterson claimed a horse for $80,000 last summer. The horse won  
easily, but took a bad step and broke down after the race. The 
owner was out his investment and Peterson had a useless horse. 
That's why he carries insurance to recoup some of his costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainers also can get lucky on a potentially bad deal.  
</P>
<P>
	When two or more trainers want to claim the same horse, numbered  
peas are assigned to each trainer. The clerk of scales puts them in 
a shaker and the first number to fall out wins the horse. 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson recently put in claims for two fillies in the same  
race, one of which won. But he lost her in a shake and ended up 
with the other filly. 
</P>
<P>
	A good thing, since the winner ended up with a bowed tendon and  
may not race again. 
</P>
<P>
	Like used car salesmen, trainers who want to unload a horse  
because it's injured or running poorly will repackage their 
product. Or they'll disguise a good horse because they don't want 
to lose it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the closet thing to a poker game that I've ever seen,''  
said Mike Mitchell, a veteran trainer of claimers. ``You're holding 
a certain hand and you're bluffing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson admits to putting bandages on the legs of a perfectly  
sound horse, leaving paddock-watchers to wonder about a possible 
injury. Other trainers will stuff cotton inside a bandage to create 
the look of a bowed tendon, a worrisome sight to buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes, Peterson's tricks confuse his owners.  
</P>
<P>
	``The owner will say, `Was there something wrong with that  
horse?' I'll say, `No, just playing the game,''' he said, smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	But trainers never want to be too deceptive.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you burn people with horses, they're not going to come back  
too often and you've got less people claiming from you,'' Peterson 
said. ``It makes it harder to play the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Snooping is a big part of claiming.  
</P>
<P>
	At 5 a.m., clockers are scattered around the Hollywood Park  
grandstand, timing horses and watching how they gallop. The 
clockers, hired privately, tip off owners and trainers on horses to 
claim later that day. 
</P>
<P>
	Gossip spreads the word, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``One guy from another barn might try to talk to a groom in my  
barn and find out if I like the horse or not,'' Peterson said. ``At 
the same time, if a horse is going bad, I don't want it to get out 
in case I want to lose the horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Claiming races at Hollywood Park range from $8,000 to $100,000,  
and usually comprise half of an eight-race card. If a trainer runs 
a horse in a $50,000 race, then drops it to a $10,000 race the next 
time, it's a sign he's looking to unload. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the ones you have to be careful of,'' Stute said.  
</P>
<P>
	Stute, 71, briefly considered buying Charismatic both times the  
horse ran in claiming races last winter. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I would've claimed him, he'd have never run in the Kentucky  
Derby. I'd have been looking for some other kind of race,'' said 
Stute, who thought the price of $62,500 was too high. ``He was no 
gift.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No one claimed Charismatic, who went on to win the Derby and  
Preakness Stakes. A victory in Saturday's Belmont Stakes would make 
him the 12th Triple Crown winner in history. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are the things that the game needs, for people to see  
that this can happen,'' Peterson said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
