<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Florida Girl Wins Spelling Bee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nupur Lala bounced up and down and smiled in  
disbelief when she became this year's national spelling bee champ, 
her reward for spending two hours a day drilling words into her 
head. 
</P>
<P>
	The 14-year-old girl from Tampa, Fla., won today in the 12th  
round of the annual contest by correctly spelling ``logorrhea,'' 
which means incoherent talkativeness. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would look at lists of uncommon words and whenever I would  
miss a word, I would mark it,'' said Nupur, who has labored over 
words for the past few months, but also found time to play the 
violin, swim and surf the Internet. ``I would keep on re-quizzing 
until all the words were just drummed into my head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She credited her success to that intensive studying and a little  
``divine intervention.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``My parents -- they would take turns quizzing me,'' said Nupur,  
an eighth-grader at Louis Benito Middle School in Tampa. ``When one 
got tired, the other would take over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Nupur was eliminated in the third round of the bee,  
tripped up by the word ``commination,'' which means the threat of 
punishment. But she proved she had mastered it by spelling it 
correctly at a question-and-answer session after becoming this 
year's champ. 
</P>
<P>
	Nupur beat David Lewandowski, another 14-year-old, from  
Schererville, Ind., who spelled 10 words correctly before missing 
``opsimath,'' a person who begins to learn late in life. He 
misspelled it as ``opsomath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The words were harder this year, especially in the first few  
rounds,'' said David, an eighth-grader at Forest Ridge Academy who 
finished 39th in last year's bee. ``I really didn't expect to make 
it as far.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 72nd annual Scripps Howard National Spelling Bee began  
Wednesday with 249 spellers, ranging in ages from 9 to 15. When the 
competition resumed today, 104 spellers were still in the running 
but they were steadily eliminated with the ding of a bell 
throughout the day. 
</P>
<P>
	All had their own spelling style. Nupur wrote imaginary words in  
the palm of her hand. David grabbed the microphone and didn't let 
go until he finished a word. Some contestants spelled with their 
hands in their pockets; others with hands clutched behind their 
backs. 
</P>
<P>
	George Abraham Thampy, 11, of Maryland Heights, Mo., who tied  
for third place with April DeGideo, 13, of Ambler, Pa., repeatedly 
pronounced each word before spelling it, his voice rising on the 
final syllable as if asking a question. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the words that tripped up young contestants in the final  
rounds: ``obtenebrate,'' ``revictualment,'' ``banns'' and 
``muumuu.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthew Ferrier, 14, of Stevensville, Mich., walked off the  
stage with his head down when he missed the word ``brouhaha,'' an 
uproar or confused medley of sounds. He stuck a ``g'' and ``h'' in 
the middle. 
</P>
<P>
	Dipal Shah, a 12-year-old from West New York, N.J., literally  
ran back to her seat after correctly spelling ``zolaesque,'' a term 
referring to the works and style of French novelist Emile Zola. But 
then she missed her next word ``pochette,'' a kit or pouch. 
</P>
<P>
	As winner, Nupur will get a $10,000 first-place cash prize, plus  
encyclopedias, two airline tickets and computer software. The 
contestants, most sponsored by their local newspapers, all won 
regional bees to qualify. David was sponsored by The Times of 
Munster, Ind., and Nupur was sponsored by The Tampa Tribune. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
