<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Down; Gold Also Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar fell against most major currencies in  
late European trading Thursday, and lost ground against the euro 
after hitting a record high against the single european currency in 
morning trading. Gold prices fell. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro dropped to $1.0340 in the morning compared with  
Wednesday's $1.0371, and climbed to $1.0387 in the afternoon before 
dropping back to $1.0350. 
</P>
<P>
	It traded as low as $1.0303 earlier in the session, its lowest  
level since it replaced the currencies of 11 European nations on 
Jan. 1. $1.0300 is a politically and psychologically important 
barrier for the euro -- the floor of a tight range with which German 
bankers say they feel comfortable. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Wednesday: 121.47 Japanese  
yen, up from 120.71; 1.5336 Swiss francs, down from 1.5338; 1.4784 
Canadian dollars, down from 1.4798. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6038, down from $1.6103.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar was worth 121.57 yen,  
while the euro was worth $1.0320 and the British pound was worth 
$1.6038. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth: 1.8830 German marks, down from 1.8859; 
6.3152 French francs, down from 6.3249; 2.1216 Dutch guilders, down 
from 2.1249; and 1,864.13 Italian lire, down from 1,867.00 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $265.40 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$266.20 on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $265.45, down from $265.95.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell $2.80 in Hong Kong to close at $264.55.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $4.96 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$4.99. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
