<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rivlin Resigns As No. 2 Fed Official  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Alice Rivlin, the No. 2 official at the  
Federal Reserve, announced today that she was resigning from the 
central bank after serving three years as its vice chairman. The 
unexpected resignation was announced in a brief statement by the 
Fed, which also released her resignation letter to President 
Clinton. In the letter, Rivlin said the resignation would be 
effective July 16. She said leaving the Fed would give her more 
time to spend as head of the Financial Assistance Authority for the 
District of Columbia, the group that is overseeing Washington's 
city government. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks End Mixed; Dow Up 85.80  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks closed higher today as strong  
sales at the nation's largest retailers reminded investors that 
economic growth isn't always bad news. The Dow Jones industrial 
average was up 85.80 at 10,663.69. Broader stock indicators were 
mixed, with the technology-dominated Nasdaq languishing throughout 
the session. The Nasdaq composite fell 23.84 to 2,408.57. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,663.69  + 85.80
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1597  Declines 1316  Unchgd  619
NYSE Volume:         696,016,880
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online106       - 4 1/8
S&AMP;P 500:         1299.54  + 4.73
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          775.94  +  4.71
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,408.57  - 23.84
Gold(final) -    $266.40    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Retailers Have a Good Month  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The raging U.S. economy encouraged Americans to  
go on a shopping spree in May, boosting sales at the nation's 
biggest retailers to better-than-expected levels for the fourth 
straight month. Discounters and specialty clothing stores fared 
best last month as consumers bought up everything from trendy capri 
pants from the Limited to new gardening equipment at Wal-Mart. 
Separately today, the Labor Department reported the number of 
Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits rose a slight 
4,000 to 305,000 last week, signaling that unemployment remains 
extremely low. But there are concerns that a sharp or prolonged 
decline on Wall Street, a rise in interest rates or signs of a 
slowing economy could cause Americans to curb their buying. 

</P>
<P>
	Factory Orders Drop 1.2 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP)) -- Evidence of an economic slowdown came today  
with a Commerce Department report that orders to American factories 
for manufactured goods fell 1.2 percent in April, reflecting a big 
drop in demand for aircraft and other transportation products. 
Additionally, Freddie Mac, the mortgage company, said that the 
average interest rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages hit its 
highest level in nearly two years, jumping to 7.41 percent from 
7.23 percent a week ago. 

</P>
<P>
	NYSE Delays Extending Trading Hours  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Stock Exchange will delay extending  
its trading hours until next year at the earliest, its chairman 
announced today. Richard Grasso said the board of the world's 
biggest stock exchange would wait to make sure stock traders 
smoothly handled two challenges -- the Year 2000 computer bug and 
the planned shift to reporting stock prices in decimals rather than 
fractions. The deadline for the move to decimals is at the end of 
the second quarter of 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Litton Agrees To Buy Avondale  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Litton Industries Inc. will buy Avondale  
Industries for $529 million after Newport News Shipbuilding 
declined to raise its offer for the shipbuilder. Litton also 
indicated today it plans to re-examine its offer to buy Newport 
News in light of potential government opposition. New Orleans-based 
Avondale had agreed earlier to merge with Newport News for $470 
million in stock. But Litton offered more in cash, ultimately 
enticing Avondale. 

</P>
<P>
	Fed Has Nest Egg For Any Y2K Crisis  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- The Federal Reserve has stockpiled $200  
billion as a cushion against Year 2000-related hysteria, enough to 
keep the nation's financial system afloat even if every adult in 
the nation withdraws $1,000 at year's end. The cash stockpile is 
just one of the many ways in which the Fed has prepared for the 
Year 2000 computer bug, according to Robert T. Parry, president of 
the Fed's San Francisco district, which covers nine Western states. 
While short-term, isolated disruptions are possible, Perry said, 
the public should have confidence that the financial infrastructure 
-- checks, automated tellers, credit and debit cards, direct 
deposits -- will run smoothly. 

</P>
<P>
	FDIC Gives Banks, Thrifts Y2K Orders  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. is  
requiring that banks and thrifts considered to be unprepared for 
the Year 2000 computer date change use a standard backup system for 
storing key deposit and loan data. The FDIC's board of directors 
proposed the new requirement and opened it to public comment for 30 
days, although it will take effect immediately. The rule is 
designed to ensure that bank customers will have quick access to 
their money in the event of Y2K problems. The new rule will apply 
to banks and thrifts with a less-than-satisfactory rating from the 
government for their Year 2000 readiness as of July 31. 

</P>
<P>
	Penny Shortages Reported  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A penny saved is a penny earned, but too  
many pennies saved is a big problem for the Federal Reserve Bank in 
Philadelphia. Some area stores have been asking customers to dig 
for exact change as their cash drawers have run short of pennies in 
recent weeks. Meanwhile, stores and banks have sharply increased 
their orders for pennies, though no one can point to a reason for a 
shortage except the accumulations that pile up on dressers, in jars 
and in piggy banks, Federal Reserve Bank spokesman Bob McCarthy 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	Profits Slip at Air France  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French national carrier Air France's profit fell 11  
percent in its latest fiscal year, hurt by a pilot strike and a 
slump in Asian cargo shipments. But it expects solid growth in 
operating results this year. Air France also said today that it 
will select a U.S. partner in the course of 1999 ``to create a 
global alliance'' although it offered few details on what kind of 
alliance it had in mind. Chief Executive Pierre-Henri Gourgeon said 
a partnership either with Delta Airlines or Continental Airlines 
would form the backbone of the alliance. 

</P>
<P>
	Vote on Plan PacBell Backs Delayed  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- State regulators postponed for a week a  
vote on a rate shift in Internet telephone charges, a proposal that 
could lead to higher fees for some Internet users in California. A 
plan pushed by Pacific Bell to shift connection fees for such calls 
to a smaller phone company, which could pass them along to Internet 
service providers, had been scheduled for a vote at today's Public 
Utilities Commission meeting. But the sponsor, Josiah Neeper, 
changed his proposal before the meeting so that it would require a 
full review and public comment before final PUC action, said 
Pacific Bell spokesman Bill Mashek. 

</P>
<P>
	Hot Dogs Blamed for Listeria Outbreak  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT, Mich. (AP) -- A federal investigation of a food  
poisoning outbreak that left 15 dead concludes the source was hot 
dogs from a Bil Mar meat plant, and recommends stronger steps 
against food-borne bacteria. The Centers for Disease Control report 
said the same rare strain of bacteria that caused the outbreak was 
found in packages of Bil Mar hot dogs made at the Zeeland plant. It 
said the bacteria was likely present in the plant five months 
before the outbreak began. But Jeffrey Smith, a spokesman for Bil 
Mar parent Sara Lee Corp., said the report ``indicates there is 
some uncertainty about the cause of the outbreak.'' He said the 
company was taking several steps to improve safety. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Factory orders: down 1.2 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: up 4,000 to 305,000  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Unemployment  

  	   	
</P>
