<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 13:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Local Police Ratings Vary by Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Blacks' dissatisfaction with police outstrips  
whites' by two-to-one or more in New York and Chicago and nearly 
that in a number of other cities, the government said Thursday in a 
report coming amid the controversy over ``racial profiling'' by 
police. 
</P>
<P>
	A survey of a dozen cities last year indicated that 24 percent  
of blacks were dissatisfied with local police compared with 10 
percent of whites, though the figures varied substantially by city. 
</P>
<P>
	Many black Americans clearly believe they are treated  
differently from whites, said Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder, 
who announced the results. 
</P>
<P>
	Calling the 24 percent black dissatisfaction figure ``too  
large,'' Holder said law enforcement agencies and all segments of 
communities must work together to break down ``the barriers of 
mistrust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, 85 percent of residents surveyed in 12 cities said they  
were satisfied with local police. Three percent said they were very 
dissatisfied and 12 percent said they were dissatisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	Hispanics were included as either black or white in the survey  
based on their individual preference. 
</P>
<P>
	In Chicago, 31 percent of blacks were dissatisfied with police,  
compared with 11 percent of whites. In New York, the figures were 
23 percent for blacks, 11 percent for whites. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the figures were closer together, 25 percent for  
blacks, 19 percent for whites. In Los Angeles, 18 percent of blacks 
were dissatisfied, compared with 11 percent of whites, according to 
the survey, which covered more than 9,000 households -- some 700 in 
each city. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest black-white difference was in Knoxville, Tenn.,  
where 37 percent of blacks said they were dissatisfied with police 
compared with 9 percent for whites. 
</P>
<P>
	Three black men died in confrontations with Knoxville police  
during a seven-month period in 1997, enraging the black community 
and leading Knoxville Mayor Victor Ashe to create a citizen panel 
to review complaints against officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's release of the survey by the Bureau of Justice  
Statistics came amid continuing controversy about police 
departments using racial profiling, the practice of stopping or 
searching people based on race. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department has investigated allegations involving  
New Jersey's state police. The matter also has become an issue in 
Florida, Maryland, Connecticut and elsewhere, and Holder said it 
was of ``great concern.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides race, personal involvement made a difference in how  
survey respondents felt about the police. 
</P>
<P>
	In each of the 12 cities, residents who had been victims of  
violent crime were less likely than others to say they were 
satisfied with local police. Likewise, people who were fearful of 
crime in their neighborhoods were less likely to be satisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, in New York, 39 percent of violent crime victims  
were dissatisfied with police, compared with dissatisfaction by 15 
percent of others. 
</P>
<P>
	And in Washington, 31 percent of those who were fearful of  
neighborhood crime were dissatisfied with police compared with 15 
percent of those who weren't fearful. 
</P>
<P>
	People get their perceptions of the police from ``their  
neighbors and the media, but an important component is based on 
personal experience,'' said Jan Chaiken, director of the Bureau of 
Justice Statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	In details of the report:  
</P>
<P>
	In Madison, Wis., 3 percent of blacks -- the same figure as for  
whites -- were dissatisfied with police. In Tucson, Ariz., 9 percent 
of blacks and 12 percent of whites were dissatisfied. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures for black dissatisfaction with police in other  
cities: Springfield, Mass., 24; Spokane, Wash., 21; Savannah, Ga., 
19; Kansas City, Mo., 14; San Diego, 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Among whites, the level of dissatisfaction with local police in  
those cities: San Diego, 5 percent; Kansas City and Springfield, 10 
percent; Savannah and Spokane, 12 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 20:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Bounce Back / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar edged higher against the yen Friday  
morning in Tokyo amid the euro's continued weakness against major 
currencies. Japanese stocks bounced back moderately. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.55 yen in late morning, up 0.01 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo but lower than its late New York level of 
121.66 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 104.76 points,  
or 0.65 percent, to 16,332.26 points at the end of the morning 
session. The index had lost 190.49 points, or 1.16 percent, on 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro's fall reflects continued disappointment with European  
economic fundamentals and unease about the realistic possibility of 
peace in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The currency hit a new record low against the dollar early in  
the Asian session Friday, dropping to $1.0284. In Tokyo trading, 
the euro was quoted at 125.19 yen, down from 125.95 yen late 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	There was some dollar-buying early in the session by players  
ahead of the release later Friday of U.S. non-farm payroll data for 
May, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The data will be scrutinized for signs of inflationary pressure,  
and the figures could indicate whether the U.S. Federal Reserve 
will favor an interest rate rise. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices posted moderate gains following the  
1.16 percent fall in the Nikkei a day earlier. Trading was thin in 
the dearth of fresh market-moving news, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazunori Jinnai, a general manager of the equity department at  
Daiwa Securities, said buying on the Tokyo Stock Exchange should 
remain steady for a while. 
</P>
<P>
	``With no strong lead from the U.S., the Tokyo stock market is  
likely to follow an independent course,'' Jinnai said. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section edged up 1.37 points, or 0.10 percent, to 1,319.06. 
The TOPIX finished down 9.08 points, or 0.68 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 85.80 to  
close at 10,663.69. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.6500 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.6050 percent, driving 
its price down to 97.85 yen from 98.23 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
