<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 15:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Slip in Thin Volume / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices slipped in thin volume Thursday as  
traders awaited more economic data to determine whether the Fed 
will move to raise interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 13/32  
point, or $4.06 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, rose to 5.95 percent from 5.94 percent the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports from retailers Thursday that sales remained strong in  
May lent more credence to the view that the U.S. economy is still 
growing, which could lead to higher interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	But many traders were holding out ahead of the May unemployment  
report, due out Friday, which might give a better insight into the 
Fed's thinking. The Fed said last month it would lean toward 
raising rates, which would hurt the values of bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged to down 1/32 point and intermediate maturities were 
down 1/32 point to 7/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.60 percent as the  
discount fell 0.11 percentage point to 4.48 percent. Six-month 
yields were 4.94 percent, as the discount rose 0.01 percentage 
point to 4.75 percent. One-year yields were 5.04 percent as the 
discount rose by 0.01 percentage point from late Wednesday to 4.79 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.81 percent from 4.69 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/32 to 121 3/16. The average yield to 
maturity was unchanged at 5.42 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 19:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Army Sgt. Sues CNN and Time Inc. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A veteran of U.S. Special Forces in Vietnam  
sued CNN and Time Inc. on Thursday, saying he was deceived into 
giving interviews for a story that accused U.S. commandos of using 
nerve gas to hunt down and kill defectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Hagen, a former Army Special Forces sergeant, sued CNN,  
Time Inc. and three producers as well as reporter Peter Arnett. He 
said he was told CNN producers could help him get medical treatment 
for his war-related illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``They took this brave war hero and made him look like a  
buffoon,'' said Hagen's lawyer, Kevin McLean. ``He was a hero, not 
a murderer and he has to restore his reputation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, which does not specify a damage amount, came a day  
after former Army Special Forces Lt. Robert Van Buskirk filed a 
defamation lawsuit in North Carolina seeking $100 million in 
damages for the same story, which was later retracted. 
</P>
<P>
	Hagen said he was never told the true nature of the story being  
investigated. 
</P>
<P>
	``They asked to interview me about my medical problems and the  
problems I was having with the Veterans Administration,'' Hagen 
said Thursday. ``The whole family was ecstatic that finally we were 
going to get some help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said producers discussed his illnesses and shot footage of  
some 20 bottles of narcotic medications prescribed for him. But 
they also asked him questions about the nerve gas sarin and about 
orders for dealing with defectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Hagen said he told producers he knew nothing about sarin gas or  
its use. 
</P>
<P>
	David Bittler, a CNN spokesman in Atlanta, declined to comment.  
Telephone messages seeking comment from Time magazine were not 
immediately returned Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint CNN-Time story telecast on June 7, 1998, claimed the  
military used sarin gas in Laos during Operation Tailwind, a 
mission to find defectors. Two U.S. defectors were supposedly 
killed in the attack, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The story was retracted after an internal investigation could  
not substantiate the allegations. Time and CNN, both owned by Time 
Warner, apologized for the story. 
</P>
<P>
	Two producers were fired and a third resigned over the story.  
Arnett, the story's lead reporter, was reprimanded and ultimately 
left the network. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 14:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange, American Stock 
Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market. 

</P>
<P>
 *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
 *Best Buy, up 6 1/8 at 54    	
</P>
<P>
	The consumer electronics retailer said sales at stores open at  
least a year, known as ``same-store sales,'' rose 13.3 percent in 
its first quarter. As a result, Best Buy expects first-quarter 
earnings of 20 cents per share, compared to 8 cents in the 
comparable period last year. 

</P>
<P>
 *Dollar General, up 3 1/16 at 30    	
</P>
<P>
	Goldman Sachs added Dollar General to its ``recommended'' list  
after the retailer said same-store sales for May rose 9.2 percent. 
For the year to date, the company said, same-store sales are up 6.6 
percent from 1998. 

</P>
<P>
 *Tricon Global Restaurants, down 4 1/4 at 47    	
</P>
<P>
	Robert C. Lowes, Tricon's chief financial officer, has resigned.  
The company will split his duties until a successor is found. 
Tricon is the parent company of KFC, Pizza Hut and Taco Bell 
restaurants. 

</P>
<P>
 *Nucor Corp., down 4 1/4 at 52 3/4    	
</P>
<P>
	Vice chairman and chief executive John D. Correnti resigned,  
citing a change in the company's corporate strategy. Nucor is a 
Charlotte, N.C.-based steelmaker. 

</P>
<P>
 *Volt Information Sciences Inc., up 2 3/16 at 19 7/8    	
</P>
<P>
	Volt earned 38 cents per share in the second quarter, up from 28  
cents a share in the second quarter of 1998. The company has 
telecommunications, electronic publication, typesetting and 
computer systems businesses. 

</P>
<P>
 *AMEX    	

</P>
<P>
 *BriteSmile Inc., up 2 11/16 at 13 3/4    	
</P>
<P>
	Orthodontic Centers of America Inc. will offer Britesmile's  
teeth-whitening process in affiliated orthodontists' offices. 
Orthodontic Centers also received an option to acquire a small 
stake in Britesmile. 

</P>
<P>
 *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
 *Winstar Communications Inc., up 2 1/2 at 57    	
</P>
<P>
	Winstar plans to offer free domestic and international  
long-distance service for one year and 18 months of free Web access 
to its new customers. The promotion targets business customers. 

</P>
<P>
 *U.S. Xpress, down 2 21/32 at 9 19/32    	
</P>
<P>
	The company will take a second-quarter charge against earnings  
after settling a breach-of-contract dispute with Employee Solutions 
Inc. U.S. Xpress, a holding company for truckload carrier and 
logistics businesses, will miss analysts' earnings estimates as a 
result of the $1.3 million charge. 

</P>
<P>
 *Ancor Communications Inc., up 3 3/16 at 14 1/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Ancor will be the original equipment manufacturer for certain  
products made by Sun Microsystems Inc. Ancor makes fibre channel 
switches for storage and data networks. 


  	   	
</P>
