<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Earthlings Look for ET on Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ray Christian doesn't use his home computer  
to shoot up fictional space aliens. He's too busy letting it search 
for the real thing. 
</P>
<P>
	Like thousands of other earthlings, the retiree from Des Moines,  
Iowa, installed a free screensaver that uses his idle computer to 
scan data from a radio telescope for evidence of intelligent life 
in the universe. 
</P>
<P>
	SETI(at)home has become one of the hottest programs on the  
Internet with more than 450,000 copies downloaded since the 
University of California at Berkeley project began May 15. 
Scientists who developed it initially expected about 100,000 users. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of using a single powerful computer, SETI(at)home  
spreads the workload among the home, school and office computers of 
its unpaid volunteers. As of Wednesday, more than 5,000 years of 
computer time had been logged. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a wide distribution of participants -- people in their  
80s, kids who are 6 years old,'' said Dan Werthimer, chief 
scientist of SETI(at)home. ``It's not just a bunch of computer 
geeks out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Projects involving the search for extraterrestrial intelligence,  
or SETI, are based on the assumption that alien beings are trying 
to communicate on specific radio frequencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The search is not unlike quickly turning a radio dial and  
hearing static and ``pops'' that indicate the signal of a station. 
</P>
<P>
	But nobody knows for sure what channel might be used by aliens.  
And the signal would be faint and mixed with radio noise from 
satellites and stars. Analysis of even a few seconds of data from a 
sliver of sky involves billions of computations. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why we're doing SETI(at)home,'' Werthimer said. ``We  
don't know what the signal is going to look like. We couldn't 
handle it even with the biggest supercomputer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Astronomers say chances are slim that a signal will be detected  
during SETI(at)home's two-year run. It's a test of distributing 
computer work over the Internet -- and a way to spark the public's 
interest in science, they say. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gives you an indication of the dynamics and the noise, the  
different interactions of forces,'' said Rubin McDavid, a Los 
Angeles environmental engineer who runs the program at home. ``It 
lets you know there is a real interaction of forces playing outside 
our planet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	SETI(at)home researchers receive the data from a  
1,000-foot-diameter radio telescope in Arecibo, Puerto Rico, and 
break it into small chunks, which are distributed via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Participants download the screensaver from SETI(at)home's Web  
site, setiathome.ssl.berkeley.edu. When their computers are turned 
on but not in use, the program kicks in, displaying a screensaver 
with colorful graphs showing what is being analyzed and whether a 
strong signal has been detected. 
</P>
<P>
	Periodically, participants dial in to download data to a  
Berkeley computer. It takes about five minutes to transmit 39 hours 
of computer work. 
</P>
<P>
	SETI(at)home organizers promise to share the credit of any  
discovery with the volunteer whose computer finds it, Werthimer 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers have been looking for ways to process more data for  
less money since Congress axed NASA's life-searching program in 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know that the interest in the idea in contact is enormous  
and it has always manifested itself in mythology, pseudoscience, 
astrology, folklore and tales of alien abduction,'' said Louis 
Friedman, who founded the Planetary Society with the late 
astronomer Carl Sagan. ``Here we're making a bridge. We're 
capturing that interest.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
