<HEADLINE> Compaq Management Exodus Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- The recent management exodus from Compaq Computer  
Corp. continued Wednesday with the announcement that John Rose, a 
senior vice president, is resigning. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's largest personal computer maker also said it has  
named Michael Capellas as acting chief operating officer, a new 
position. He had been a senior vice president and chief information 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	A wave of executive departures began earlier this year when, in  
the wake of stunningly poor earnings, the board of directors ousted 
chief executive officer Eckhard Pfeiffer. Earl Mason, chief 
financial officer, also resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq also named Enrico Pesatori as a senior vice president to  
replace Rose atop the company's Enterprise Computing Group. Fred 
Jones moves up to replace Capellas as acting chief information 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	As Compaq searches for a new chief executive, chairman Benjamin  
Rosen is heading an interim management team composed of directors 
Frank Doyle, a retired General Electric Co. executive, and Robert 
Ted Enloe III. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
