<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 12:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tears Shed for Fenway Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A. Bartlett Giamatti once compared Fenway Park to  
Mount Olympus, the pyramids at Giza and the Louvre. 
</P>
<P>
	``Except ... it was better than all those inconsequential  
places,'' wrote the scholar-turned-baseball commissioner who, like 
many American intellectuals, was given to flights of poetry and 
hyperbole about the nation's smallest major league ballpark, built 
in 1912. 
</P>
<P>
	Old and small, however, do not add up to major league profits.  
</P>
<P>
	The Boston Red Sox want to tear down Fenway Park and build a  
bigger ballpark across the street. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal has led to an outpouring of opposition, nostalgia  
and, yes, support from Fenway's most faithful. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever tears I've had for Fenway, I've long since shed,''  
said Roger Angell, the New Yorker magazine editor who wrote the 
classic baseball book ``The Summer Game.'' ``We can let some of 
these parks go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fenway and Detroit's Tiger Stadium are the nation's oldest major  
league ballparks. They opened on the same day, April 20, 1912. 
Tiger Stadium, however, will close at the end of the season, and 
the team will move to a new stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Fenway was featured in the 1989 movie ``Field of Dreams,'' and  
the writer John Updike once called the lopsided, 33,871-seat 
ballpark a ``lyric little bandbox.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A recent Boston Herald poll showed 49 percent of Massachusetts  
voters don't want to let go of Fenway's beloved nooks and crannies, 
its hand-operated scoreboard, the outfield bullpens where Ted 
Williams used to deposit his homers, and the Green Monster, the 
37-foot-high wall in left field. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fenway's awesome,'' David Doucette, a 28-year-old corporate  
banker, said Thursday. ``I like the old Fenway just like I liked 
the old Garden,'' referring to the Boston Garden, legendary home of 
the Celtics and Bruins that was torn down last year after a newer, 
larger arena was built next door. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-one percent of those polled supported tearing down the  
park and getting rid of the narrow seats, the views obstructed by 
grandstand poles, and the puddles of standing water when it rains. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about time they did it,'' said pitcher Pedro Martinez,  
the team's Cy Young Award winner. ``It's like an old man who passes 
away. You have to let go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox say they need the revenue from a bigger park if  
they're ever to win a World Series, something that has eluded them 
ever since they committed the error of selling Babe Ruth to the 
Yankees in 1918. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one should, with that treacly `baseball is life' stuff,  
convince you otherwise: I believe baseball is life, but life is 
profits,'' said filmmaker Ken Burns, a Fenway fan who chronicled 
baseball's history in an affectionate, nine-part series on PBS. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox plan is to build a ballpark that is 35 percent  
bigger than the house that Ruth fled, but -- like Baltimore's Camden 
Yards and Cleveland's Jacobs Field -- one that retains the intimacy 
and charm of older ballparks. 
</P>
<P>
	Many residents of the Kenmore Square neighborhoo agree the Red  
Sox need a better home field. But many of them object mightily to 
the team's plans to destroy 24 buildings when they move home plate 
206 yards away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe that this new megaplex belongs in this area at  
all,'' said Stephen M. Mindich, chairman of the Phoenix Media Group 
and owner of several buildings the Red Sox want the city to take by 
eminent domain. 
</P>
<P>
	A neighborhood group called Save Fenway Park! hired an architect  
to draw up plans to renovate the old ballpark by adding seats, 
luxury boxes and concession areas. But Red Sox officials, along 
with Baseball Commissioner Bud Selig, have said saving the park is 
not feasible. 
</P>
<P>
	The team has cultivated the state's most powerful politicians,  
who may be called on for up to $200 million for the $350 million 
park. The preservationists are likewise lobbying lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate will probably intensify during the days leading up to  
this year's All-Star Game, which will be held at Fenway on July 13. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox best-case scenario has a new park opening in 2003.  
But Dan Shaughnessy, the Boston Globe sportswriter who has waxed 
eloquent on the old ballpark in two books and hundreds of columns, 
believes it will take at least five more years, given Boston 
politics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like it to be forever,'' he said, ``but I understand the  
reality.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
