<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belmont Stakes Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After surveying the proximity of  
Silverbulletday's assigned stall in Barn 1 at Belmont Park to the 
heavy traffic on Hempstead Turnpike, trainer Bob Baffert set out to 
find other quarters for the filly. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday morning, shortly before Silverbulletday's arrival  
from Kentucky, Baffert and owner Mike Pegram happened to visit 
exercise rider Tonja Batsch at Barn 50, on the complete opposite 
end of the track. Underneath the towering oaks next to the barn is 
a shady, cool deck with a picnic table covered by an umbrella. It 
was built by trainer Bobby Barbara, whose horses occupy most of the 
stalls in Barn 50. 
</P>
<P>
	After being introduced to Baffert, Barbara offered him the use  
of one of his stalls for Silverbulletday. But Pegram, already 
ensconced in one of the chairs and enjoying the morning breeze, had 
already reached a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ain't moving from here,'' said Pegram. ``To heck with Barn  
1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The filly arrived at Barn 50 an hour later.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *VISA RENEWS SPONSORSHIP: VISA USA has renewed its exclusive  
sponsorship of the $5 million Visa Triple Crown Challenge bonus, 
which began in 1996 and will now continue through 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	The $5 million bonus is awarded to the owner of any horse that  
wins all three Triple Crown races: the Kentucky Derby, the 
Preakness and the Belmont Stakes. There have been only 11 Triple 
Crown winners in thoroughbred racing history, the most recent being 
Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Charismatic will try to complete the sweep when he  
takes on 11 challengers in the 1 1/2 mile Belmont, which will see a 
Triple Crown on the line for the third straight year. In 1997, 
Silver Charm was foiled by Touch Gold and last year Real Quiet's 
bid was thwarted by Victory Gallop. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NEW YORK TRIPLE: June 5 may be one of the biggest days in New  
York sports history.. 
</P>
<P>
	At 5:27 p.m. at Belmont Park, Charismatic will try to become  
racing's 12th Triple Crown winner in the Belmont Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	About four hours earlier, the New York Mets host their American  
League rivals, the New York Yankees, at Shea Stadium beginning at 
1:15 p.m. in the middle game of their interleague series. 
</P>
<P>
	And at 6:30 p.m. at Madison Square Garden, the New York Knicks  
will face the Indiana Pacers in Game 3 of the NBA Eastern 
Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	At Belmont Park, the Yankees-Mets games will be shown on TV  
on-track at many locations and the track will keep the third floor 
clubhouse and the second floor grandstand open and tuned in to the 
Pacers-Knicks game until its conclusion. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RUNNING MAN: Jockey Chris Antley, who will be aboard  
Charismatic in the Belmont, says he has a new appreciation of what 
horses go through in their training regimens. In the effort to lose 
the 30-odd pounds he gained while away from riding, Antley ran up 
to 25 miles a day for weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was about nine or 10 percent body fat at 125 pounds, so I  
had to kind of go into my own muscle,'' said Antley, who weighs in 
at 114 pounds. ``So I kind of played with my body until it cursed 
me back. 
</P>
<P>
	``My left knee went, and my right knee went, and I have no  
cartilage in my right knee from the constant pounding. I had to 
change my training because I kept breaking down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wayne (Lukas) talks about training -- I have a lot more  
respect now.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BELMONT BITS: The Belmont Stakes was first run at Jerome Park  
in 1867, then moved to Morris Park in the Bronx in 1890. In 1905, 
the race was moved to its current location at Belmont Park. ... A 
filly, Ruthless, won the very first Belmont Stakes, while another 
filly, Tanya, took the first running at the new Belmont Park in 
1905. ... Of the 130 previous runnings of the Belmont, 58 have been 
won by favorites. ... The lowest-priced winner was Count Fleet 
($2.10 in 1943), the highest-priced was Sherluck ($132.10 in 1961). 
... Best of Luck, the 6-1 fourth choice in the Belmont, worked 4 
furlongs in 49 3-5 and galloped out 5 furlongs in 1:02. ``I'd have 
liked to go a little faster, but he seems to be doing OK,'' trainer 
Allen Jerkens said. ... Vison and Verse, trained by Hall of Famer 
Bill Mott, had a strong 1 1-2-mile gallop on the main track, and 
Mott said ``he definitely got something out of it. At this point, 
everything is going well.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
