<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic Must Do More Than Promise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- No one in the Clinton administration is  
willing to simply take Slobodan Milosevic at his word. 
</P>
<P>
	He will, at a minimum, have to order his army and police forces  
in Kosovo to stop fighting and start heading home. 
</P>
<P>
	Given his history of broken promises, any NATO decision to stop  
bombing Yugoslavia will rest on a judgment about whether the 
long-defiant Milosevic has really been broken after 72 days of 
airstrikes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want this to be an exercise in paper promises,''  
Defense Secretary William Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton struck the ``trust, but verify'' theme in  
remarks Thursday at the White House in which he welcomed 
indications from Belgrade that the Yugoslav leadership has decided 
to yield to NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on our past experience, we must also be cautious,''  
Clinton added. ``First we must have clarity that the Serbian 
leadership has fully accepted these conditions and intends to fully 
implement them.'' Until a verifiable Serb troop withdrawal is under 
way NATO will keep bombing, the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who was deeply  
involved in the diplomacy that brought about the Yugoslav 
agreement, said Milosevic must now begin ``prompt unambiguous 
implementation'' of the terms. 
</P>
<P>
	The West learned a lesson in Milosevic's methods last fall, when  
he agreed -- under threat of NATO bombing -- to stop attacking the 
rebel Kosovo Liberation Army, which was fighting for independence 
from Serbia. The KLA agreed to a cease-fire and to enter good-faith 
negotiations. But the deal fell apart within weeks, and monitoring 
officials said both sides broke their peace promises. 
</P>
<P>
	The difference this time, in the view of Brookings Institution  
analyst John Steinbruner, is that a large, heavily armed 
international force under NATO command would enter Kosovo to 
implement the accord. Also, an interim administration for Kosovo 
would be set up under the auspices of the United Nations, which 
Steinbruner believes would mean that Milosevic would have less 
opportunity to undermine it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an entirely different situation'' from last fall,  
Steinbruner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also different is the condition of Milosevic's military after  
more than two months of unrelenting bombing. NATO claims to have 
destroyed at least one-third of the Serb armor in Kosovo, 80 
percent of the Serb air force, and large portions of the air 
defenses, fuel, ammunition and other resupply resources. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past seven days alone, NATO warplanes struck 310 pieces  
of Serb heavy armor, the Pentagon said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration's cautionary response Thursday  
reflects a determination not to let Milosevic off the hook by 
stopping the bombing before it is clear that the peace terms will 
be met in full. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin said the bombing would be  
suspended, not ended, if Milosevic demonstrates his acceptance of 
NATO's terms by beginning a verifiable withdrawal from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``The word suspension is extremely important because if the rest  
of the withdrawal didn't take place ... and this is what we need to 
guard against given the history of our dealings with President 
Milosevic as recently as his violations, repeated violations, of 
the October agreements -- we would want to be able to resume the air 
campaign,'' Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to halt the bombing will rest with the North  
Atlantic Council, the primary decision-making body of NATO. The 
Clinton administration wants to be as certain as possible of 
Milosevic's intentions before that NATO decision is made, because 
once the bombing stops it would be hard to restart. 
</P>
<P>
	Some doubt that anything short of forcing Milosevic from power  
will bring a lasting peace to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't accept promises or pledges from people like  
Milosevic,'' former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger told CNN. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Robert Burns is the Pentagon correspondent for  
The Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
