<HEADLINE> Lockheed To Cut 2,000 Jobs in Ga. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARIETTA, Ga. (AP) -- Lockheed Martin Corp. is cutting another  
2,000 jobs at its Marietta plant, or nearly 21 percent of its work 
force at facility. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense contractor disclosed the plans today, saying it  
hopes to accomplish 40 percent of the cuts through early 
retirement, attrition and transfers. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant makes the C-130J military transport plane and is the  
lead developer of the F-22 stealth fighter jet. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesman Sam Grizzle said the cuts will be across the board,  
including management. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is part of an ongoing initiative. We've been looking hard  
at how to cut costs,'' Grizzle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Orders for the C-130J have been slow, and Lockheed faces a  
production slowdown over the next three to six years. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which laid off 280 workers in January, had as many  
as 32,000 employees in Marietta, northwest of Atlanta, in the 
1970s. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
