<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Immigrants Can't Work During Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Illegal immigrants can't work while they  
appeal their deportation orders, a federal court ruled Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals overturned a federal  
judge's 1998 injunction that entitled 19 immigrants to keep their 
work permits pending court appeals of their deportations. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1986 law entitles illegal immigrants appealing deportation  
orders to have work permits if their applications are 
``non-frivolous.'' The law specified that the permits would be 
valid until a final determination of their status. 
</P>
<P>
	The Immigration and Naturalization Service interpreted the law  
to mean it was required to provide work permits only until its own 
``final determination'' of applications, leaving immigrants 
ineligible to work legally while awaiting court review. 
</P>
<P>
	Reasoning that a ``final determination'' includes a judicial  
review, U.S. District Judge Martin Jenkins of San Francisco 
prohibited the government from revoking the permits until the 
workers had lost their appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	But the appeals court, in a 3-0 ruling, said Congress had  
consistently used the term ``final determination'' in immigration 
laws to refer to INS actions, not court decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	If the ruling had been upheld, it could have affected thousands  
of immigrants nationwide, said Jonathan M. Kaufman, lawyer for the 
immigrants in the suit. He said judicial review of deportation 
orders can take up to six years. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who have no employment authorization have to work  
illegally,'' Kaufman said. ``Obviously that leaves them open to all 
kinds of exploitation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judges said making things difficult for illegal aliens was  
one of the specific goals of the 1986 law. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 14:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on Weather Fears / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures rose sharply on the  
Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts for weather conditions that 
could reduce this year's crop production. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service's latest 10-day forecast calls for  
above-normal temperatures and normal to below-normal rainfall in 
Midwest growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Hot, dry weather could stress young crops early, and market  
participants are beginning to worry a dry weather pattern in some 
eastern growing states could sharply reduce production on what is 
expected to be bumper acreage. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, substantial rainfall in western growing states such as  
North Dakota and Iowa was keeping farmers from completing final 
planting. Wheat futures in particular benefited from such delays in 
spring wheat plantings, which come as the window of opportunity for 
getting those crops into the ground comes to a close. Wheat also 
gained amid expectations heavy recent rainfall in the Plains may 
have reduced the quality of the winter wheat crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 7 3/4 cents to $2.61 a bushel; July  
corn jumped 6 1/2 cents to $2.23 1/4 a bushel; July oats rose 3 3/4 cents to 
$1.26 1/4 a bushel; July soybeans rose 6 3/4 cents to $4.65 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and lean hog futures advanced on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while feeder cattle were mixed and pork 
bellies retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .25 cent to 64.77 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .30 cent to 75.37 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .37 cent to 51.02 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .48 
cent to 53.07 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
