<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Claims Edge Up Slightly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for  
unemployment benefits edged up slightly last week to the highest 
level in three weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said today that 305,000 Americans filed new  
claims for jobless benefits last week, up by 4,000 from the 
previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase was unexpected. Most economists had been looking  
for jobless claims to remain unchanged from the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-week moving average for jobless claims, which helps  
smooth out week-to-week volatility, also was up, rising to 304,250, 
also the highest level since the week ending May 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the slight increase, the jobless claims applications  
are remaining at low levels, which analysts say depicts an 
extremely tight labor market. 
</P>
<P>
	The government on Friday will report on unemployment for the  
month of April and many analysts believe the rate will stay at 4.3 
percent, close to a 29-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing has lost more than 400,000 jobs in the past year  
due to the global financial crisis, which has cut into exports and 
increased cheap imports into this country. But the rest of the U.S. 
economy has continued to forge ahead, powered by strong consumer 
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said that for the week ending May 22, 32  
states and territories reported declines in jobless claims while 21 
had increases. The state data lags a week behind the national 
figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The states with the biggest declines in applications for jobless  
benefits were Michigan, down 913; Pennsylvania, down 873; New 
Jersey, down 786; Missouri, down 702, and New York, down 652. 
</P>
<P>
	The state with the biggest increase in claims for the week  
ending May 22 was Mississippi, where claims rose 1,607, an increase 
officials blamed on layoffs in apparel and service industries. 
Other states with large claims increases were Iowa, up 1,277; 
Arkansas, up 1,064; Oregon, up 896, and Florida, up 646. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
