<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mark Portugal May Quit Baseball </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PAWTUCKET, R.I. (AP) -- After meeting with Boston Red Sox general  
manager Dan Duquette and manager Jimy Williams for nearly an hour 
Thursday, pitcher Mark Portugal said he will make an announcement 
about his future on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation that the 36-year-old would retire to spend more time  
with his three children mounted after Portugal cleaned out his 
locker after pitching three innings against the Detroit Tigers on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important priority is my state of being and we're  
going to try and work on that and tomorrow have a better answer,'' 
Portugal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan confirmed that the right-hander  
wants to retire, The Boston Globe reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite indications that he would leave the game after pitching  
11 years in the major leagues, Portugal did not rule out that he 
might continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've just got to tie up some loose ends on my end before I can  
come back and play baseball,'' Portugal said. ``The kids are the 
most important things in my life and I know they want me to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal signed a $2.7 million, one-year contract with the Red  
Sox, a deal that gives Boston a $3.3 million option with a $300,000 
buyout. He is 3-3 with a 5.33 ERA in 10 starts this season. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last two years, Portugal, who has been on the disabled  
list 10 times in his career, has had surgery on both his pitching 
elbow, which caused him to miss almost all of the 1997 season, and 
his left knee. He wears a brace on his right knee, which was 
operated on previously. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Williams said Portugal's issue is not physical.  
</P>
<P>
	``If it's not his health. You know, mentally maybe he's not into  
it anymore,'' center fielder Darren Lewis said. ``If that's the 
case and you're at the point mentally, then there's no point to be 
in the game if you don't have that fire to compete. Plus, wanting 
to see his kids, that just adds to the problems. I'm sure he want 
to spend some time with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he has the team in mind when he does make the decision  
because he's not doing us any good by being here if he's not into 
it,'' pitcher Derek Lewis added. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally drafted by the Minnesota Twins in 1980, Portugal  
played for the Astros, Giants, Reds and Phillies before coming to 
Boston. An 18-game winner in 1993, Portugal is 105-86 in the major 
leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams said Pat Rapp was scheduled to take Portugal's turn on  
the mound Sunday against the Atlanta Braves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
