<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pittsburgh's Smith Wins 7th Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- For the second straight year, Stanford  
runners finished 1-2-3 in the 10,000 meters, helping their team 
take the early lead in the NCAA men's track championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Nathan Nutter won the event in 29 minutes, 11.96 seconds  
with a burst in the final yards, and teammates Jason Balkman and 
Brent Hauser were right behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford, runnerup to Arkansas last year, moved into first place  
with 24 points, 11 ahead of Auburn. The Cardinal also led after the 
first day of last year's championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Finals were scheduled today in the women's shot put, men's long  
jump, women's high jump and women's 10,000 meters. Competition on 
the Boise State University track continues through Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Abdi Abdirahman of Arizona came into the race with the fastest  
time this season in the 10,000 meters and led the first two-thirds 
of the race. But the Stanford runners stayed close, burst into the 
lead in the final laps and won going away. 
</P>
<P>
	Nutter said it was his best race of the season. He captured the  
Pac-10 championship last month, but said it was only because a 
teammate let him finish first because he was a senior. 
</P>
<P>
	``Phenomenal,'' he said. ``We couldn't win any more points than  
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh's Trecia Smith wons her seventh national track and  
field title, but wanted to talk more about her upcoming events than 
winning the long jump. 
</P>
<P>
	She competes Friday in the triple jump and Friday and Saturday  
in the heptathlon. ``My goal is to finish all three events. I 
pulled up last year in the triple jump, and I want to finish all 
three events.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She had no problems Wednesday, winning her second outdoor long  
jump championship with a leap of of 21 feet, 8 1/4 inches. That was 
nearly six inches ahead of runnerup Angie Smith of James Mason, 
last year's champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Florence Ezeh of Southern Methodist won the women's hammer with  
a toss of 207-2. 
</P>
<P>
	The LSU women's team, which saw a string of 11 straight  
championships broken by Texas last year, saw its chances fall when 
the 400-meter relay team dropped the baton on the first exchange 
and didn't finish, failing to qualify. 
</P>
<P>
	Chenelle Marshall and Joyce Bates of LSU didn't make the  
connection in the first handoff in the 400 relay, and the baton 
fell to the track. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just brushed my hand,'' Marshall said. ``I'm very  
disappointed. It's my only event. We've just got to put this behind 
us.' 
</P>
<P>
	``I just couldn't believe it,'' Bates said. ``I didn't think we  
would come out here and drop it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Bates still thinks LSU has a good chance to recapture the  
championship. ``We've always come from behind. Everybody just has 
to focus and do what they do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A freshman who has been in the United States only since January,  
Auburn's Gabor Mate won the discus at 202-1, and immediately 
pronounced himself ``the happiest man in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mate, a native of Hungary, said it was the first time he'd ever  
won against major competition. He was 7 inches behind his personal 
best, but said, ``I'm happy with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Janus Robberts of Southern Methodist won the eight points for  
second place in the discus with a throw of 198-11, and Northern 
Arizona's Nick Petrucci was third at 195-5. 
</P>
<P>
	SMU, Kansas State and Pittsburgh held the first-day lead in the  
women's competition with 10 points each. Southern California was 
fourth with 9 points. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
