<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polygamist Convicted of Incest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A member of a polygamist clan was  
convicted Thursday of incest and unlawful sex with his 16-year-old 
niece, who testified she was forced to become her uncle's 15th 
wife. 
</P>
<P>
	The case of David Ortell Kingston brought renewed attention to  
polygamy in Utah, where the polygamist population is estimated to 
include between 20,000 and 30,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The secretive Kingston clan has as many as 1,000 members and  
business assets worth up to $150 million. While the clan shares 
many of the beliefs of other polygamous groups in Utah, it stands 
apart in practicing incest, former members said. 
</P>
<P>
	At trial, the girl, now 17, said in October 1997 that Kingston,  
33, called her and suggested they marry. 
</P>
<P>
	Her father performed the ceremony and the defendant's other  
wives were in attendance. Her uncle later gave her a ring with 15 
diamonds, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the ceremony, they had four sexual encounters, all in  
1998, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The girl, now is in foster care, stayed at home and sometimes  
visited her uncle after the wedding, she said. She repeatedly tried 
to avoid her husband-uncle and would stay out late with friends 
when she knew he was planning to visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers contended there never was a wedding and no sex  
ever happened. 
</P>
<P>
	Kingston, an accountant for the family's multimillion dollar  
business empire, was convicted of two of the four felony counts. 
Each conviction carries a penalty of up to five years in prison. 
Sentencing was set for July. 
</P>
<P>
	About 70 percent of Utah's population are members of The Church  
of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, which renounced polygamy in 
1890 after Congress passed tough anti-bigamy laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Large-scale prosecution of polygamists has not taken place in  
Utah for more than four decades. Kingston was not charged with 
polygamy, and there was limited discussion of the topic during the 
trial. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
