<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Affirmed Still Going Strong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- His back is level and remarkably strong,  
and his chestnut coat shows only the lightest smattering of white 
hair around the muzzle and eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	At age 24, Affirmed, thoroughbred racing's last Triple Crown  
winner, looks as though he could join Charismatic and 12 other 
horses in Saturday's Belmont Stakes -- and maybe even win. 
</P>
<P>
	Brought from his stall to meet a tour group visiting Jonabell  
Farm on Wednesday, Affirmed strutted and posed as though he, not 
Charismatic, would be going for the Triple Crown this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	As he walked in circles on the lawn in front of the Jonabell  
stallion barn, the 1978 Triple Crown champion's muscles were 
sharply defined, and the ribs of his barrel chest were outlined by 
his taut, shining coat. 
</P>
<P>
	Showing a little spirit, Affirmed tossed his white-blazed head  
against the lead held by Jonabell stallion manager Phillip Hampton. 
His steps, however, were sure and steady, belying any notion of 
skittishness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if you didn't know he was a Triple Crown winner, you  
would enjoy being around him on an every-day basis just because of 
his personality,'' Hampton said. ``He's a real gentlemen. He's just 
an exceptional individual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a camera shutter clicked, Affirmed's gaze had the calm  
certainty of one accustomed to being the center of attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``He does have that command presence, and he always knows when  
there's a camera around,'' Jonabell manager Jimmy Bell said. ``From 
a physical standpoint, he defies age.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was 21 years ago that Affirmed made thoroughbred racing  
history by winning the Belmont in a riveting stretch duel with his 
equally famous rival, Alydar. 
</P>
<P>
	That victory produced the sport's last Triple Crown winner.  
Since then, six colts have won the first two races -- the Kentucky 
Derby and the Preakness -- only to lose in the Belmont, including 
Silver Charm in 1997 and Real Quiet in '98. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, it's Charismatic's turn, and Affirmed's former  
jockey said he will be rooting for the D. Wayne Lukas-trained colt 
to end the Triple Crown drought. 
</P>
<P>
	``Affirmed will always have his place in history, and so will  
I,'' said Steve Cauthen, who was 18 then and a Kentucky horse 
breeder now. ``Nothing will change if Charismatic wins the Triple 
Crown, except it'll be good for racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What's missing this time, though, is the fierce rivalry that  
binds Affirmed to Alydar to this very day. 
</P>
<P>
	Alydar finished second in all three races, coming closer to  
victory each time. Affirmed won by 1 1/2 lengths in the Derby, a neck 
in the Preakness and a mere head in the Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	The most famous duel, of course, was the last, when Affirmed and  
Alydar battled side-by-side down the final seven furlongs. 
</P>
<P>
	``He pulled it out under the most extreme situation,'' Cauthen  
said. ``Anyone that saw that race will never forget it, and 
probably remember it as the greatest race they ever saw.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Affirmed was retired to stud after the 1979 season, having won  
14 stakes races and more than $2.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Affirmed has not had as successful a stud career as Alydar, who  
was euthanized in 1990 after breaking a leg in his stall, or fellow 
Triple Crown winner Seattle Slew, now 25 and still standing at 
Three Chimneys. But his progeny have been strong turf runners and 
his daughters have made good broodmares. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the nearly 660 Affirmed foals who had reached racing age as  
of last fall, 68 had won stakes races. As a group, his foals had 
earned more than $33.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, when he's not in the breeding shed or posing for visitors,  
Affirmed splits time between the paddock and his stall in the 
Jonabell stallion barn, diagonally across from that of 1994 Horse 
of the Year Holy Bull. There, Hampton frequently finds the stallion 
gazing out his window, which overlooks a pasture and a line of 
trees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he's a very content horse,'' Bell said. ``I think he  
enjoys his lifestyle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hampton said Affirmed's breeding book recently has been trimmed  
to about 45 mares a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just trying to sustain him here in the latter years,''  
he said. ``By him still seeing mares and doing a good job of it, 
he's turned back the hands of time a little.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cauthen bred one of his mares to his former mount in 1998, and  
now is raising a 3-month-old Affirmed filly. When the former jockey 
came to visit Affirmed earlier this week, he showed off a snapshot 
of the foal to Hampton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was glad to breed to him and I'm glad I got a filly'' who  
might be both a runner and a broodmare, Cauthen said. ``Maybe he'll 
do me one more favor.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Cos. Eye California Drilling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Oil companies eager to drill their 40  
offshore leases along California's coast have turned in exploration 
and development plans, a critical step that could mean new oil 
drilling there within a few years, federal officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The leases are the only sites along the entire U.S. West Coast  
where new offshore oil development can take place for at least 12 
years and would be the first new offshore drilling facilities since 
1989, said John Romero, spokesman for the Minerals Management 
Service's Pacific region. 
</P>
<P>
	At last year's National Oceans Conference in Monterey, President  
Clinton extended until 2012 a moratorium on new offshore leasing, 
``to protect our oceans and coasts from the environmental risks of 
offshore oil and gas drilling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton's ban only covers new leases. The 40 leases now  
subject to planning were sold between 1968 and 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil companies collectively paid $1.25 billion for the 40 leases  
along the coast of San Luis Obispo, Santa Barbara and Ventura 
counties. In 1990, the federal government stopped development on 
the sites after local communities demanded a study on the impact of 
offshore drilling on their lands and economies. 
</P>
<P>
	That suspension expires on June 30, when the California Offshore  
Oil and Gas Energy Resources study is completed. Minerals 
Management will review the submitted plans and announce whether 
they have been approved by the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	One company, Whiting Petroleum, says it's ready to drill.  
Whiting plans to pull oil from wells near its existing platform 
near Point Arguello and anticipates production by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Four companies proposed revisions of their exploration plans in  
order to drill up to six wells from mobile drilling structures. 
Another company asked to submit plans for a site that has not been 
explored. 
</P>
<P>
	``The leases are getting back on track to hopefully be a normal  
course of business'' said Frank Holmes, coastal coordinator for the 
Western States Petroleum Association, which represents prospective 
operators at all the undeveloped sites. 
</P>
<P>
	``With success, these will generate a lot of revenue,'' Holmes  
said, adding it will take about eight to 10 years to get new 
platforms into production. 
</P>
<P>
	County officials and environmental groups oppose any new  
development on the leases, and have called on state and federal 
government officials to scrutinize the proposals or cancel the 
leases altogether. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still dealing with two of the largest oil spills in the  
nation,'' says John Euphrat, senior planner for San Luis Obispo 
County. ``It's not a question of if, but when the next one will 
happen. The technology today isn't adequate to contain spilled 
oil.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
