<DOCNO> APW19990603.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 10:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sorvino Back in 'Championship' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Paul Sorvino and his co-stars in ``That  
Championship Season'' are tossing dialogue to each other with the 
deftness of a winning team. Then, abruptly, a line is dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cut, cut, cut. I was wondering who was up,'' says Sorvino.  
``It's me. I know it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The actor can be forgiven for the flub and for calling the time  
out: Sorvino was directing Showtime's remake of the Pulitzer 
Prize-winning drama as well as playing the pivotal role of the 
coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Vincent D'Onofrio, Terry Kinney, Tony Shalhoub and Gary Sinise  
also featur in the TV movie, filmed last January in a studio north 
of Los Angeles. It debuts 8 p.m. EDT Sunday on the cable channel. 
</P>
<P>
	``That Championship Season'' is an exercise in nostalgia and  
reinvention for Sorvino, who appeared in the Jason Miller play on 
Broadway that won a Tony Award in 1973, and in the 1982 movie 
version. 
</P>
<P>
	In both, Sorvino was Phil Romano (now D'Onofrio's role), one of  
four middle-aged men who have gathered with their high school 
basketball coach to relive the triumph of winning the state 
championship two decades before. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides trying on a different character, Sorvino is attempting  
to give the play a different treatment. He believes the first 
movie, starring Bruce Dern, Stacy Keach, Robert Mitchum and Martin 
Sheen, missed the basket. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics agreed, with one dubbing the film ``unimaginative.''  
</P>
<P>
	``We never rehearsed before the production began and there were  
some casting problems, there were some things that didn't go 
right,'' Sorvino said. ``It was Jason's first directing job, and he 
was pushed into it. He was a playwright then. ... It just never 
came off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sorvino strongly believes the drama, adapted by Miller for the  
new production, deserves to be revisited. 
</P>
<P>
	``What makes this play for me the finest play of the century and  
the American repertoire is that it's not only a supreme, towering 
drama -- to quote most of the original reviewers -- but it's an 
extraordinarily funny comedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not a black comedy; it's just very funny. It's a slice of  
life about men who are lost -- fatherless men who seek to create a 
family with one another, with all the antagonisms and frustrations 
of their lives and old sins and new conspiring to tear them 
apart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He got just the cast he wanted, ``extraordinarily high caliber  
actors,'' Sorvino said. The appearance of a smoothly functioning 
team is not deceiving, said Shalhoub (``Big Night,'' TV's 
``Wings''), who plays George Sitkowski, athlete-turned-politician. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a true ensemble piece. The biggest trap in doing this  
play would be to find yourself in a situation where everybody's out 
for their own advancement or taking care of themselves as opposed 
to feeding the other actors,'' Shalhoub said. 
</P>
<P>
	He lauds Sorvino's contributions: ``He did the play. He was  
there while it was being created. ... He has a feel for the 
intricacies of the material.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While respecting the play's integrity, Sorvino says he has added  
small touches and opened it up to take advantage of the move from 
stage to screen. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see the men going into a store to buy liquor instead of  
just hearing about it,'' Sorvino said. ``I put an old man playing 
violin outside, as homage to Fellini and company. Little touches 
like that can bring it out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also wrote a bit of business for that scene to illuminate Tom  
Daley, the character played by Sinise. When another one of his 
former teammates passes by the old musician, Tom empties his 
pockets for him. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can set the character up in a visual way, which you can't  
do on stage,'' Sorvino said. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as his co-stars are bringing new dimensions to their roles,  
Sorvino said, he is reinterpreting the coach, played by Richard A. 
Dysart (``L.A. Law'') on stage and by Mitchum in the '82 film. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a more emotional actor than the other fellows, and I allow  
myself to have my emotional tectonic plates shifted more. I've 
never seen the role played the way I'm playing it, and I hope 
that's a good thing. But I don't know if it is,'' he said, 
laughing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm hoping I hit it right and, if I do, it should vitalize the  
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sinise believes the play carries its own timeless energy.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at what informs the characters' being and what has  
gotten them to this point, to where the best moment in their lives 
was a moment in high school, a lot of people can relate to that. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people have their greatest moment in their life happen in  
their first two decades, and they never get that rush, that shining 
moment again.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	BY WOMEN, FOR WOMEN: Anjelica Huston is host of the third annual  
Lifetime Women's Film Festival, a two-hour program showcasing five 
short films directed by female independent filmmakers. These 
include Kara Harshbarger's ``A Little Inside,'' about a young girl 
whose desire to dance goes against her father's wish for her to 
play ball, and Angela Robinson's ``The Kinsey 3,'' a 
tongue-in-cheek film about a team of art thieves. Another film, 
``Jazz Night,'' commissioned by Lifetime and directed by Wallis 
Nicita, stars Beverly D'Angelo and John Heard. The festival debuts 
8 p.m. Sunday, June 6. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
