<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 12 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Milosevic Accepts Western Peace Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Caving in to Russian and Western  
demands, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accepted a peace 
plan for Kosovo on Thursday that is designed to end mass expulsions 
of ethnic Albanians and 11 weeks of NATO airstrikes. Even though 
the draft appeared to signal a victory for NATO, President Clinton 
and other U.S. officials reacted cautiously. In the meantime, 
NATO's bombing campaign continued, with airstrikes reported in 
Kosovo and elsewhere Thursday night. Though cloaked in language 
meant to make it palatable to the Belgrade government, the plan 
contained tough conditions Milosevic had until now resisted 
including the deployment of foreign troops on Yugoslav soil. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Says Kosovo Prayers Answered  
</P>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Pope John Paul II welcomed Yugoslavia's  
acceptance Thursday of an international peace plan as an answer to 
prayer. The pope has repeatedly pushed for appeals and diplomacy to 
end the conflict in Kosovo. John Paul, who was conferring with U.N. 
Secretary-General Kofi Annan at the Vatican when the news came out 
of Belgrade, urged the United Nations to oversee the quick return 
of refugees to Kosovo. Annan later pronounced himself encouraged by 
Yugoslavia's acceptance, but told reporters, ``It's premature to 
jump for joy.'' 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Moves Closer to Seante Run  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton intends to form an  
exploratory committee in early July, preparing for a potential 
Senate campaign in New York next year, a top adviser said Thursday. 
Harold Ickes, who is heading Mrs. Clinton's political operation, 
disclosed her plans after Rep. Nita Lowey said, in a telephone call 
to the first lady, that she would seek re-election to the House. 
That leaves the Democratic Senate field clear for Mrs. Clinton. She 
would be the first sitting first lady to run for public office. 

</P>
<P>
	Discovery Leaves Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Discovery and its crew  
sailed away from the international space station Thursday after 
getting the satellite ready for its first permanent residents next 
year. Pilot Rick Husband, who was at the shuttle controls, said he 
was leaving ``with some regret.'' Although Discovery was linked to 
the space station for six days, the astronauts spent less than 3 1/2 
days inside the orbiting complex. The first inhabitants are due to 
move in next March. 

</P>
<P>
	Conservatives Win in Ontario  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- The Conservative Party retained its majority in  
Ontario's provincial legislature, winning a vote marred by a bomb 
threat and menacing phone calls that prevented several polling 
stations from opening on time. The bomb threat Thursday against one 
polling station at a school in Simcoe-Grey, north of Toronto, 
forced its evacuation and shut it down for hours. As many as 500 
polling clerks in other areas called in sick or quit after 
receiving threatening phone calls, said Warren Bailie, head of 
Elections Ontario. 

</P>
<P>
	Tribes Sue for Tobacco Settlement  
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Representatives of more than 20 American  
Indian tribes and groups said Thursday they were snubbed in the 
tobacco industry's $200 billion settlement with the states, and 
they're suing for what they claim is their fair share. The class 
action suit, filed Wednesday in San Francisco federal court, 
demands $1 billion in compensation and punitive damages from 
several tobacco companies. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., Libya To Hold Talks  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United States and Libya will hold  
direct talks next week, the first step toward resuming official 
contact after diplomatic relations were severed 18 years ago, 
diplomats said Thursday. Secretary-General Kofi Annan arranged the 
meeting at Washington's request, the diplomats said. The meeting is 
set for June 11 in Annan's chambers. 

</P>
<P>
	Nikkei Gains 104.76 in Midday Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices bounced back moderately Friday.  
The Nikkei rose 104.76 to 16,332.26 in midday trading. In New York 
on Thursday, the Dow industrials ended at 10,663.69, up 85.80. 

</P>
<P>
	Tennessee Star Returns Home a Pro  
</P>
<P>
	KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw, bidding farewell to  
Tennessee basketball fans, had 20 points, 10 rebounds and six 
assists in the Washington Mystics' 68-64 victory over the Houston 
Comets in a WNBA exhibition. The game, held in conjunction with the 
opening of the Women's Basketball Hall of Fame in Knoxville, drew 
9,279. 

</P>
<P>
	McGwire Homers But Marlins Win  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Rookie Mike Lowell, who missed the start of the  
season following surgery for testicular cancer, hit his first major 
league homer tonight to help the Florida Marlins rally past the St. 
Louis Cardinals 4-2. Mark McGwire hit his 17th homer, but left in 
the sixth inning as a precaution because of tightness in his lower 
back. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
