<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aging Panda Has Kidney Disease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- His appetite has improved, along with his  
energy, but officials at the National Zoo say an aging Hsing-Hsing 
isn't likely to survive the latest illness plaguing the popular 
black-and-white giant panda. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently diagnosed with severe kidney dysfunction, the  
28-year-old mammal has responded well to various medication and 
fluids. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's irreversible but stabilizable,'' zoo veterinarian Lucy  
Spelman said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Vets discovered the kidney problems May 15 after putting  
Hsing-Hsing (pronounced Shing-Shing) under anesthesia for an exam. 
Zookeepers had noted the animal seemed lethargic and had lost both 
weight and appetite. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a day-to-day situation with him and that's just how we  
have to take it,'' said Lisa Stevens, the zoo's mammal curator. 
</P>
<P>
	The illness will probably be his last, Stevens acknowledged, and  
zoo officials are doing all they can to make Hsing-Hsing 
comfortable. 
</P>
<P>
	The kidney problem is probably related to the animal's advanced  
age, Steven said. Zoo officials have ruled out extreme measures, 
including dialysis treatment. Dialysis would require daily 
anesthesia, a huge risk for such an elderly animal. Pandas rarely 
live to their 20s in the wild. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens reminded reporters that Hsing-Hsing was relatively  
healthy until two years ago when he was diagnosed with testicular 
cancer and underwent surgery. Veterinarians removed an enlarged, 
tumorous testicle. They also removed the other testicle as a 
precaution. 
</P>
<P>
	Hsing-Hsing also suffers from arthritis.  
</P>
<P>
	For now, the giant panda exhibit, a major draw for the National  
Zoo, which is part of the Smithsonian Institution, remains open 
although it closes periodically to allow Hsing-Hsing to rest or 
receive treatment. A handwritten sign posted at the exhibit's 
entrance informs visitors that ``Hsing-Hsing is not feeling well 
... at times, we may need to close the panda house to care for 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hsing-Hsing, along with his female mate, Ling-Ling, arrived in  
Washington in 1972 as a gift from the People's Republic of China 
following President Nixon's trip to Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ling-Ling died of heart failure in 1992. None of the cubs that  
the pair produced survived more than a few days. 
</P>
<P>
	Devra Kleiman, a senior research scientist at the zoo, said  
officials have discussed conservation and breeding programs with 
zoo officials in China for the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have hopes of receiving another pair sometime in the  
future,'' she said. Kleiman said a team from the National Zoo is 
scheduled to go to China this month, and ``we hope to come back 
with an agreement.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
