<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hobbled Floyd Happy to DH for Marlins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Cliff Floyd will be the Florida Marlins' designated  
hitter this weekend at Tampa Bay, and he's delighted with the 
assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	Many players dislike the DH role, but Floyd will gladly give up  
his left fielder's glove. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not that I don't want to play defense,'' Floyd said Thursday.  
``I want to be an all-around player. But I kind of like just 
hitting. If you do something good at the plate but stink it up in 
the field, you didn't have a good day. If you just hit and you do 
good, then you had a good day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense is not what Floyd does best. His throwing arm is  
inconsistent, and a sore knee that kept him out of the first 19 
games makes it difficult for him to cover ground in left. 
</P>
<P>
	It's clear his confidence in his fielding is shaky, even though  
he made a fine running catch Wednesday with the bases loaded 
against the St. Louis Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``If that ball gets in the lights and hits off my glove and  
three runs score, it's not a good day,'' Floyd said. ``Now I won't 
have to worry about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins visit the Devil Rays beginning Friday for a  
three-game interleague matchup billed as the citrus series. Floyd 
was a DH against Tampa Bay last year when he hit a homer off Dennis 
Springer, who now pitches for the Marlins. 
</P>
<P>
	``To just hit will be good for me,'' Floyd said. ``I'm not  
Harold Baines, who's my idol, but I think I can handle being a 
designated hitter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays' artificial turf and Floyd's troublesome knee  
made the decision to use him as a DH an easy one, Marlins interim 
manager Fredi Gonzalez said. Bruce Aven, batting .365 through 
Wednesday in 63 at-bats, will replace Floyd in left field. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd, 26, who is in the first season of a $19 million,  
four-year contract, said his left knee remains sore and weak 
following surgery April 6 to repair torn cartilage. It hasn't 
affect him much at the plate, and he was hitting .280 with six 
homers and 24 RBIs in 33 games through Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the field and on the bases, Floyd is at least a step  
slow. He stole 27 bases last year but is just 1-for-5 this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``The distances I've been thrown out -- it's embarrassing,'' he  
said. ``My grandmother runs faster than me right now, and she's 
86.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
