<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Up; Factory Orders Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The raging U.S. economy encouraged Americans to  
go on a shopping spree in May, boosting sales at the nation's 
biggest retailers to better-than-expected levels for the fourth 
straight month. 
</P>
<P>
	Discounters and specialty clothing stores fared best last month  
as consumers bought up everything from trendy capri pants from the 
Limited to new gardening equipment at Wal-Mart. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers today have a tremendous sense of well-being and  
wealth,'' said Wendy Liebmann, president of the retail consulting 
firm WSL Strategic Retail. ``Even though many know that their 
spending can't go on forever, they are thinking `I better spend it 
while I can.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Retailers have watched their sales rise steadily over the last  
year, benefiting from a strong U.S. economy, as well as low 
unemployment and inflation levels. That's made consumers confident 
about their personal finances and eager to spend. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately Thursday, the Labor Department reported the number of  
Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits rose a slight 
4,000 to 305,000 last week, signaling that unemployment remains 
extremely low. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are concerns that a sharp or prolonged decline on Wall  
Street, a rise in interest rates or signs of a slowing economy 
could cause Americans to curb their buying. 
</P>
<P>
	Some evidence of a slowdown came Thursday with the Commerce  
Department's report that orders to American factories for 
manufactured goods fell 1.2 percent in April, reflecting a big drop 
in demand for aircraft and other transportation products. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, Freddie Mac, the mortgage company, said that the  
average interest rate on 30-year fixed-rate mortgages hit its 
highest level in nearly two years, jumping to 7.41 percent from 
7.23 percent a week ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are all sorts of things that can turn people away from  
shopping very quickly,'' Liebmann said. ``While they are spending a 
lot now, most consumers today realize that this boom can't go on 
forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite concerns over what's to come, Americans did plenty of  
shopping in May. They bought lots of clothes and accessories at the 
specialty apparel stores, and turned to the discount chains for 
everything from patio furniture to groceries to new ``Star Wars'' 
toys. 
</P>
<P>
	The growth in May sales came despite being compared with the  
very strong performance of May 1998. Retail stocks surged on Wall 
Street on Thursday, helping lift the Dow Jones industrial average 
up 85.80 to 10,663.69. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are looking at a very strong second quarter,'' said Walter  
Loeb, who runs the retailing consulting firm Loeb Associates. ``May 
was great and June has started off with a great bang. It think the 
quarter could end above expectations.'' For retailers, the fiscal 
year's second quarter runs from May through July. 
</P>
<P>
	While most fared well in May, some merchants -- including Kmart  
and J.C. Penney -- were hurt by the late Memorial Day this year. 
Most retailers ended their fiscal month of May on the 28th or 29th, 
which meant that much of the buying over this year's holiday 
weekend will be included in June's sales figures. Memorial Day was 
observed on May 31 this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Merrill Lynch retail index, the investment firm's barometer  
of sales performance at department stores and discount chains, was 
up 4.8 percent in May. It rose 6.4 percent in May 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, reported sales from  
stores open at least a year rose 7.7 percent from a year earlier, 
while total sales were up 14.3 percent. Sales from stores open at 
least a year, known as same-store sales, are considered the most 
accurate measure of a retailer's strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Other retailers' reports:  
</P>
<P>
	--Sears: Same-store sales up 1.9 percent, total sales down 2.8  
percent. --Kmart: Same-store sales up 3.7 percent, total sales up 
5.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--J.C. Penney: Same-store department store sales up 2.2 percent,  
same-store sales at Eckerd drugstores rose 13.4 percent, total 
sales rose 9.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Dayton Hudson: Same-store sales up 6.3 percent, total sales up  
10.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Federated: Same-store sales rose 4.1 percent, total sales up  
14.9 percent. Federated's total sales included revenue from the 
Internet and from catalog seller Fingerhut, which it acquired in 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	--May Department Stores: Same-store sales up 2.9 percent, total  
sales up 7.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Limited: Same-store sales up 10 percent, total sales up 8  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Gap: Same-store sales up 8 percent, total sales up 28 percent.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
