<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elvis Items To Be Auctioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Elvis may have left the building, but his Army  
fatigues could soon hang in your closet. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 2,000 of the King's never displayed treasures from his  
Graceland compound will be sold at auction in October at Las Vegas' 
MGM Grand hotel, Gurnsey's auction house announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	The bulk of the items to be auctioned are record, movie and  
performance contracts, including the publishing contract for 
``Heartbreak Hotel'' and letters from Marilyn Monroe, Frank Sinatra 
and President Kennedy. 
</P>
<P>
	There will also be some classic pieces like a vintage yellow  
Cadillac station wagon with wood-grain side panels and an ivory 
wool cape decorated with rhinestones and an American eagle. 
</P>
<P>
	No minimum prices were set. Arlan Ettinger, owner of the  
Manhattan auction house that also sold Mark McGwire's 70th home run 
ball for just over $3 million in January, said he expected the 
prices to range from affordable to six figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The items were selected to help weed out the collection at  
Graceland. 
</P>
<P>
	Money raised from the auction will help build houses for  
homeless families in Memphis. The development, called Presley 
Place, will cost about $1.5 million to build. It will be operated 
by the Metropolitan Interfaith Association and will provide 
counseling and job training for a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Before Elvis -- who died Aug. 16, 1977, at age 42 -- was  
discovered, the Presley family lived for several years in a federal 
housing project in Memphis. 
</P>
<P>
	The items will be previewed in Las Vegas beginning Sept. 28. The  
auction is slated for Oct. 8-10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
