<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Truck Carrying Explosives Overturns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) -- An overturned tractor-trailer on the  
Washington area's busiest intersection forced people to sit and 
wait in traffic for hours -- but not Raina Alexis Cooper. 
</P>
<P>
	The 8-pound baby girl was born Wednesday in her parents' car  
while they were stuck in traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	The driving nightmare began at 4 a.m. Wednesday when a  
tractor-trailer carrying 20 tons of explosive fireworks powder 
overturned at an interchange where 370,000 drivers converge daily 
at the intersections of Interstates 95, 395 and 495. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities evacuated more than 50 homes near the accident site  
and traffic was backed up for 20 miles. The interchange was 
reopened and the residents were allowed back in their homes about 
8:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	The tractor-trailer's driver, Juanita Kirk, 41, was charged with  
reckless driving, although police have not determined the cause of 
the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	The traffic stretched across the Potomac River into Maryland,  
where Venita Cooper and her husband Wesley were headed to Bethesda 
Naval Hospital for the birth of Rainia. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooper helped deliver his third child in the car.  
</P>
<P>
	``She just fell asleep and we waited,'' Cooper said. ``It seemed  
like forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A rescue crew, delayed in traffic, arrived about 20 minutes  
later. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
