<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Comments on the Closing of Fenway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Some comments on the eventual demise of Fenway Park.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know what the Red Sox mean to the people of New England, and  
I know Fenway Park is part of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Red Sox general manager John Harrington, before choking up as  
he recalled his father taking him on the trolley to the ballpark. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	``When it is official and they do have a new building and this  
thing is going into the dumpster, that will be very sad for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Dan Shaughnessy, The Boston Globe columnist and author of  
``The Curse of the Bambino'' and ``At Fenway: Dispatches from Red 
Sox Nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	``It really does seem like they're trying to preserve the best  
of the past. It's still going to be in the city, it's still going 
to be open air, it's still going to have real grass, the seats will 
still be near the field and we need the revenue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Doris Kearns Goodwin, historian and Red Sox season ticket  
holder 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	``I will cry and really mourn the passing of it, but I think for  
Boston and for its favorite team, it's shedding its old skin and 
getting a new skin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Ken Burns, producer of the film ``Baseball'' and co-author of  
book by the same title. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a strange ballpark. There are some really bad seats in  
the far reaches. ... It's pretty grungy down there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Roger Angell, author of ``Five Seasons'' and ``The Summer  
Game,'' commenting on the park. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about time they did it. It's like an old man who passes  
away. You have to let go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Pedro Martinez, Red Sox pitcher.  
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Fenway's awesome. I like the old Fenway just like I liked the  
old Garden.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- David Doucette, 28-year-old Red Sox fan  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
