<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Markets Rise, Tokyo Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets edged higher Thursday,  
but Tokyo, the region's biggest bourse, fell after a three-day 
rally. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 190.49  
points, or 1.16 percent, to close at 16,227.50. The index had 
gained 9.49 points, or 0.06 percent, on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	With few incentives to encourage buying, many investors remained  
on the sidelines awaiting U.S. employment data, due out Friday in 
Washington, for clues on the direction of U.S. interest rates and 
stock prices, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asian markets are closely watching whether the U.S. Federal  
Reserve will raise interest rates later this month to alleviate 
inflationary pressure. Higher U.S. rates would encourage investors 
to shift funds from Asia to higher yielding U.S. fixed income 
instruments. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the U.S. dollar rose against the Japanese  
yen after rumors that China might devalue the yuan emerged once 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	In late trading, the dollar bought 121.54 yen, up 1.00 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
121.33 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The People's Bank of China, China's central bank, later  
reaffirmed the government's commitment to a stable currency. 
</P>
<P>
	In Indonesia, the Jakarta Stock Exchange Composite Index soared  
2.3 percent, or 13.254 points, to 587.569, as a massive rally by 
parliamentary frontrunner Megawati Sukarnoputri concluded 
peacefully. Declining interest rates contributed to the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The election campaign, grouping 48 political parties, will end  
Saturday, and voters head to the polls June 7. Some had worried 
that Thursday's rally, which gridlocked the capital, would turn 
chaotic. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, share prices edged up slightly amid talks among  
local brokers that the United States may not raise interest rates 
this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index gained 0.1 percent, or 12.97  
points, to close at 12,471.61. It gained 0.8 percent Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai share prices rose in brisk trading on reports of  
falling inflation. The SET index rose 1.19 points, or 0.2 percent, 
to 476.05. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares fell slightly in the absence of  
fresh incentives. The Composite Index fell 4.96 points, or 0.67 
percent, to 744.50. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks fell as investors unloaded shares on  
fears of a possible U.S. interest rate hike. The PSE index fell 
33.36 points, or 1.4 percent, to 2,382.41. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: South Korean stocks rose for the eighth consecutive day,  
encouraged by expectations of an economic recovery and stable local 
interest rates. The Kospi index rose 3.21 points, or 0.41 percent, 
to 778.21. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares rose slightly as retail investors sold their  
shares to cash in profits. The Straits Times Index rose 14.74 
points, or 0.8 percent, to 1,942.10. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares rose, buoyed by gains in media and  
selected industrial stocks. The All Ordinaries index rose 26.9 
points, or 0.92 percent, to 2,941.6. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Taiwan shares rose for the fourth straight day, led by  
technology shares, which rallied on news of a potential alliance 
between two leading technology companies, Taiwan Semiconductor 
Manufacturing Co. and Acer Semiconductor Manufacturing Inc. The 
Weighted Price Index rose 84.88 points, or 1.1 percent, to 
7,572.91. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares ended flat after international  
ratings agency Moody's Investors Service put the domestic currency 
ratings of Telecom Corp. of New Zealand Ltd. on watch. The NZSE-40 
Capital Index rose 1.11 points, or 0.05 percent, to 2,129.07. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
