<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pilots Warned About MD-80 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One major airline has reminded its pilots they  
can turn up the automatic brakes on MD-80 aircraft, a reminder that 
came after a number of them overshot runways. 
</P>
<P>
	One such model, an American Airlines MD-82, crashed and ran off  
the runway in Little Rock, Ark., on Tuesday, killing nine people. 
The cause remains under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta Air Lines, which flies 120 custom versions of the MD-80,  
the MD-88, recently instituted new procedures in which both members 
of the two-person flight crew must ensure that the spoilers are 
armed before touchdown. Spoilers, which pop up from the wing, 
disrupt air flow and slow a plane. 
</P>
<P>
	A Delta captain, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the  
procedure was instituted because it's hard to tell whether the 
spoiler lever is armed or in the stowed position. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the airline reminded its pilots that the autobrake switch  
has a ``maximum'' position and pilots shouldn't be afraid to use 
that highest setting if there is the slightest doubt. Autobrakes 
slow a plane evenly and are used on most landings. 
</P>
<P>
	Pilots are often reluctant to use the maximum setting because it  
slows a plane rapidly, which can alarm passengers. The switch is 
usually positioned to ``light'' or ``medium'' unless it's raining. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always the pilot's decision, but they've been pushing the  
use of max autobrakes when landing,'' the captain said. ``They 
basically say, `You have all these tools available. It's better to 
use what you've got than to explain it before the'' federal 
transportation regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	The MD-80 series, which includes the MD-81, -82, -83, -87 and  
-88, was designed by McDonnell Douglas, which was bought in 1997 by 
the Boeing Co. Spokesman John Thom said he had not heard of any 
problems with the planes overshooting runways, and only nine of 
1,167 delivered have been lost in accidents, including the American 
Airlines plane in Tuesday night's incident. 
</P>
<P>
	A Delta spokeswoman did not immediately return a call seeking  
comment on the new procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	The Delta captain said there is nothing inherently wrong with  
the MD-80 series, which he has flown for several years. However, 
because the plane is a smaller aircraft used on short to medium 
routes, many airlines use them for the first assignment they give 
their new captains. 
</P>
<P>
	Paired with a more junior pilot, ``that means less experience in  
the cockpit,'' the captain said. 
</P>
<P>
	That can be particularly troublesome in bad weather, which has  
been a factor in many of the MD-80 overshoots. 
</P>
<P>
	On March 15, a Korean Air plane skidded off a runway while  
landing in Pohang, South Korea, during a heavy rain. On Dec. 24, a 
Delta plane skidded off a snow-covered runway in Providence, R.I. 
</P>
<P>
	In November 1996, planes owned by Delta and American skidded off  
snow-covered runways in Cleveland on consecutive days. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
