<DOCNO> APW19990603.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 15:31:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Jones and Johnson To Square Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BILOXI, Miss. (AP) -- Roy Jones Jr. saw this fight coming almost  
a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	He knew when Reggie Johnson moved in with him and his father and  
began training with Roy Jones that the boxers were on a collision 
course. 
</P>
<P>
	``What my father didn't understand was that it was inevitable  
that we would one day meet in the ring,'' Jones said Thursday. ``I 
knew it right away. I knew we were both headed for the championship 
and we'd have to settle it between us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday night, Jones, who holds the WBC and WBA light  
heavyweight championships, and Johnson, the IBF titleholder, will 
unify the title for the first time in 14 years. The last time there 
was an undisputed champion was in 1985, when Michael Spinks held 
the titles. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighters have a tempestuous history. Both trained with the  
elder Jones in 1991 and even sparred against each other. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones had been trained by his father throughout his amateur and  
early pro career. But he called his father's decision to bring 
Johnson into his training program the final straw that broke their 
relationship. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he wanted to bring someone in to get me ready for the race,  
it shouldn't have been the horse I was going to have to run 
against,'' Jones said. 
</P>
<P>
	Father and son had a bitter split, not even speaking to each  
other for years. Although they have since reconciled and now talk, 
Jones said many of their ties remain broken. He doesn't blame 
Johnson, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not at all. We both have a lot of respect for each other,''  
Jones said. ``There aren't going to be any mind games or any other 
kind of games. There's just going to be some big boxing. This is 
going to be the real deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, 30, is 39-1 as a professional, with 33 knockouts. He has  
successfully defended his WBC title three times, the WBC 
championship once. He won his last fight by stopping New York City 
policeman Rick Frazier. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 32, is 39-5-1 with 24 KOs. He is 7-4 in championship  
fights, with all his losses in close, disputed decisions. His last 
fight was Feb. 27 when he took a 12-round unanimous decision 
against top-ranked contender Will Taylor. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be the toughest fight of my life,'' Johnson  
said. ``I have a lot of respect for Roy. I know how tough he is, 
how good he is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reminiscing about their days as sparring partners, Jones said he  
remembered the damage Johnson could do with either hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was very heavyhanded, knockout power in either hand,''  
Jones said. ``He's a big puncher, a good defensive fighter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson said Jones was a guy who could hurt you fast and often.  
</P>
<P>
	``He has extremely fast hands, he's very smart,'' Johnson said.  
``He's a little flashier than I am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two other title fights are on Saturday night's card. IBF  
cruiserweight champion Arthur Williams will make his first defense 
against Vasilly Jirov, the fourth-ranked challenger. 
</P>
<P>
	IBF lightweight champion Roberto Garcia will defend against No.  
2 Derrick Gainer. 
</P>
<P>
	HBO will broadcast the fights.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0252 </DOCNO>
