<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Accepts Peace Plan  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Caving in to Russian and Western  
demands, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic accepted a peace 
plan for Kosovo today that is designed to end his mass expulsions 
of ethnic Albanians and 11 weeks of NATO airstrikes. Even though 
the draft appeared to signal a victory for NATO, President Clinton 
and other U.S. officials reacted cautiously, waiting for signs that 
Milosevic would begin pulling his troops out and allow the return 
of more than 855,000 refugees. Clinton said NATO airstrikes would 
continue until Milosevic produced ``real results.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Conflict Gives Raytheon Big Contracts  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The missiles and bombs raining down on Serb forces  
in Yugoslavia could add up to big money for the Raytheon Co., whose 
officials estimate they could gain about $1 billion in new 
contracts to replace munitions used in the Balkans. While 10-figure 
defense outlays are nothing new in the United States, Raytheon's 
direct link between military action and possible revenues cast the 
Kosovo conflict in a new economic light. 

</P>
<P>
	Discovery Leaves Space Station  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Space shuttle Discovery and its crew  
glided away from the international space station today after 
getting the place ready for its first permanent residents next 
year. The connecting latches popped open, upon command, as the two 
spacecraft soared above Mongolia. Discovery was linked to the space 
station for six days. The astronauts have one last job before they 
return to Earth early Sunday: They will release a mirror-studded 
satellite on Saturday that students around the world will track as 
part of an education project. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Moves Closer to N.Y. Run  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton intends to form an  
exploratory committee in early July, preparing her for a potential 
Senate campaign in New York next year, a top adviser said today. 
She would be the first sitting first lady to run for public office. 
Harold Ickes, who is heading Mrs. Clinton's political operation, 
disclosed her plans after Rep. Nita Lowey said, in a telephone call 
to the first lady, that she would seek re-election to the House. 
That leaves the Democratic Senate field clear for Mrs. Clinton. 

</P>
<P>
	NTSB Says Doomed Jet Was Briefed  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- The pilot of the American Airlines jet  
that crashed in a thunderstorm was warned twice about a dangerous 
wind shear and received more notice than usual of bad conditions as 
he brought the plane in for a landing, a federal investigator said 
today. Investigators are analyzing the conversation between the 
tower and the pilot, information from the plane's flight data 
recorder and evidence from the wreckage to try to determine why 
Flight 1420 skidded off the runway at the Little Rock airport, 
killing nine people, including the pilot. 

</P>
<P>
	Supermarket Rampage Leaves Four Dead  
</P>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- A man dressed in camouflage blasted away with a  
pump-action shotgun as he roamed through a supermarket before 
sunrise today, killing four employees and critically wounding one. 
Police arrested the gunman in the parking lot after talking him out 
of killing himself. Officers were alerted by a 911 call from inside 
the Albertsons supermarket as shots were being fired. They 
confronted a man with a goatee and shaved head who walked out the 
door with a shotgun. The victims were all shot at point-blank 
range, Officer Steve Meriwether said. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Senator Urges Cuban Ties  
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Wrapping up a rare visit to Cuba by a Republican  
U.S. senator, Arlen Specter today said he would work to increase 
ties between the United States and the island nation in the areas 
of public health and drug interdiction. ``It's important that 
people like me in the U.S. Senate know what is going on in Cuba,'' 
the Pennsylvania senator said. During his two-day visit to the 
communist country, Specter met for more than six-and-a-half hours 
with President Fidel Castro. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 85.80  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks closed higher today on strong  
sales at the nation's largest retailers. The Dow industrials ended 
at 10,663.69, up 85.80. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 
1,597-1,316. Market indexes held steady after the NYSE announced it 
will not adopt extended trading hours until at least 2000. The 
Nasdaq was at 2,403.73, down 28.68. 

</P>
<P>
	Malone Wins Bittersweet MVP Award  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Karl Malone today won his second NBA Most  
Valuable Player award in three years. Despite posting his lowest 
scoring and rebounding numbers in over a decade, he edged fellow 
big men Alonzo Mourning of Miami and Tim Duncan of San Antonio in 
the voting by 118 North American media members. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ANDREW DAMPF  

  	   	
</P>
