<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Rights Leader Pleads to Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- A civil rights leader who helped blacks  
gain voting rights and get elected to offices in Alabama was 
sentenced to six months in federal prison for vote fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Spiver Gordon, 59, who lost his post as a Eutaw City Councilman  
after pleading guilty in the federal vote fraud case, also was 
fined $2,000 on Wednesday and required to serve three years on 
supervised probation when he leaves prison. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, Gordon was a field lieutenant in the state for the  
Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. in the fight for voting rights. Gordon 
is one of six Greene County residents, including County Commission 
Chairman Garria Spencer, who pleaded guilty to vote fraud charges 
stemming from the 1994 general election. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, a Southern Christian Leadership Conference vice  
president, admitted that he solicited a person who lived outside of 
Greene County to fill out an absentee ballot and list a Greene 
County address on it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
