<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Chinese Police Detain Dissidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese police detained dissidents, closely  
watched others and reportedly broke up one attempt at public 
mourning today, the 10th anniversary of the night soldiers shot 
their way into Beijing to end democracy demonstrations in Tiananmen 
Square. 
</P>
<P>
	The entirely state-controlled media made no mention of the  
sensitive anniversary. Families of people killed in the military 
assault planned private memorials at home, despite the presence of 
plainclothes security agents outside their doors. 
</P>
<P>
	About 50 people, some wearing the white flowers that are a sign  
of mourning, gathered in a park in the eastern city of Hangzhou to 
remember the crackdown's victims, the Hong Kong-based Information 
Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Plainclothes police broke up the gathering, beat one 70-year-old  
man who resisted and took him and two others away, the group said. 
Police refused to confirm the incident. But in recent days, 
repression against dissidents has increased, especially in 
Hangzhou, a center for democracy campaigners who have tried to 
organize an opposition party. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, authorities have questioned nearly 100 activists and  
warned them against holding memorials and have detained at least 
34, the group said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among six people held Wednesday was Peng Cheng, a construction  
company manager recently fired for collecting 190 names on a 
petition demanding the government stop condemning the 1989 
protests. 
</P>
<P>
	After seven weeks of demonstrations that brought 1 million  
people to Tiananmen Square, soldiers swept through Beijing late on 
June 3, 1989, to dislodge the protesters. 
</P>
<P>
	By the dawn of June 4, soldiers and tanks reached the square,  
killing hundreds on the way. The true number of casualties is not 
known. The communist government has never given a credible account. 
</P>
<P>
	Police go on heightened alert every year as the anniversary  
approaches. This year, authorities fear dissidents could exploit 
public discontent over unemployment and corruption. State-run media 
this week have reiterated President Jiang Zemin's call for 
``stability above all else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dissidents have called on ordinary Chinese to wear plain  
clothing, light candles and perform other minor acts to commemorate 
the victims of the military assault. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hangzhou, five activists who tried to donate blood as a  
memorial gesture were turned away because the blood center did not 
want to take part in a political act, the South China Morning Post 
in Hong Kong reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Two police sat in chairs near the entrance to the Beijing  
apartment of Ding Zilin and Jiang Peikun, retired professors whose 
17-year-old son was killed in the crackdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Visitors were turned away and their phone line was cut, said Su  
Bingxian, a woman whose 21-year-old son was shot to death in the 
assault. All three parents have urged the government to re-examiner 
the killings. 
</P>
<P>
	Ding and Jiang traditionally have marked the night quietly at  
home by cooking their son's favorite dinner. Ms. Su said she and 
her other children would light candles in their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiananmen Square, a broad concrete expanse in the heart of the  
city, was quiet today. It is being resurfaced and is blocked off by 
a wall of corrugated metal. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao accused some Western  
media for using the anniversary to spread ``anti-China 
propaganda.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In the political turmoil which took place in 1989, some of the  
anti-Chinese forces played an inglorious role. They did not have 
their way, and they will not have their way now,'' Zhu said at a 
routine briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	Police ordered hotels, offices and apartment buildings allowed  
to receive CNN in Beijing to stop carrying the cable broadcasts 
until June 8 because of reports about the anniversary. In Shanghai, 
some foreign newspapers delivered to hotels had articles and 
pictures snipped out. 
  	   	
</P>
