<DOCNO> APW19990603.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Reporters Ordered Jailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A judge ruled Thursday that two reporters for The  
Atlanta Journal-Constitution are in contempt of court and ordered 
them jailed for refusing to disclose sources for stories about 
former Olympic bombing suspect Richard Jewell. 
</P>
<P>
	Fulton County Judge John Mather's order to jail Kathy Scruggs  
and Ron Martz was stayed indefinitely when the newspaper 
immediately filed its intent to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Jewell, who was working as a security guard at the 1996 Atlanta  
Olympics, is suing the Journal-Constitution for libel. He was 
identified as a suspect in the fatal bombing in Centennial Olympic 
Park, but was eventually cleared by the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	He claims he was libeled ``in a series of false and defamatory  
articles which portrayed him as an individual with a bizarre 
employment history and an aberrant personality who was likely 
guilty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judge ruled last year that reporters are not legally  
protected from naming their sources when the reporters are parties 
to a lawsuit or criminal case. In an order on March 16, the judge 
gave the reporters 60 days to disclose their sources. 
</P>
<P>
	``The court has shown defendants considerable patience, but  
there arrives a point at which the authority of the court and 
respect for the commands of that court must be vindicated,'' Mather 
wrote in Thursday's order. 
</P>
<P>
	He ordered the reporters jailed for civil contempt until they  
disclose their confidential sources. Editor Ron Martin pledged the 
newspaper would challenge the order. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is really an important issue for us,'' Martin said.  
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper's attorney, Peter Canfield, has said the reporting  
was accurate. He has asked the judge to dismiss the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Jewell attorney Lin Wood praised the order as ``clearly a  
significant victory for Richard Jewell in his continued pursuit of 
the truth from the Journal-Constitution and its reporters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood said Jewell recently started his own security firm and also  
serves as a fishing guide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 07:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DC To Get Alexander Pushkin Statue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A monument to Alexander Pushkin, sometimes  
called the Russian Shakespeare, will go up this year on the campus 
of George Washington University in celebration of the 200th 
anniversary of his birth. 
</P>
<P>
	Groundbreaking in front of the university library is set for  
Friday, two days before Pushkin's actual birthday. The monument, a 
statue of the poet in a frock coat and elaborate neckcloth, will be 
more than 11 feet high and will include an image of Pegasus, the 
winged horse symbolic of poetry. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having the statue may be more important for Russia than the  
next loan from the World Bank,'' said sculptor Alexander Burganov. 
He spoke to a small group representing the university and the 
American-Russian Cultural Cooperation Foundation, headed by former 
Rep. James Symington, D-Mo, chief of protocol in President Lyndon 
Johnson's White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Burganov is also doing a figure of the poet for the front of the  
Pushkin House on the Arbat, Moscow's broad pedestrian avenue. 
Pushkin died in 1837 from a wound in a duel brought on by rumors 
that his wife Natalya was unfaithful. 
</P>
<P>
	A one-time official in the czar's foreign ministry, Pushkin was  
frequently in trouble with Russian authorities for his democratic 
opinions. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Rollberg, who teaches Slavic languages at the university,  
said Pushkin is known more for his poetry and stories than for his 
one big drama, ``Boris Godunov,'' which has become a standard of 
the opera repertory. He said Pushkin was largely responsible for 
transforming the Russian language into the eloquent medium it has 
become for poets and novelists of the past 200 years. 
</P>
<P>
	His novel in verse, ``Eugene Onegin,'' has been translated in  
English repeatedly and also has been made into an opera. Its witty, 
dramatic style owes much to the English poet Lord Byron, some of 
whose work Pushkin translated into Russian. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian empire of Pushkin's time is already represented  
among Washington's memorials by a statue of the poet Taras 
Shevchenko. His place in the literature of the Ukrainian language 
is similar to Pushkin's in Russian. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:51:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Supermarket Rampage Leaves Four Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- A man dressed in camouflage blasted away with a  
pump-action shotgun as he roamed through a supermarket before 
sunrise Thursday, killing four employees and critically wounding 
one. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested the gunman in the parking lot after talking him  
out of killing himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers were alerted by a 911 call from inside the Albertsons  
supermarket as shots were being fired. They confronted a man with a 
goatee and shaved head who walked out the door with a shotgun. 
</P>
<P>
	``He placed the gun to his head and officers were able to talk  
him into surrendering,'' Lt. Rick Alba said. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims were all shot at point-blank range, Officer Steve  
Meriwether said. Some were chased. 
</P>
<P>
	Zane Floyd, 23, who was honorably discharged from the Marines at  
Camp Pendleton, Calif., last July, was arrested for investigation 
of murder. He worked as a security guard and part-time as a bouncer 
at a bar. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators were baffled as to what triggered the rampage,  
Alba said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have not found any connection between Floyd and the  
victims -- three men and a woman -- and there was no indication he 
had had any run-ins at the store. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd was fired by Affirmative Security on May 14. Owner Laura  
Sellers said Floyd started missing shifts and acting differently 
after a while, but added ``there was not one incident of 
aggression, violence or abrupt behavior ... We're not looking at a 
bad boy or someone who would go insane at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't pick up his belongings and final paycheck until  
Wednesday night, Sellers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was agitated last night, a little bit more sarcastic,'' she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fearing the gunman had an accomplice, police took at least three  
hours to search and clear the store, finding two employees hiding 
in a walk-in vegetable cooler. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-five people, including 14 employees, were in the  
42,000-square foot store when the 911 call was made to police at 
5:16 a.m., Clark County Sheriff Jerry Keller said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were people hiding throughout the store in various  
locations,'' Meriwether said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last weekend, Floyd moved from an apartment into a guest house  
behind his parents' home just two blocks from the supermarket, 
friends said. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's all they talked about is when he would be coming home  
from leave. They did everything they could for him,'' said neighbor 
Cathy Downey. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd served four years in the Marines. After the Marines, he  
started college but dropped out, Downey said. Floyd had worked one 
day a week for the past month at Sneakers, a sports bar in Las 
Vegas, said bar manager Tom Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a regular 23-year-old guy who likes to party and hang out  
just like me. I don't understand what happened,'' said Tony 
Marquez, a fellow bouncer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
