<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shuttle Undocks From Space Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) -- Their supply run to the  
international space station over, Discovery's astronauts enjoyed 
some time off today after the shuttle undocked from the outpost and 
soared away. 
</P>
<P>
	The only job left for the astronauts is the deployment early  
Saturday of a mirror-studded satellite that students worldwide will 
track as part of an education project. Discovery and its crew of 
seven are due home the next day. 
</P>
<P>
	The shuttle separated from the space station Thursday evening,  
six days after Discovery made the historic first docking with the 
fledgling outpost. The connecting latches popped open upon command 
as the two spacecraft soared above Mongolia. 
</P>
<P>
	With pilot Rick Husband at the controls, Discovery took 2 1/2 slow  
laps around the gleaming space station so the crew could photograph 
the exterior. Then Husband fired the engines, and the shuttle flew 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	``You all certainly left the international space station in much  
better shape than you found it,'' Mission Control told the 
departing astronauts. 
</P>
<P>
	While the spacecraft were linked, the astronauts transported 2  
tons of supplies to the interior and exterior of the station. They 
also fixed a broken radio, replaced battery packs and installed 
foam insulation to reduce fan noise. 
</P>
<P>
	The work was in preparation for the first permanent station  
residents, who are scheduled to arrive next March for a five-month 
stay. The living quarters for that three-man crew are due in 
November, followed by another shuttle visit a month later to 
deliver additional supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	The first station component, the Russian-built Zarya control  
module, was launched in November, followed a month later by the 
second part, the American Unity node. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA estimates 45 launches and more than 160 spacewalks will be  
needed over the next five years to assemble the complex. Once 
completed, the 16-nation outpost will have a mass of 1 million 
pounds, be longer than a football field and house up to seven 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	Flight controllers said the work of Discovery's crew went a long  
way toward preparing the station for a long-term presence in space. 
</P>
<P>
	``Space station is not going to be just about those large  
assembly pieces, but it's going to be a lot about supporting a crew 
on orbit,'' Mission Control's Jeff Bantle said. ``This is a mission 
that took a big step in making the station a home.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
