<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 05:40:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four Seasons Wins James Beard Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- They have wined and dined world leaders, top  
celebrities and Manhattan's social elite. Now Alex von Bidder and 
Julian Niccolini have their own claim to fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Their restaurant, The Four Seasons, recently won the 1999 James  
Beard Award as the nation's outstanding restaurant. 
</P>
<P>
	Von Bidder said winning the award -- the food industry's  
equivalent of the Oscars -- was a ``Roberto Benigni moment,'' with 
Maguy Le Coze of Le Bernardin filling in as Sophia Loren at the 
podium. 
</P>
<P>
	But after 40 years as one of New York's top restaurants, The  
Four Seasons was hardly an underdog. 
</P>
<P>
	The Four Seasons is the only Manhattan restaurant named an  
architectural landmark. And the physical space is as impressive as 
the food prepared by executive chef Christian Albin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grill Room -- where the term ``power lunch'' was born -- is a  
warm, wood-paneled room. In contrast, the Pool Room is elegant and 
tranquil, with a white-marble pool centerpiece beneath a canopy of 
trees that change with the seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis called the Four Seasons her  
``cathedral,'' where she could find solace, von Bidder said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ronald and Nancy Reagan are among von Bidder's all-time favorite  
customers. Richard Holbrooke, who is awaiting Senate confirmation 
as the new U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, is a familiar 
face. 
</P>
<P>
	Von Bidder said he still can't get used to the idea that  
presidents, first ladies and high-ranking diplomats dine at the 
restaurant when they visit Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	However, there are still some customers that command a second  
glance. 
</P>
<P>
	For Niccolini, it was Sharon Stone.  
</P>
<P>
	Niccolini and von Bidder said they have grown accustomed to the  
attention their restaurant gets in the gossip columns, as well as 
the accolades it receives from the culinary world. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're the ultimate New York experience,'' Niccolini  
said. ``Even if people find out about us from Page Six (the New 
York Post's gossip page), they should come. We make an extra effort 
to seat everyone. We're here to take care of customers, whomever 
they are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Von Bidder said they have never forgotten that they are in a  
service business. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a notion that a fancy restaurant is automatically  
snobby, but we really see ourselves as here to please,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Niccolini is the showman of the duo, the comic to von Bidder's  
straight man. And it was Niccolini who was carrying the 
medallion-shaped Beard award in his back pocket the day after the 
ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've worked so long together and we complement each other,''  
von Bidder said. ``I have the patience to renegotiate our lease for 
a year and a half. Julian cannot. He thrives on being a 
troublemaker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Von Bidder spent an uninterrupted hour with an interviewer  
detailing the restaurant's history. Niccolini greeted and charmed, 
and then was off to a wine tasting -- with the award still in his 
pocket. 
</P>
<P>
	``After 23 years, we still have fun, and the customers have fun.  
That's the important thing,'' von Bidder said. ``We get a kick out 
of being with customers so long that we become part of their 
families -- through births, weddings and funerals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The restaurant's most famous clients are treated like valued  
customers. But they are not catered to with the ``yes, ma'am'' and 
``no, sir'' they hear all day -- and they like it. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the guidance of von Bidder, who joined The Four Seasons in  
1976, and Niccolini, who followed a year later, the restaurant's 
interior has been restored to its original 1959 look, designed by 
Philip Johnson and Mies van der Rohe. The kitchen recently 
underwent an extensive renovation. 
</P>
<P>
	Being the best is a process. Winning the James Beard Award  
doesn't signal that there is no room for improvement, von Bidder 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Four Seasons' pledge is ``may we always change,'' allowing  
the restaurant to continually undergo a cycle of renewal that keeps 
it fresh and contemporary, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the changes are subtle -- a varied preparation of the  
soft-shell crab special in the springtime or a change in the shade 
of the carpet -- so a customer is never jarred by the unexpected. 
</P>
<P>
	In honor of the restaurant's 40th anniversary, von Bidder is  
updating ``The Four Seasons: A History of America's Premier 
Restaurant,'' with co-author John Mariani. 
</P>
<P>
	A star-studded birthday bash is planned in June. Seagram  
president and CEO Edgar Bronfman Jr. and Vanity Fair editor Graydon 
Carter are in charge of the guest list. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be better than the Oscar party. We'll have big stars  
and good food,'' von Bidder said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 14:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cocoa Up As Producer Selling Slows  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Cocoa futures prices soared more than 10 percent Thursday on the  
Board of Trade of the City of New York as massive producer selling 
began to weaken, signaling supplies may shrink in the weeks ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, grain and soybean futures also rose sharply,  
while energy products were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures posted their biggest gains in nearly nine years,  
recovering from recent six-year lows, as cocoa traders and 
exporters reported fewer arrivals of beans at ports in Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivory Coast, the world's largest cocoa grower, in the week ended  
May 30 shipped an estimated 7,540 metric tons, down by nearly half 
the week's previous 14,280 metric tons. Exporters in that country 
said there likely wouldn't be much more to sell from the midyear 
crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghana, another large grower, also is expected to run out of  
shipments soon, providing supply-side relief to a market that has 
been pressured by a bumper world crop and weaker world demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Importers from Russia and Asia have sharply curtailed purchases  
in recent months because of economic problems, while Western 
chocolate makers have been content to sit on the sidelines as they 
waited for prices to reach a bottom. 
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa for July delivery rose $97, or 10.5 percent, to $1,023 a  
ton 
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures rose sharply on the Chicago Board of  
Trade amid forecasts for weather conditions that could reduce this 
year's crop production. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service's latest 10-day forecast calls for  
above-normal temperatures and normal to below-normal rainfall in 
Midwest growing regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Hot, dry weather could stress young crops early, and market  
participants are beginning to worry a dry weather pattern in some 
eastern growing states could sharply reduce production on what is 
expected to be bumper acreage. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, substantial rainfall in western growing states such as  
North Dakota and Iowa was keeping farmers from completing final 
planting. Wheat futures in particular benefited from such delays in 
spring wheat plantings, which come as the window of opportunity for 
getting those crops into the ground comes to a close. Wheat also 
gained amid expectations heavy recent rainfall in the Plains may 
have reduced the quality of the winter wheat crop. 
</P>
<P>
	July wheat rose 7 3/4 cents to $2.61 a bushel; July corn jumped 6 1/2  
cents to $2.23 1/4 a bushel; July oats rose 3 3/4 cents to $1.26 1/4 a 
bushel; July soybeans rose 6 3/4 cents to $4.65 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Unleaded gasoline futures retreated on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange after weekly figures showed an unexpected rise in 
inventories -- at a time when they usually begin to fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Petroleum Institute reported inventories last week  
rose a sharp 2.32 million barrels to 222.27 million barrels. 
</P>
<P>
	While the figures do not factor in the beginning of the peak  
summer driving period, which began on Memorial Day, investors had 
bet that demand in the week leading up to that period also would be 
higher as Americans geared up to take to the roads. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil was virtually unchanged after inventories showed an  
unexpected decline. 
</P>
<P>
	July unleaded gasoline fell .37 cent to 48.60 cents a gallon;  
July crude rose 9 cents to $16.74 a barrel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 12:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
