<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Actor Sweetens 'Hurrah at Last' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Laurie, the protagonist and novelist-hero of  
``Hurrah at Last,'' Richard Greenberg's uneven and slightly sour 
new comedy, has done enough suffering for art. 
</P>
<P>
	Show him the money, preferably a nice fat advance for adapting  
one of his less-than best sellers into a film. Laurie would like to 
eat regularly and pay his rent on time. The man could be consumed 
by opportunism. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortunately, Laurie is played by Peter Frechette, an actor of  
uncommon ability at portraying the neurotic -- with a great deal of 
charm. Whenever the production, which the Roundabout Theater 
Company has opened at off-Broadway's Gramercy Theater, threatens to 
turn into a whinefest, Frechette pulls it back from the sobs and 
the self-pity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a savage, bitter man with a lump of coal where my heart  
should be,'' Laurie complains. You don't quite believe him, 
particularly when the playwright gives him some wry, often funny 
observations about the vicissitudes of life. When a friend insists 
money can't buy happiness, Laurie retorts, ``But it upgrades 
despair so beautifully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Laurie certainly has things to worry about. The man is destitute  
and desperate. And physically sick with a mysterious illness. He is 
almost delirious, as he feverishly contemplates the success of his 
relatives and friends. 
</P>
<P>
	There are sister Thea and brother-in-law Eamon who live in an  
expensive loft but still are unhappy. They can't conceive a child, 
a fact that has put a strain on their marriage. 
</P>
<P>
	There are Laurie's squabbling parents, an older Jewish couple  
for whom fighting became a way of life. Mom originally is from 
Brooklyn, Dad from the Bronx, and those differences were enough to 
start them battling. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of all, there is his good friend, Oliver, a fabulously  
successful playwright who has been hired to adapt one of Laurie's 
novels for the movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver is one of those cheerfully intense people, forever  
proclaiming friendship and announcing he would do anything for a 
good buddy -- anything, except tell him how much money he was paid 
for the screenplay of Oliver's book. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenberg seems to believe that telling how much money one makes  
is the last taboo. People will do almost anything else, including 
shedding their clothes, before revealing their finances. In one of 
the play's funniest scenes, Oliver does just that. 
</P>
<P>
	Director David Warren injects a liveliness into ``Hurrah at  
Last,'' even when the dialogue falters. The cast catches his 
spirit. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Michael Valley is hilariously enthusiastic as the  
excessively devoted Oliver. Kevin O'Rourke and Ileen Getz add some 
warmth and commonsense as the infertile couple. Larry Keith and 
Dori Brenner do well as Laurie's parents, roles that teeter on 
stereotypes. Only the talented and vocally strong Judith Blazer 
seems wasted in the underwritten part of Oliver's Italian wife. 
</P>
<P>
	An inconsistent play, this ``Hurrah at Last.'' Often smart and  
funny, it veers into an anger that often seems as indecisive and 
unhappy as its troubled lead character. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
