<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mostly Higher; Dow Up 62.06 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mostly higher on Wall Street today  
as investors turned from the technology stocks that rallied late 
Wednesday to retailers that showed surprising strength in May. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was up 62.06 at  
10,639.95. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was up 5.36 at 1,300.17, and the Nasdaq composite index, 
which is dominated by technology stocks, was down 5.97 at 2,426.44. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Dow fell 18.37 to 10,577.89, but other market  
indicators rose as investors began seeking bargains after two weeks 
of losses. Technology stocks that have been battered recently were 
snapped up at their new, lower prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the volatile Internet companies led the technology sector  
right back down. Amazon.com fell 4 1/8 to 108. 
</P>
<P>
	But the broad market rose as new reports indicated the economy  
is faring well enough to entice consumers to spend, but perhaps not 
so well that the Federal Reserve will have to raise interest rates 
to slow growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's biggest retailers were mostly higher after  
reporting stronger-than-expected sales in May. Wal-Mart rose 1 5/16 
to 45 11/16 and Gap Inc. rose 3 11/16 to 66 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	The market also gained support from a Commerce Department report  
that showed orders to American factories for manufactured goods 
fell 1.2 percent. The decline suggested that the nation's economic 
growth may be slowing a bit. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks have been volatile since the Fed served notice last month  
that it is willing to raise interest rates to cool off the booming 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders remain focused on the Friday morning release of the  
Labor Department's unemployment data. The wage component of the 
report is expected to offer a more pointed indication of whether 
inflation has returned to the U.S. economy. A separate report today 
showed the number of Americans filing new claims for unemployment 
benefits rose slightly last week. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, investors turned to a broad-based range of  
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sure looks like rapid sector rotation,'' said Tom Madden,  
chief investment officer for domestic equities at Federated 
Investors of Pittsburgh. ``The market's tone is better, but there's 
no strong conviction for any sector.'' 
</P>
<P>
	American Express, up 1 3/4 at 120 3/16, and Johnson &AMP; Johnson, up  
1 1/4 at 92 15/16, led the Dow stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron slipped 1/8 to 91 7/8 and Texaco fell 1 13/16 to 62 11/16  
after the companies called off merger talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 566.3 million 
shares, slightly behind Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 3.05 at 623.55, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 3.52 at 774.75. 
</P>
<P>
	Market indexes held steady after the New York Stock Exchange  
announced it will not adopt extended trading hours until at least 
2000. The board that governs the Nasdaq Stock Market expects to 
start an extended schedule as soon as September. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
