<HEADLINE> Ventura Pig Stamp Displeases One </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Gov. Jesse Ventura used a rubber stamp  
depicting a sitting pig to veto legislation, prompting a squeal of 
displeasure from one constituent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura wanted to send the message that the Legislature needs to  
avoid pork-barrel spending. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ramsey County prosecutor Susan Gaertner complained that the  
stamp of the pig was next to a $500,000 appropriation for a new 
domestic violence prosecution program. 
</P>
<P>
	``The message that was received was one of insensitivity to the  
needs of women and children in crisis,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura spokesman John Wodele said the pig stamp was meant to be  
funny and was not necessarily a comment on the worth of the 
proposals. 
  	   	
</P>
