<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hasek Has Everything But a Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Dominik Hasek has won an Olympic gold medal  
and been the NHL's MVP the past two years. He's earned millions of 
dollars and the adoration of fans who marvel at his brilliant 
goaltending. 
</P>
<P>
	But there's one important thing missing from his resume -- the  
Stanley Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	That could change soon because his Buffalo Sabres are getting  
ready to play for the NHL championship against the winner of 
tonight's Game 7 in the Western Conference final between the 
Colorado Avalanche and Dallas Stars. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's hungrier than ever,'' Sabres defenseman Jason Woolley  
said. ``Nothing would compare to winning this thing, and it's nice 
to have him in there with that drive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Stanley Cup championship would be a crowning achievement for  
Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of us feel that there's always a little hole if you  
don't get it,'' Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said. ``He's going to feel 
that way if we don't accomplish what we set out to accomplish. You 
can't say it doesn't bother you if you don't win it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek has won a lot. He's the only goalie in NHL history to win  
two MVPs, and he's a contender to make it three in a row. 
</P>
<P>
	His greatest achievement was leading the Czech Republic to its  
first gold medal in the 1998 Olympics in Nagano, Japan. He earned 
the right to be called the world's best goalie after beating 
Patrick Roy and Canada 2-1 in the semifinal and shutting out Russia 
1-0 for the gold. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as he runs out of things to win, it seems Hasek never runs  
out of things to prove. The Stanley Cup might quiet critics who 
question his heart and tolerance for pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``The gold medal was something I did for my country and the  
Stanley Cup is something I want for all the Buffalo Sabres fans,'' 
said Hasek, who was bothered by a strained groin this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek sat out the first two games of the Eastern Conference  
finals against Toronto because of the groin injury, which also 
forced him to miss 12 games during the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	Some fans wondered just how hurt Hasek really was. The goalie  
bristles at the suggestion that he was faking it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was tough to go to the coach and tell him that I could not  
play, but I'm glad I made the decision,'' he said. ``I could play 
hurt and maybe give up some bad goals and we could lose. I feel 
good about the decision I made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek remains sensitive on the subject. On Thursday, he snapped  
at a reporter who asked him about his exercise routine. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never ride the bike ... I hate the bike,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hasek has the opportunity to answer one other nagging question:  
Who is the best goalie in the NHL? 
</P>
<P>
	Roy is the winningest goalie in playoff history, and Hasek rode  
the bench behind the other goalie he could face in the Stanley Cup 
final, Dallas' Ed Belfour, when both played for Chicago. Hasek 
spent two seasons in Chicago before the Blackhawks traded him to 
Buffalo in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eddie Belfour is a great goaltender and Patrick has won three  
Stanley Cups,'' Hasek said. ``But it doesn't matter to me if we 
play Dallas or Colorado.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek's teammates are simply relieved he's playing.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's good to see that guy back in the net,'' Woolley said.  
``It just breeds confidence throughout our defense. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dom's our general back there. He's attentive, he's vocal. If  
you forget what you're doing, he'll tell you. He's the best I've 
ever seen and the best I've ever played in front of.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
