<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Reporters Ordered Jailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A judge has ordered two Atlanta  
Journal-Constitution reporters to jail for refusing to disclose 
their sources for a story on Richard Jewell, an Olympic bombing 
suspect who was later cleared. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper immediately filed a notice of appeal, blocking the  
jail sentence in the libel suit filed by Jewell. 
</P>
<P>
	Jewell, who was working as a security guard at the 1996 Atlanta  
Olympics, was identified as a suspect in the fatal bombing in 
Centennial Olympic Park but was eventually cleared by the Justice 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Fulton County State Court Judge John Mather ruled last year that  
reporters Kathy Scruggs and Ron Martz are not legally protected 
from naming their sources. In a March 16 order this year, he gave 
the reporters 60 days to disclose their sources. 
</P>
<P>
	``Defendants, through counsel, have conveyed their clear intent  
to continue to disobey the order of this court,'' Mather wrote 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The court has shown defendants considerable patience, but  
there arrives a point at which the authority of the court and 
respect for the commands of that court must be vindicated,'' Mather 
said, ordering them jailed for civil contempt ``until such time as 
they disclose their confidential sources.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Editor Ron Martin pledged the newspaper would challenge the  
order. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is really an important issue for us,'' Martin said.  
</P>
<P>
	Jewell sued in January 1997, claiming he was libeled ``in a  
series of false and defamatory articles which portrayed him as an 
individual with a bizarre employment history and an aberrant 
personality who was likely guilty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper's attorney, Peter Canfield, has said the reporting  
was accurate and has asked that Mather dismiss the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	``The point of our defense is even leaving aside the  
constitutional protection for reporters and their sources, you 
should not even get to that issue in this because you need a false 
statement to get to a libel case,'' Canfield said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Journal-Constitution reporting was accurate,'' he said.  
``He (Jewell) was the focus of the investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jewell attorney Lin Wood praised the order as ``clearly a  
significant victory for Richard Jewell in his continued pursuit of 
the truth from the Journal-Constitution and its reporters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper's appeal ``will do nothing more than create more  
delay,'' Wood said. ``These reporters and their newspaper are going 
to face some very tough decisions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wood said Jewell recently started his own security firm and also  
serves as a fishing guide. The former security guard at first was 
hailed as a hero for spotting the knapsack that held the bomb that 
killed one woman and injured 111 people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
