<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Said Lagging on Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Defense Department faces a backlog of up  
to 600,000 background security investigations that need to be done 
on Pentagon and contractor employees, USA Today reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper said security inquires are made each year on tens of  
thousands of people who need access to sensitive classified 
material, a task handled for the past 27 years by the Defense 
Security Service. 
</P>
<P>
	The most recent director of the agency, Steven Schanzer, was  
reassigned to a post in the Energy Department on Tuesday as USA 
Today was completing its look into the agency's practices, the 
paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Defense Secretary John Hamre told the paper the agency's  
``management hasn't been as strong as we needed'' and that he has 
ordered aides to put in place a plan he hopes will resolve the 
backlog problem within 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of that will involve hiring private investigative firms to  
help with the background checks, something strongly opposed by 
Schanzer. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper said the workforce of the Pentagon security service  
has been cut by about 1,600 over the past decade, to 2,466 now, 
even though the caseload has remained steady. 
</P>
<P>
	The paper said the service does about 120,000 comprehensive  
investigations annually on military, civilian Defense Department 
employees, and contractor personnel needing top secret and secret 
clearances. 
</P>
<P>
	Additionally, it does 400,000 less-comprehensive inquiries a  
year on military recruits and personnel whose jobs are not so 
sensitive. 
</P>
<P>
	USA Today said the backlog has been a problem for years.  
</P>
<P>
	About 2.5 million Defense Department employees and contractor  
personnel have security clearances. 
</P>
<P>
	The Defense Security Service also conducts investigations on  
contractor employees for 22 non-Defense Department government 
agencies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
