<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 15:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Pilot Called a Good Aviator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The American Airlines pilot whose jet crashed in  
a thunderstorm in Little Rock, Ark., was considered a highly 
skilled professional who was unlikely to take risks. 
</P>
<P>
	Since January, Capt. Richard Buschmann, 48, had been a chief  
pilot for American in Chicago, where he and three others were 
responsible for supervising 1,800 pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	Buschmann ``had an unblemished record, an outstanding record,''  
said Carl Price, who retired this year as a chief pilot for 
American. ``He was the type of pilot we put new co-pilots with, 
because he was so experienced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Slitt, an American spokesman, said chief pilots are  
required to fly planes for at least two months a year. They also 
are required to take yearly training, just as regular pilots do. 
</P>
<P>
	When Buschmann's jet crashed Tuesday night, he and the crew of  
the MD-82 had been on duty for 13 1/2 hours, having flown from Chicago 
to Salt Lake City and to Dallas before Little Rock. The airline's 
maximum is 14 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government does not specify a limit for duty time  
but caps pilots' actual flying time at eight hours in a day. They 
also must have eight hours of rest in a 24-hour period. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight was two hours late leaving Dallas-Fort Worth, and  
passengers have questioned Buschmann's decision to land in the 
storm. Federal investigators said they want to know whether the 
desire to end a long day played into the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Spooner, who has flown MD-80s for American since 1988,  
suggested a sudden, unusual wind problem might have caused the 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the wind shifts 180 degrees in minutes, just keeping the  
plane on the runway is tough,'' he said. ``It's one of those human 
factors of being in the wrong place at the wrong time. Probably the 
fact so many survived is a tribute to Capt. Buschmann's 
experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buschmann was a 1972 graduate of the U.S. Air Force Academy,  
served in the Air Force Reserve and reached the rank of lieutenant 
colonel, academy spokesman John Monroe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buschmann was married and had two children, a 20-year-old  
daughter and a 16-year-old son. Friends and neighbors in the 
Chicago suburb of Naperville said Buschmann was a marathon runner, 
enjoyed sailing and was a fixture on the sidelines of his 
children's soccer and baseball games. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 07:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ACLU: Race Profiles Used in Drug War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The war on drugs has resulted in a sharp  
increase in the incidence of racial profiling by law officers 
patrolling highways across the country, civil rights activists say. 
</P>
<P>
	``Skin color has become a substitute for evidence in a way that  
really resembles Jim Crow justice on the nation's highways,'' Ira 
Glasser, head of the American Civil Liberties Union, said Wednesday 
as the group released its report on the controversial practice. 
</P>
<P>
	The Drug Enforcement Administration's ``Operation Pipeline'' has  
trained at least 27,000 law enforcers to use race as a factor in 
spotting potential drug couriers, Glasser said. 
</P>
<P>
	The practice is so common that the minority community has given  
it the derisive term DWB -- ``driving while black or brown,'' or 
stopping minorities for no reason other than their skin color. 
</P>
<P>
	DEA officials in Washington did not immediately return calls for  
comment on ``Operation Pipeline,'' launched in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	The ACLU's report is largely a collection of case studies from  
23 states and not a statistical analysis. 
</P>
<P>
	``By laying out the facts in such detail in this report, we hope  
that we can now get beyond `Is there really a problem?' to `What 
are we as a nation going to do about it?''' said David Harris, a 
University of Toledo law professor and author of the report. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't suggest that this will be easy, only that it is  
necessary if we are to call ourselves a democratic nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ACLU is calling on police departments to voluntarily begin  
documenting incidents of racial profiling. Some already have, 
including the forces in San Diego and San Jose, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, North Carolina became the first state to pass a law  
requiring data collection on all traffic stops. Similar bills have 
been introduced in Congress and in Arkansas, California, 
Connecticut, Florida, Maryland, Massachusetts, New Jersey, 
Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Texas and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're a young black man there's three things you can count  
on in your lifetime: death, taxes and police harassment,'' said 
ACLU lawyer Reginald Shuford. 
</P>
<P>
	The ACLU has pending lawsuits in Maryland, Illinois, New Jersey  
and Oklahoma regarding racial profiling. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 18:51:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Michigan Bumps Up GOP Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Michigan is inching closer to New Hampshire's  
place as the first presidential primary in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Both chambers of the Michigan legislature -- the Senate and the  
House -- have passed a law moving the state's Republican primary to 
Feb. 22, 2000, just one week after the crucial New Hampshire vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Gov. John Engler is expected to sign the bill into  
law. 
</P>
<P>
	With 16 electoral votes, Michigan is one of the largest states  
in the nomination process. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has picked a  
prominent New York fund-raiser and socialite as his presidential 
campaign co-chair. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgette Mosbacher will join former Sen. Warren Rudman of New  
Hampshire, and current Sens. Jon Kyl of Arizona and Chuck Hagel of 
Nebraska as co-chairs of McCain's campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Mosbacher, who made millions in the cosmetics industry, lives in  
New York and serves as a GOP committeewoman from there. She is also 
finance chief of the Republican Governors Association, which 
includes Texas Gov. George W. Bush among its members. 
</P>
<P>
	Her former husband, Robert Mosbacher, was Commerce Secretary  
under former President Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Steve Forbes' new campaign chairman says he  
will not resign from the U.S. Census Monitoring Board despite a 
congressman's concern about possible conflicts of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Blackwell said in a letter to Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., that  
he feels no conflict and that his role on the census board is too 
important to give up. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am uniquely positioned to address the principal problem that  
exists in the 2000 Census -- counting real people where they 
actually live,'' Blackwell wrote in response to a letter from 
Miller urging him to resign from the board. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackwell, who is black, also is keeping his job as Ohio's  
secretary of state. One of his duties is to oversee election 
accuracy throughout the state. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
