<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NYC Police Torture Case Nears Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Defense lawyers for officers charged in the  
beating of a Haitian immigrant accused prosecutors Thursday of 
using one crazed cop's actions to create a case of widespread 
police abuse that did not exist. 
</P>
<P>
	The case ``was not about a culture of police brutality. ... It  
was about one sick, depraved individual and the acts he 
committed,'' said lawyer Stephen Worth in his closing argument. 
</P>
<P>
	Worth's client, Officer Charles Schwarz, is charged with holding  
down Abner Louima while an enraged Officer Justin Volpe sodomized 
the handcuffed prisoner with a broken broom handle. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other officers face lesser civil rights charges in a case  
that shocked the city and sparked demonstrations against police 
brutality. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury was to begin deliberating Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Last week, in a mid-trial guilty plea, Volpe confessed he  
attacked Louima because he thought -- mistakenly -- that he had 
punched him in a melee outside a nightclub. The officer said 
another officer he didn't identify was in the bathroom; Schwarz 
claims he wasn't there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Abner Louima's been vindicated by Justin Volpe's guilty  
plea,'' Worth said. ``Now it's time to vindicate Charles Schwarz 
and stop this scurrilous accusation of him as a sex torturer and a 
member of police brutality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schwarz, 33, along with Thomas Wiese, 35, and Thomas Bruder, 33,  
also is charged in federal court with joining Volpe in beating 
Louima in a patrol car on Aug. 9, 1997. A fourth defendant, Sgt. 
Michael Bellomo, 37, allegedly made false reports to cover up the 
assault on Louima and another Haitian man, Patrick Antoine. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted, Bellomo, Wiese and Bruder face up to 10 years in  
prison. Schwarz, because his charges involve a sexual assault, 
would face a maximum of life without parole. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Loretta Lynch accused Worth of trying to distort the  
evidence and distract the jury. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're very quick to dump on Justin Volpe now that he's no  
longer here,'' Lynch said in her closing statement. ``But that's an 
attempt to shift the focus away from the four defendants still on 
trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors have said that Louima, who recovered from severe  
internal injuries, has consistently told authorities that the 
officer who restrained him in the bathroom was the driver of the 
patrol car he was put in after his arrest; records show the driver 
was Schwarz. 
</P>
<P>
	Two police officer witnesses testified that they saw Schwarz  
leading Louima in the direction of the bathroom on the morning of 
the attack. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
