<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa GOP Poll To Show Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Iowa straw poll this summer will give an  
early indication of the strength of the Republican presidential 
field in a state that launches the nominating season, the state's 
GOP leader said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 12,000 Iowa Republicans will cast straw votes Aug.  
14 in Ames, Iowa. A strong finish can bring some attention to a 
campaign and offer an early measure of various campaign 
organizations' ability to deliver backers to events. 
</P>
<P>
	That's important in a caucus state like Iowa, where  
organizations next Feb. 7 will try to deliver backers to thousands 
of precinct caucuses, which are essentially neighborhood meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	The track record of straw polls predicting results is mixed.  
</P>
<P>
	Televangelist Pat Robertson won one in 1987, giving a signal of  
some early strength among religious conservatives that hadn't been 
apparent earlier. And Texas Sen. Phil Gramm tied for the win in one 
during the last presidential election cycle, then bombed badly when 
real votes were cast. 
</P>
<P>
	Certain to win this poll is the state Republican Party, which is  
collecting $25 for each ticket that allows an activist to vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a huge benchmark test,'' said Kayne Robinson, the Iowa  
Republican Party chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Every major GOP candidate will be on the mock ballots in August.  
All will have time to make a 10-minute speech during the four-hour 
voting period. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the GOP presidential hopefuls have field operations  
running in Iowa, and they are focusing heavily on turning out 
backers. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner in early  
polls, has yet to campaign in the state, and he's only recently put 
a campaign staff in place. Bush has not yet decided whether he will 
actively compete in or even attend the straw poll, said campaign 
spokesman Dave Beckwith. 
</P>
<P>
	``The decision has not been made, and won't be made, until  
Governor Bush visits Iowa and gets a feel for it,'' Beckwith said. 
</P>
<P>
	One major change to the straw poll this year is that will be  
open only to Iowa residents. Previously, anyone of voting age who 
attended could cast a ballot, regardless of residency. 
</P>
<P>
	Since its inception in 1988, the Iowa straw poll has been a  
harbinger of what to expect in the other national primary races, 
Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The truth is, for anyone who comes in the top three -- that is  
a good indicator of how they're doing in Iowa and across the 
country,'' he said. In addition, he said, ``This event will be a 
fantastic test of who has a good organization. In Iowa, you have to 
have an organization on the ground to turn people out on Feb. 7.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson declined to say which candidate has the best  
organization in Iowa, saying, ``Most of the campaigns have the 
leadership horsepower to do very, very well in the caucuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Bush's prospects, Robinson said, ``There seems to be  
something about him that makes people think he's better able to 
connect with voters. People are interested in meeting him.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 17:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
