<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Border Nations Near Deal on Trucking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) -- U.S. Transportation Secretary Rodney  
Slater wrapped up a two-day border conference Thursday with a 
pledge to resolve a four-year dispute over international trucking. 
</P>
<P>
	Slater was one of several high-level officials from both  
countries who attended the U.S. Mexico Border Infrastructure 
Conference to discuss the impacts of the North America Trade 
Agreement on border communities and how to handle future growth as 
free trade continues to flourish. 
</P>
<P>
	Slater briefly met with Mexican Transportation Secretary Carlos  
Ruiz Sacristan on Thursday to discuss allowing commercial trucks 
from both countries to freely cross the border, improving the flow 
of commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	Cross-border trucking was to be permitted under the NAFTA, but  
the Clinton administration, citing safety concerns with Mexican 
vehicles, suspended that provision of the treaty in 1995 shortly 
before it was to go into effect. Trucking companies currently use 
third parties to drive goods across the international zone. 
</P>
<P>
	``The discussions are going very, very well and it is our hope  
that we will be able to move forth within a reasonable period of 
time to open up the border,'' Slater said. 
</P>
<P>
	Slater declined to speculate when an agreement would be reached,  
but said it would come before the end of the Clinton 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've made a commitment and we're trying to get it done,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Business leaders on both sides of the border have argued that  
the current rules hurt commerce and factor into the long delays at 
crossing points along the 2,000-mile U.S.-Mexico border. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goals of NAFTA will not be fully realized if goods cannot  
be transferred from buyer to seller in a safe and efficient 
manner,'' said Sam Vale of the Border Trade Alliance, an advocacy 
group participating in this week's conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Slater and Commerce Secretary William Daley attended the  
conference along with Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, California 
Gov. Gray Davis and Mexico Trade Minister Herminio Blanco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
