<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Landry Checks Out of Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Former Dallas Cowboys coach Tom Landry has been  
released from a Dallas hospital after completing the first stage of 
his treatment for leukemia. 
</P>
<P>
	The 74-year-old Landry left Baylor University Medical Center on  
Tuesday, his son, Tom Landry Jr., said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Landry will spend the next 30 days convalescing at home, his son  
told The Dallas Morning News. 
</P>
<P>
	Landry entered the hospital on May 4 after he was diagnosed with  
leukemia, a cancer that impairs the production of blood cells. He 
is scheduled to return to the hospital in a month to continue a 
90-day treatment program. 
</P>
<P>
	``Treatment has progressed as outlined by his doctors,''  
Landry's son said. ``Certainly there is more time to go and 
treatment to continue. But to date, things have gone real well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Morning News said it received about 1,700 get-well faxes  
within a five-day span last month through its web site. Those 
messages were relayed to Landry while he was in the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of my condition (isolated to avoid infection), I  
couldn't have flowers or visitors, so you can imagine how much it 
meant to me to receive so many cards, phone messages and all those 
e-mail letters,'' Landry told the newspaper from his residence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I read all of them and was really touched by everyone's  
concern and prayers,'' Landry said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 23:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Canada Reach Salmon Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- After years of bitter feuding among negotiators  
and fishermen, the United States and Canada have reached an accord 
aimed at conserving and rebuilding their shared West Coast wild 
salmon runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't easy, but after five frustrating years of  
negotiating breakdowns we finally ended the stalemate,'' Washington 
Gov. Gary Locke said Thursday of the renewed Pacific Salmon Treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations hit a low in 1997 when Canadian fishing boats  
blocked an Alaska state ferry from departing Prince Rupert, British 
Columbia, after fishermen there contended Alaskans were taking too 
many salmon. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal divides up salmon among Canadian and U.S. fishermen  
only after ensuring that enough remain to reproduce healthy and 
growing runs, especially of wild chinook, sockeye and coho salmon. 
Increasing numbers of those runs are being listed as endangered or 
threatened under the U.S. Endangered Species Act. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement gives Canada more Fraser River sockeye salmon at  
the expense of Washington and Oregon fishermen, but reduces 
Canada's catch of chinook salmon bound for Washington, Oregon and 
Idaho rivers, Locke said. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Alaska has agreed to reduce its chinook and coho  
salmon catches, backers of the agreement said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a joint statement, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and  
Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy called the accord ``a 
victory for all those on both sides of the border interested in 
salmon conservation and the long-term viability of our salmon 
industries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement requires Congress to appropriate $140 million to  
be used to restore salmon habitat and take other steps to rebuild 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. government and Washington state are expected to  
appropriate another $30 million to $35 million to buy out the 
licenses of some U.S. fishermen who will lose a big chunk of their 
customary Fraser sockeye harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement will be in effect for 10 years everywhere but  
British Columbia's Fraser River, where it will last 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Fixed harvest quotas will be replaced by an ``abundance-based''  
system. Harvest levels will decline when stocks are low and will 
rise when stocks are again plentiful. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be seeing thousands of additional wild chinook and coho  
salmon returning to rivers on Washington's coast and Puget Sound as 
well as the Columbia (River) each year as a result of this 
agreement,'' said Kelly White, chairman of the Washington state 
Fish and Wildlife Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement sets up two regional funds to be managed jointly  
by both countries to address restoration and salmon production 
enhancement. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Curtis of Trout Unlimited welcomed the agreement -- with  
reservations. 
</P>
<P>
	``From what we know about this agreement, it seems to be more  
about providing money for restoration than cutting harvests,'' 
Curtis said. ``We are worried that they are going down the road of 
trying to make more fish, rather than conserving the resource.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Provisions of the treaty, which dictate how many fish are  
allotted to U.S. and Canadian fishermen, expired in 1992 and 
negotiators have been working ever since to come up with a new 
agreement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 01:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Antigay Slur Carved on Student </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- A dispute over musical tastes drove two  
prep school students to carve an antigay slur into the back of a 
classmate, police say. 
</P>
<P>
	Jonathan Shapiro, 18 of Keene, N.H., and Matthew Rogers, 20, of  
Franklin, Tenn., are accused of using a pocket knife to cut the 
word ``HOMO'' into the back of a 17-year-old junior at Northfield 
Mount Hermon School. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Wednesday the victim was attacked because he liked  
the British rock band Queen, whose lead singer, Freddie Mercury, 
died of AIDS complications in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``Rogers called it a gay band,'' said Gill Police Chief David  
Hastings. 
</P>
<P>
	Both students pleaded innocent to charges of assault and battery  
with a dangerous weapon, assault with intent to maim, and assault 
with intent to intimidate, resulting in bodily harm. They were 
released on bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Each could get up to 25 years in prison, as well as counseling  
and diversity training, if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	The victim, whose name was not released, initially kept quiet  
about the May 27 attack. He has since returned to his family's 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastings described the wounds as ``deep enough to draw blood.''  
</P>
<P>
	``When I saw them they were three days old and they were still  
very visible,'' he said. ``The letters were 4- to 5-inches high and 
ran all the way across his back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rogers had accepted an appointment to the U.S. Naval Academy,  
according to Karen Myers, an academy spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once we are able to verify the charges we will have to  
reconsider the appointment,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
