<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tampa Bay, Florida Get Their Joshes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Tampa Bay Devil Rays and Florida Marlins  
each got the Josh they wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay selected Josh Hamilton, an outfielder from Athens  
Drive High School in Raleigh, N.C., with the first pick in 
Wednesday's draft, while Florida took Josh Beckett, a right-hander 
from Spring, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton became the first high school player drafted No. 1 since  
the Seattle Mariners chose Alex Rodriguez in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've seen him over the last three years and we believe Josh  
Hamilton was the finest player in the draft this year,'' Tampa Bay 
general manager Chuck LaMar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marlins scouting director Al Avila was pleased to get Beckett.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's the Josh we wanted,'' Avila said. ``Beckett has good  
size and has an overpowering fastball. He's a bulldog on the 
mound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beckett was the first high school righty taken as high as second  
since Bill Gullickson in 1979. He was 13-2 with an 0.39 ERA and 178 
strikeouts in 89 innings this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit selected Southern California catcher Eric Munson with  
the third pick. Arizona then unexpectedly chose shortstop Corey 
Myers of Phoenix. Minnesota chose outfielder B.J. Garbe, from Moses 
Lake, Wash., with the fifth pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton is an outstanding hitter projected to be a right  
fielder, even though he has a 94 mph fastball. He hit .514 with a 
school-record 13 homers and 36 RBIs this season, and is also 
regarded as a sound defensive player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess not going No. 1 wouldn't have totally destroyed me,''  
Hamilton said. ``But there's prestige going No. 1, and I'm 
certainly happy to be No. 1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beckett, who does not lack confidence, constantly hears the  
comparisons to fellow Texas pitchers Roger Clemens and Nolan Ryan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ain't done nothing yet,'' Beckett said. ``But I think one  
day, I'll live up to all of that. If someone told me different, I'd 
call them a liar. I think I'm going to be better than all those 
guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Munson, who will be playing in the NCAA's super regionals  
against Stanford starting Friday, is hitting .338 with 14 homers 
and 40 RBIs. The left-handed power hitter missed 21 games because 
of a broken hand midway through the season, but picked up where he 
left off. 
</P>
<P>
	Myers hit .560 and set an Arizona high school record with 22  
homers. 
</P>
<P>
	Garbe, a two-sport star, hit .500 with six homers and 22 RBIs  
this season. He was the first high school quarterback in the state 
to run and pass for over 1,000 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Montreal selected left-hander Josh Girdley from Jasper, Texas,  
with the sixth pick. Girdley struck out 29 in 10 innings earlier 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	With the seventh pick, Kansas City chose North Carolina  
right-hander Kyle Snyder. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh chose high school right-hander Bobby Bradley with the  
eighth pick. Bradley threw seven one-hitters this season in 
Wellington, Fla., and was 12-1 with an 0.38 ERA and 156 strikeouts 
in 92 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakland took Southern California left-hander Barry Zito, who had  
three 16-strikeout games this season, with the ninth pick. 
Milwaukee selected Northeast Louisiana right-hander Ben Sheets. 
Sheets, 14-1, had a 20-strikeout game against Louisiana Tech this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati Reds selected Ronald LeFlore, son of former major  
league outfielder Ron, in the sixth round. LeFlore was an 
outfielder at Pinellas Park, Fla. Montreal chose Largo, Fla., 
shortstop Cletis Boyer, son of Clete Boyer, third baseman on five 
New York Yankees World Series teams, in the seventh round. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington right-hander Jeff Heaverlo, whose father, Dave,  
pitched in the majors for seven years, was taken by Seattle with 
the 33rd pick. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Cubs, with the 26th pick, took Wichita State  
right-hander Ben Christensen, who was suspended by the Missouri 
Valley Conference for hitting Evansville's Anthony Molina in the 
head with a warmup pitch before their game April 23. 
</P>
<P>
	The pitch cut Molina over the left eye, broke his cheekbone and  
may have caused permanent damage. Before the suspension, 
Christensen was 9-1 with a 2.40 ERA for the Shockers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he regrets the whole thing happening,'' Cubs general  
manager Ed Lynch said. ``In our judgment, he's an outstanding young 
man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore, which had four first-round picks, took Clemson  
right-hander Mike Paradis with the 13th pick, left-hander Richard 
Stahl of Newton, Ga., with the 18th pick, Ball State outfielder 
Larry Bigbie with the 21st pick and Providence outfielder Keith 
Reed with the 23rd pick. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego had three first-rounders and took outfielder Vince  
Faison from Toombs County, Ga., with the 20th pick. With the 28th 
and 29th picks, the Padres took Gerik Baxter, a right-hander from 
Edmonds, Wash., and right-hander Omar Ortiz from Texas-Pan 
American. 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto signed third baseman-outfielder Alex Rios, a high school  
star in Puerto Rico, shortly after he was selected with the 19th 
pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Four teams -- Anaheim, Atlanta, Cleveland and the New York Mets --  
did not have any picks until the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami shortstop Bobby Hill, expected to be a first-rounder,  
slipped to the second as the Chicago White Sox took him with the 
66th pick. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 15:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Up 85.80 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks closed higher Thursday as  
strong sales at the nation's largest retailers reminded investors 
that economic growth isn't necessarily bad news. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 85.80 to close at  
10,663.69. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index rose 4.73 to 1,299.54, but the technology-dominated Nasdaq 
composite fell 29.09 to close at 2,403.32. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock trading has been especially volatile since May 18, when  
the Federal Reserve warned it would raise interest rates if it 
determined that inflation is creeping into the booming U.S. 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Since that warning, the market has turned on every new sign of  
inflationary pressures. Continued signs of growth -- ordinarily a 
boon to stocks -- have spooked investors who fear higher interest 
rates will cut into the profits of major U.S. corporations. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, however, investors welcomed good news from the  
nation's biggest retailers. Most reported stronger-than-expected 
sales in May, with specialty retailers and discounters leading the 
sector. Wal-Mart rose 1 1/8 to 45 1/2, and Gap Inc. gained 3 1/4 to 65 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	The market also gained support from a Commerce Department report  
that showed orders to American factories for manufactured goods 
fell 1.2 percent. The decline suggested that if the Fed does raise 
rates, the increase will be a modest quarter of a percentage point, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Madden, chief investment officer for domestic equities at  
Federated Investors of Pittsburgh, said many market players have 
begun moving money under the assumption that rates will rise. 
</P>
<P>
	``There seems to be a growing consensus that the Fed will  
tighten rates in June,'' he said. ``Maybe that is helping calm the 
market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Traders remain focused on the Friday morning release of the  
Labor Department's unemployment data. The wage component of the 
report was expected to offer a more pointed indication of whether 
inflation has returned to the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was also expected to be moved by the surprise  
resignation of Alice Rivlin, the No. 2 official at the Fed. Rivlin 
announced after the close of the market Thursday that she is 
stepping down after three years as the Fed's vice chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	The volatile Internet companies that helped the Nasdaq Stock  
Market rally Wednesday headed lower again. Amazon.com led the 
decliners, and is now worth less than half its value in late April. 
It fell 7 1/16 to 105 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, investors turned to a broad-based range of  
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sure looks like rapid sector rotation,'' said Madden. ``The  
market's tone is better, but there's no strong conviction for any 
sector.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Companies as diverse as American Express, up 2 15/16 to 121 3/8,  
Hewlett Packard, up 1 11/16 to 91 7/16, and Johnson &AMP; Johnson, up 2 
to 93 11/16, led the Dow stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevron fell 7/16 to 91 9/16 and Texaco dropped 2 3/16 to 62  
5/16 after the companies called off merger talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a perception that this might be the end of the giant  
oil merger talks,'' said Robert Stovall, president of 
Stovall/Twenty-First Advisers. ``There aren't many other potential 
partners for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Market indexes held steady after the New York Stock Exchange  
announced it will not adopt extended trading hours until at least 
2000. The board that governs the Nasdaq Stock Market expects to 
start an extended schedule as soon as September. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where consolidated volume totaled 868.80 
million shares, compared to 877.17 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 3.70 to 624.20, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 4.71 to 775.94. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.76 to 435.98.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.16 percent.  
Britain's FT-SE 100 gained 1.7 percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 
0.9 percent higher. German markets were closed for a religious 
holiday. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition Indonesia Leader Popular </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Hundreds of thousands of euphoric  
supporters of opposition leader Megawati Sukarnoputri paraded 
through Jakarta on Thursday, gridlocking the capital with one of 
the biggest rallies of Indonesia's election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Fans whooped, pounded drums and blew whistles. Horns bleated and  
engines groaned, dimming chants of ``Mega, Mega.'' Her party's 
color was everywhere -- red T-shirts, red jackets, red berets and 
red flags with the cartoonish symbol of a glaring black bull. A 
tractor-trailer rig towed a huge wood-and-canvas bull. 
</P>
<P>
	The huge turnout showed how much Megawati's fortunes have  
shifted since 1996, when the government of then-President Suharto 
engineered her ouster as the pro-reform leader of one of three 
officially approved political parties. 
</P>
<P>
	At one rally in Jakarta, which began with a band playing U.S.  
rap music, she reminded people that Suharto had tried to destroy 
her party. Suharto, like many Indonesians, uses only one name. 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati also reiterated a call for supporters to stick around  
after casting their ballots, particularly in rural areas, to stymie 
vote fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	``Make sure everyone only votes once,'' she said as a dozen  
parachutists landed in the crowd carrying large party flags. 
</P>
<P>
	With democratic change sweeping Indonesia, Megawati has emerged  
as a frontrunner ahead of Monday's parliamentary elections, 
expected to be the nation's fairest in 44 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Forty-eight parties are vying for seats in Parliament, whose  
members will help choose a president later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign officially wraps up Friday, followed by a two-day  
cooling-off period. 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati inspires adulation that owes much to the memory of her  
charismatic father, Indonesia's founding President Sukarno. He died 
in 1970 after losing his grasp on power to an ascendant Suharto, 
then an army general. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign has been largely peaceful. On Thursday night, about  
300 supporters of the People's Democratic Party protested near the 
General Election Committee headquarters, demanding the release of 
their jailed leader. Budiman Sudjatmiko was sentenced to 13 years 
in 1997 for fomenting a riot. 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested about 60 supporters of the ruling Golkar Party  
on Thursday, confiscating slingshots and arrows, after brief 
clashes with three other parties in the South Sulawesi provincial 
capital of Ujungpandang, about 900 miles northeast of Jakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Police fired warning shots to disperse Megawati supporters  
beating up two Golkar backers. 
</P>
<P>
	In the West Java town of Cirebon, dozens of people were injured  
in clashes Wednesday involving Golkar, Megawati's party and the 
Muslim-based United Development Party, the daily Kompas newspaper 
reported. Buildings, cars and motorcycles were damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	Clashes also broke out Wednesday in the Bali capital of Denpasar  
between supporters of Golkar and Megawati's Indonesian Democratic 
Party for Struggle. Several people were injured, while one car was 
burned and some houses were damaged, including the local Golkar 
leader's home. 
</P>
<P>
	In Jakarta, throngs of Megawati revelers gathered at the pool  
surrounding the Welcome Monument, a tall pedestal topped by a 
statue of a waving young man and woman in the center of the city. 
</P>
<P>
	``After 32 years of disruption and pain, I think this is the  
right time for Mega to show her power,'' said Ibeng Viki, a 
27-year-old member of Megawati's party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 06:10:31 </DATE_TIME>
