certainly happy to be No. 1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beckett, who does not lack confidence, constantly hears the  
comparisons to fellow Texas pitchers Roger Clemens and Nolan Ryan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I ain't done nothing yet,'' Beckett said. ``But I think one  
day, I'll live up to all of that. If someone told me different, I'd 
call them a liar. I think I'm going to be better than all those 
guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Munson, who will be playing in the NCAA's super regionals  
against Stanford starting Friday, is hitting .338 with 14 homers 
and 40 RBIs. The left-handed power hitter missed 21 games because 
of a broken hand midway through the season, but picked up where he 
left off. 
</P>
<P>
	Myers hit .560 and set an Arizona high school record with 22  
homers. 
</P>
<P>
	Garbe, a two-sport star, hit .500 with six homers and 22 RBIs  
this season. He was the first high school quarterback in the state 
to run and pass for over 1,000 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Montreal selected left-hander Josh Girdley from Jasper, Texas,  
with the sixth pick. Girdley struck out 29 in 10 innings earlier 
this season. 
</P>
<P>
	With the seventh pick, Kansas City chose North Carolina  
right-hander Kyle Snyder. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh chose high school right-hander Bobby Bradley with the  
eighth pick. Bradley threw seven one-hitters this season in 
Wellington, Fla., and was 12-1 with an 0.38 ERA and 156 strikeouts 
in 92 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakland took Southern California left-hander Barry Zito, who had  
three 16-strikeout games this season, with the ninth pick. 
Milwaukee selected Northeast Louisiana right-hander Ben Sheets. 
Sheets, 14-1, had a 20-strikeout game against Louisiana Tech this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cincinnati Reds selected Ronald LeFlore, son of former major  
league outfielder Ron, in the sixth round. LeFlore was an 
outfielder at Pinellas Park, Fla. Montreal chose Largo, Fla., 
shortstop Cletis Boyer, son of Clete Boyer, third baseman on five 
New York Yankees World Series teams, in the seventh round. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington right-hander Jeff Heaverlo, whose father, Dave,  
pitched in the majors for seven years, was taken by Seattle with 
the 33rd pick. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chicago Cubs, with the 26th pick, took Wichita State  
right-hander Ben Christensen, who was suspended by the Missouri 
Valley Conference for hitting Evansville's Anthony Molina in the 
head with a warmup pitch before their game April 23. 
</P>
<P>
	The pitch cut Molina over the left eye, broke his cheekbone and  
may have caused permanent damage. Before the suspension, 
Christensen was 9-1 with a 2.40 ERA for the Shockers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know he regrets the whole thing happening,'' Cubs general  
manager Ed Lynch said. ``In our judgment, he's an outstanding young 
man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baltimore, which had four first-round picks, took Clemson  
right-hander Mike Paradis with the 13th pick, left-hander Richard 
Stahl of Newton, Ga., with the 18th pick, Ball State outfielder 
Larry Bigbie with the 21st pick and Providence outfielder Keith 
Reed with the 23rd pick. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego had three first-rounders and took outfielder Vince  
Faison from Toombs County, Ga., with the 20th pick. With the 28th 
and 29th picks, the Padres took Gerik Baxter, a right-hander from 
Edmonds, Wash., and right-hander Omar Ortiz from Texas-Pan 
American. 
</P>
<P>
	Toronto signed third baseman-outfielder Alex Rios, a high school  
star in Puerto Rico, shortly after he was selected with the 19th 
pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Four teams -- Anaheim, Atlanta, Cleveland and the New York Mets --  
did not have any picks until the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami shortstop Bobby Hill, expected to be a first-rounder,  
slipped to the second as the Chicago White Sox took him with the 
66th pick. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
