<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tiny Company Takes On Microsoft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- As Microsoft Corp.'s pivotal antitrust  
trial winds down in Washington, D.C., the big software maker faced 
a second judge and jury Thursday, but the issues were similar. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft stood accused of attempting to throttle a competitor.  
</P>
<P>
	Opening statements were heard in a civil suit filed by Bristol  
Technology Inc., a tiny software company that claims that the maker 
of the Windows computer operating system is improperly withholding 
programming code that Bristol needs to survive. 
</P>
<P>
	If Microsoft loses this trial, it would erode the company's  
contention in the larger case that its business dealings, while 
aggressive, are legal. 
</P>
<P>
	As the trial opened in U.S. District Court, a lawyer for Bristol  
told the 10-member jury that Microsoft used Bristol as a business 
partner to move into the large corporate computing market, then 
reneged on its promise to continue to supply Bristol with 
technology it needs to make its main software product. 
</P>
<P>
	But a lawyer for Microsoft told the jury that Bristol's lawsuit  
is nothing more than an attempt by Bristol to force more favorable 
business arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	In the larger antitrust case in Washington -- brought by the  
Justice Department and 19 states -- the government contends that 
Microsoft illegally wielded monopoly power from its dominant 
Windows product to expand into new markets, such as Internet 
software, and thus crush competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol makes a product called Wind/U, which allows programs,  
such as word processors and spreadsheets, written to work with 
Windows to be converted to run on computers with different 
operating systems such as Unix. Operating systems are the central 
nervous system of computers. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Microsoft signed a three-year contract with Bristol  
giving the company access to software blueprints for Windows NT 
3.0, a version of its operating system designed to work with 
powerful corporate computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Those blueprints allowed Bristol to make Wind/U, but the  
agreement expired in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol filed its lawsuit after the two companies could not  
reach a new agreement for access to the blueprints for the newer 
versions of Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	In opening arguments, Bristol attorney Patrick Lynch told the  
jury that Microsoft first approached Bristol in 1992 about working 
together. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch said Bristol executives were wary about becoming  
Microsoft's partner, because they realized they would be dependent 
on the Microsoft software blueprints, known as the ``source code.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``They knew that when an elephant asks a mouse to dance, it's a  
mouse that's in danger, not the elephant,'' Lynch said. But he said 
Bristol agreed to the deal after Microsoft made public statements 
indicating support for allowing programs to work on multiple 
operating systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynch said that when Bristol went to Microsoft and asked for a  
new contract, Microsoft offered only limited access to Windows 
source code. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft attorney David Tulchin told the jury that Bristol  
hired a public relations firm and attorneys months before it filed 
its lawsuit, while it claimed to be negotiating a new contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bristol chose litigation instead of negotiation,'' Tulchin  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Bristol rejected the new contract because Microsoft  
wanted more money. But he said Microsoft was able to negotiate a 
contract with similar terms with Mainsoft, Bristol's main 
competitor. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol called one of its founders, Ken Blackwell, as its first  
witness. 
</P>
<P>
	Blackwell, Bristol's chief technical officer, testified that  
Microsoft executives repeatedly said they were committed to 
providing Microsoft source code for future versions of Windows NT, 
beyond the three-year contract it had signed with Bristol. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Janet Hall told the jury that in order to  
find in favor of Bristol, that company must prove that Microsoft 
has monopoly power or a probability of obtaining monopoly power, 
and that it was willfully obtained by anti-competitive conduct. 
Microsoft has denied it is a monopoly. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial is expected to last six to eight weeks. On Friday,  
Bristol is expected to play a videotaped deposition from Microsoft 
Chairman Bill Gates. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
