<HEADLINE> Pats Look To Buy Property for Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- The New England Patriots' plan to build a  
$225 million megaplex had better include $2 million if the team 
wants to buy Norman Lawton's little piece of land next to the 
current stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	That's what Lawton says, anyway. He's lived on the property,  
which his family has owned since 1720, for 70 of his 80 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got some flowers and then some. It's a pretty little  
location and I'm used to being able to hit the driveway at night,'' 
the retired chicken geneticist said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	After years of frustrating negotiations to build a stadium, the  
Patriots are moving quickly since the May 24 signing ceremony in 
which Gov. Paul Cellucci signed a bill giving $70 million in state 
money for the project. 
</P>
<P>
	Gil Campos, a real estate agent with RE-MAX Real Estate Center,  
said the Patriots asked him last week to visit Lawton and others on 
North Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was taking the temperature to see who was interested and who  
wasn't,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots have four options for relieving traffic around the  
stadium, which would involve buying one to five homes nearby, 
Campos said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're trying to make it as least impactive as possible,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But, said Campos, ``most people have said they'd prefer,  
obviously, not to move.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
