<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Gets Top On-Time Ranking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- For the first time since September  
1996, Northwest Airlines has earned a No. 1 ranking in monthly 
on-time performance among the nation's seven biggest carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	But the carrier also drew the highest rate of consumer  
complaints for April, according to the Transportation Department's 
Air Travel Consumer Report issued Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest's on-time performance for April was 80.6 percent,  
slightly ahead of TWA at 80.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest drew 2.71 consumer complaints for every 100,000  
passenger boardings. That compared with 1.39 complaints per 100,000 
passenger boardings at Continental Airlines, Northwest's domestic 
alliance partner. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest's consumer complaints for the month were only slightly  
worse than those at American Airlines and US Airways. 
</P>
<P>
	For two consecutive quarters in the middle of last year,  
Northwest ranked last among the nation's 10 largest carriers in 
on-time performance. The ratings coincided with a work slowdown by 
mechanics and other ground workers who were disgruntled by 
drawn-out contract negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest still hasn't settled contracts with its flight  
attendants and mechanics. The results of a strike authorization 
vote by flight attendants will be announced Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal is to promptly and expeditiously conclude those  
contracts on fair and equitable terms,'' said Richard Anderson, 
Northwest executive vice president and chief operating officer. ``I 
think we're anxious to have the flight attendant contract done.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
