<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 05:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cathay Cancels Many of Its Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Cathay Pacific Airways canceled nearly half its  
flights on Thursday, but hired more charter services to try to keep 
passengers moving as a sickout by pilots entered its seventh day 
with no end in sight. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay bosses said they expected to ground 56 of the company's  
117 scheduled flights, though they were bringing in help from other 
airlines who have been hired to fly 27 services Thursday as a pay 
dispute with cabin crew continues. 
</P>
<P>
	The sickout has brought chaos to Hong Kong's Chek Lap Kok  
airport, where Cathay is by far the biggest carrier. More than 
20,000 travelers have been inconvenienced, and some have waited for 
days trying to get out of town. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay angered the pilots by demanding pay cuts averaging 8  
percent in exchange for stock options to help cut costs. The 
situation deteriorated last week when the company gave the pilots 
until June 11 to either take its offer or lose their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Pilots began phoning in sick, saying the layoff threats had left  
them too stressed-out to fly. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots say they will call a strike vote if anybody is fired  
in the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay says it needs to cut costs after losing millions as a  
result of the Asian economic crisis and Hong Kong's recession. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 10:05:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Another Good Month for Retailers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Americans' shopping spree extended into May,  
boosting sales at the nation's biggest retailers to 
better-than-expected levels for the fourth straight month. 
</P>
<P>
	The continued strength of the U.S. economy combined with warmer  
weather through much of the country encouraged consumers to do lots 
of buying in May -- from sundresses to patio furniture to beach 
towels. 
</P>
<P>
	``The numbers for May are extremely strong and that's because  
the consumer is very confident about their current economic 
situation and the outlook for the coming months,'' said Kurt 
Barnard, who heads the retail consulting firm Barnard's Retail 
Trend Report. 
</P>
<P>
	The robust U.S. economy, as well as low unemployment and  
inflation levels have made consumers confident about their personal 
finances and has raised their eagerness to spend. 
</P>
<P>
	And their spending didn't slow last month even with the extreme  
volatility on Wall Street. The Dow Jones industrial average surged 
to a record high of 11,107.19 on May 13, but then fell by about 5 
percent by the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no doubt that the vibrant and value-conscious American  
consumer is still very much alive,'' said Jeffrey Feiner, managing 
director at Lehman Brothers Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The big winners in May were specialty clothing chains, while  
department stores also fared well. Discounters were strong, as 
shoppers turned to stores like Wal-Mart and Target for their wide 
selection and affordable prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The strength in sales came despite being compared with the very  
strong performance of May 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	However, some merchants -- including Kmart and J.C. Penney -- were  
hurt by the late Memorial Day this year. Most retailers ended their 
fiscal month of May on the 28th or 29th, which meant that much of 
the buying over the holiday weekend will be included in June's 
sales figures. Memorial Day was observed on May 31 this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Merrill Lynch retail index, the investment firm's barometer  
of sales performance at department stores and discount chains, was 
up 4.8 percent in May. It rose 6.4 percent in May 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, reported sales from  
stores open at least a year rose 7.7 percent from a year earlier, 
while total sales were up 14.3 percent. Sales from stores open at 
least a year, known as same-store sales, are considered the most 
accurate measure of a retailer's strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Other retailers' reports:  
</P>
<P>
	--Sears: Same-store sales up 1.9 percent, total sales down 2.8  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Kmart: Same-store sales up 3.7 percent, total sales up 5.6  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--J.C. Penney: Same-store department store sales up 2.2 percent,  
same-store sales at Eckerd drugstores rose 13.4 percent, total 
sales rose 9.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Dayton Hudson: Same-store sales up 6.3 percent, total sales up  
10.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Federated: Same-store sales rose 4.1 percent, total sales up  
14.9 percent. Federated's total sales included revenues from the 
Internet and catalog seller Fingerhut, which it acquired in March. 
</P>
<P>
	--May Department Stores: Same-store sales up 2.9 percent, total  
sales up 7.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Limited: Same-store sales up 10 percent, total sales up 8  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Gap: Same-store sales up 8 percent, total sales up 28 percent.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990603.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-03 16:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Mutual Fund Assets Rise / Money Market Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Assets of the nation's retail money market  
mutual funds increased by $837.7 million to $860.57 billion , the 
Investment Company Institute said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of taxable money market funds in the retail category  
decreased by $84.5 million to $713.81 billion for the week ended 
Wednesday, the Washington-based mutual fund trade group said. 
Tax-exempt fund assets increased by $922.2 million to $146.76 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets of institutional money market funds increased by $4.30  
billion to $594.76 billion for the same period. Among institutional 
funds, taxable money market fund assets increased by $3.24 billion 
to $544.50 billion; assets of tax-exempt funds increased by $1.06 
billion to $50.26 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Total money market assets stood at $1.455 trillion for the week.  
</P>
<P>
	Assets for the previous week were revised to $1.450 trillion to  
reflect reporting errors and a change in the number of funds 
reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in  
the week ended Tuesday to 4.32 percent from 4.27 percent the 
previous week, said IBC's Money Fund Report, a trade journal 
published in Ashland, Mass., by IBC Financial Data Inc. The 30-day 
average yield held steady at 4.29 percent from the previous week, 
IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The seven-day compounded yield rose to 4.42 percent from 4.36  
percent the previous week, and the 30-day compounded yield was 
unchanged at 4.39 percent, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was  
59 days, down from 60 days, IBC Financial Data said. 
</P>
<P>
	The online service bankrate.com said its survey of 100 leading  
commercial banks, savings and loan associations and savings banks 
in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the annual percentage 
yield available on money market accounts remained unchanged from 
the previous week at 2.06 percent as of Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based unit of Intelligent Life Corp.  
said the annual percentage yield available on interest-bearing 
checking accounts also was unchanged from the previous week at 0.91 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Bankrate.com said the annual percentage yield was 4.13 percent  
on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 4.12 percent the 
previous week. Yields were 4.42 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 4.39 
percent; 4.56 percent on 2 1/2-year CDs, up from 4.51 percent; and 
4.73 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 4.68 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
