<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minnesota School To Repay Fed Grant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The University of Minnesota will repay  
$11,000 in grant money that a school researcher used to buy and 
study cocaine that killed him. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Keith Kajander died April 28 from a cocaine overdose while  
conducting a study on pain research that involved cocaine and other 
controlled substances. 
</P>
<P>
	Kajander ordered 140 grams of cocaine hydrochloride in 28  
shipments from April 1992 to April 1999, according to a university 
audit. He held a valid federal license from the Drug Enforcement 
Administration to research the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	School officials will repay the National Institutes of Health  
$11,000 for the grant money Kajander spent on cocaine. University 
officials were unable to determine how much of the cocaine Kajander 
used for himself. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
