<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tax Cut Linked to Insurance Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It may amount to just a few dollars a month,  
but millions of Americans are getting an income tax cut this year 
because of a change in how the federal government values group life 
insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	``The net effect for workers is a reduction in the taxes they  
pay for the benefit,'' said Carroll Campbell, president of the 
American Council of Life Insurance, which represents 500 companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulations released Thursday, which take effect July 1, are  
based on updated mortality estimates showing that people are living 
longer and that women now make up roughly half the U.S. work force. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internal Revenue Service considers group life insurance a  
benefit to the worker that is taxable like regular income, with the 
first $50,000 in coverage exempt. The income shows up each year on 
W-2 forms under code ``C.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom line of the change: An estimated 163 million workers  
with group term life insurance provided by employers will see cuts 
of 11 percent to 52 percent on the taxable income derived from that 
coverage, depending on a person's age. 
</P>
<P>
	It is difficult to show how the change will lower the amount  
someone might owe Uncle Sam, given the many variables in an 
individual's tax picture. But here are two examples of how it will 
reduce taxable income: 
</P>
<P>
	--Under current regulations, a 45-year-old worker who has  
$100,000 in death benefit protection pays taxes on $174 in annual 
income from that insurance policy. The new rules will cut that 
taxable income to $90, a reduction of 48 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--A 55-year-old with $200,000 in group coverage will see taxable  
income for that policy reduced from $1,350 to $774, a cut of 43 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Total death benefit coverage by group term life insurance  
provided by employers is estimated by ACLI at about $6.2 trillion. 
Typically, employees get coverage worth at least twice their annual 
salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	While sales of individual policies have been dropping, group  
coverage sales grew 6.5 percent in 1997 compared with the year 
before. They have become one of the most popular benefits offered 
by companies because of relatively low costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The table the IRS now uses to figure the value of the insurance  
to an individual is rooted in mortality estimates of the 1970s. In 
the early 1990s, the life insurance companies began a campaign to 
modernize the table as it became clear that societal and 
demographic changes were lowering the costs of coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies knew the government calculations weren't fair,  
said Laurie Lewis, senior counsel for federal taxes at ACLI. 
``There aren't many times when government lowers taxes just because 
it's the right thing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After years of study, the Treasury Department and IRS developed  
a new table to reflect today's longer life expectancy, which is 
about 2.5 years longer than 20 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The new table also raised the ratio of women in the work force  
from 15 percent to 50 percent. Because women live longer on average 
than men, that was an additional factor in the longer life 
expectancy estimate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
